Charismatic & hawt. Good lecture style
rating_tags: Get ready to read--ACCESSIBLE OUTSIDE CLASS--Amazing lectures

comment: Amazingly well-informed. Guy's a walking neuro (and other subjects too) encyclopedia. Ask him anything and he'll respond. Slightly snarky, but nice.
Hendry is kind, hilarious, and redefines knowing his stuff. He will explain until you understand, and his lectures are the best I've had at Hopkins so far. Highly recommend his class.

Do yourself a favor and take one of his courses. You learn so much more than just the subject material. He cares about how his students do, he is incredibly easy to talk to and is the one of the best lecturers at Hopkins. I took 4 courses with this man and have turned out for the better.
You HAVE to keep up with the material. It is hard, but doable if you are passionate about the Nervous System.

Dr. Hendry is a great professor. He cares for his students and ensures that you understand the material before you leave his office any way how. He is also really fun to talk to outside of neuroscience, so that it seems like you are talking to a person rather than an intimidating professor. Great guy, great knowledge, can't wait for second semester

Hendry is an amazing professor. Its nice to have a professor who is so passionate about teaching. One time I ran into him and he was really bouncy. I asked him why he was so excited and he said that he just gave his favorite lecture in his Visual System course. --- passion
Really interesting teacher. Funny guy who takes pride in his work. Not easy but fair. His course led me to consider neuro as a major.

Hendry is a brilliant person, effective teacher, and a good guy. It bothers me a lot to hear people ever say anything to the contrary, because I have not had a professor who takes as much of an interest in the success of their students. Work hard in his classes, go talk to him once in a while, and it will pay off.
easily the best professor at hopkins
Hendry is awesome. His class is interesting and he's incredibly helpful. It doesn't hurt that his TAs are amazing...smart and good-looking!
Great teacher! Very helpful and all around awesome. He can be a but mean, but only to those who deserve it.

He is the best teacher on campus by far.  He truly cares about the students and wants to see them succeed.  Go talk to him if you have questions because he enjoys helping clarify things.  If you haven't taken a class with him by the time you graduate, you really missed out.

Dr. Hendry is not only the best and most knowledgeable professor at Hopkins, but he is one of the kindest and most helpful teachers I have ever had. The notion that he favors girls over boys is absolutely ludicrous. If you attend this school without having taken one of his classes, you are really missing out.
Greatest thing since sliced bread. difficult class though

One of the best professors on campus. His lectures are very intriguing and funny at times but there is one major drawback: if you are a girl, then he will be the best thing that has happened to you since coming to Hopkins; however, if you are a guy and piss him off, then god help you.

Though I can see why he may come off as arrogant to some people, it's because he really just does know everything- but is extremely easy to talk to.He went very slowly through the material with me when I felt like I understood nothing, and after doing poorly in the prereq to this class, ended with an A here. Probably one of the best professors here

This prof is knowledgable and teaches fairly well. but he is arrogant, ****ous to pretty girls, somehow makes sure they're getting better grades and pts back on exams (please understand this is NOT anecdotal). Ask him a question during an exam, or ever, & he looks at you as if you're committing a crime. His notes are very often confusing/unclear.
My biggest word of advice in this class: go to office hours and in exams use AS FEW WORDS AS POSSIBLE. Seriously, if you write a novel you WILL get a bad grade. The less you write the better.
Hero of an instructor. A true "good" person.

Hendry is extremely helpful during and outside of class. The notes for neuro are absolutely awesome, although he does make quite a few typos. It's much better than having a textbook though. Genius that he can write his own class notes in a clear manner.

If you are into biomedical sciences you will enjoy Hendry's classes. Personally I was very interested by the content of the lectures and I liked the fact that the grade is based solely on exam performance. Outside the class he is very helpful and willing to discuss issues in neuroscience, which are not mentioned in his lectures.

Great Professor! Extremely helpful. I've heard he treats girls better, but not sure how true that is. I'm so glad he's my advisor! He's given me such good advice from studying for his exams to applying to medical school.

BEST Prof. EVERRR..... he's really great and funny during his lectures, but if you miss them you'll have a hard time understanding the subject. The tests are relatively easy, but make sure to take notes during class and never go to the bathroom he always says something important.

Best professor I've had. Makes lectures fun and interesting. Writes his own notes so easy to follow up after class. Clarified so many points about neuroscience. Ultimately made me decide to be neuro major and pre-med

Great professor teaching wise, kinda arrogant sometimes (considers some questions stupid and not worth asking). Does seem to prefer girls and acts nicer to them, whereas may act more hostile to guys. May be just this year tho. Overall, very clear in teaching, but I'd rather hold my judgement on his personality.

Most helpful and gifted professor at JHU.  Also a great advisor, helped me understand the brain and get into medical school with little stress and lots of fun.  Don't miss the opportunity to take his class.  Seriously.

I agree that Hendry is a great lecturer and is very helpful outside of class as well. The downside to him is that he can be pretty rude if you ask a question he considers stupid. The grading in this class is also very inconsistent, sometimes curved, sometimes not. Also, if you don't do well on the final you are pretty much screwed.
BEST professor ever! The nervous system is a relatively hard class but he makes it crystal clear. I liked the subject before hand and now I love it even more. I will take any classes he offers!

Dr. Hendry lectures like a pro and truly cares about his students.  Sometimes he cares so much that he really gets personally offended if his class does not do well on an exam.  Overall, he is conceivably the best professor I have had thus far at JHU.  I RECOMMEND!
Great teacher. Very clear in lecture and helps out the class by posting notes online. Made a difficult topic (Systems Neuroscience) seem easy.

Hendry's a REALLY good lecturer and superb at explaining difficult concepts. Unfortunately, he talks so quickly that it was difficult to take adequate notes. His online notes (we didn't use a textbook) were helpful, but he posted some the night before the final so it was difficult to study. Overall, he's a great prof.
very good professor, extremely approachable for questions, easily available by email. Online lecture notes very helpful for exams
He is my favorite professor! He's really funny and very good at explaining confusing topics.
No Comments
Dead sexy!

I am a math major, so I know who is a good math teacher and what it takes to teach a good math course. Zucker has no idea what he's doing. He's useless in classs. If you must take his course, buy whatever textbook he's using and rely solely on that. Anything that you 'learn' from Zucker will actually detract from your understanding of the material

Worst professor ever. He doesn't feel the need to teach, his lectures are composed of nonsensical mumblings and imcomprehensible 'non-sequitur' style structure, and he is impossible to deal with on a personal level. He is self-absorbed, clearly (and openly) despises his students and teaching, and offers absolutely no help to students.
Lin Alg is a very theoretical subject, and Zucker is the worst guy to be teaching it... He's absolutely useless

Lectures are slow, unclear, hard to follow, and unorganized. He insists on getting sidetracked and making small, unfunny jokes.  Also spends the first two classes arguing why everything's the students' fault. Changed homework 5 days after assigning it, and then changes the due date to the next class, rather than a couple days later. Avoid.
Plan to read the textbook alot, and dont bother going to his class, cuz you wont understand his mumbles or handwriting.
God awful.  Avoid at all costs.
He babbles on about nothing every lecture, and it's not even worth it to go, which is fine if you enjoy freeing up an hour of your day.

WORST TEACHER IN HISTORY. hates his students, does nothing to help them, and his lectures are painful. talks about unrelated topics, makes fun of students, and seems to resent teaching. i retook this class for a better grade after having him and got an A easily because the qualilty of the teacher was 100% better, which goes to show he is the worst

I HATE THIS GUY!!! His lectures are horrible! He complains about how students these days are not what they used to be. This guy does not care about teaching whatsoever. He is really weird and his jokes are NEVER funny, even though the front row kids always laugh at them...AVOID AT ALL COSTS! Found out I got him again and I dropped his class...
one of the worst professors ever. he made all his lectures so awkward that many students would grimace in horror. get out before it is too late.

Terrible instructor. Going to class was actively detrimental to my understanding of the material. Instructor is also obsessed with proving that he is an excellent teacher, often by quoting the few students from years past who enjoyed his company.

It's not the fact that he blabs about stuff loosely related to math during lectures and assigns homework that has pretty much nothing to do with whats going on that pisses me off. Rather, its that while doing all this, he says, with a smile, that he intended to do so all along, and sees no reason why he actually has to teach.
Very Very bad. Some people should not pro-create; he is definitely one of them.
Horrible teacher.  On the first day he hands out a sheet explaining his philosophy that he shouldn't teach anything.  Everything he does is to serve his own ego and prove to himself that he is smart.
The worst class I have ever taken. Avoid this guy at   all costs.
well worth the price of admission
Boo.
The man is a comic genius.  And he has incredible style.
unclear lecturer who is unwilling to help students. made me drop my major, taking this class was so bad.
The most unapprochable person at hopkins.  Very strange guy with a weird sense of humor.  Unfairly treats his class and didn't teach.
The only thing that he wants to do is sit in his office and do research he has no intention to teach anything, unless of course you are asian, but otherwise you're screwed

Does not teach. Basically likes to brag about how mean he is. Homework is 2-3 times the length of the homework I've had in any other math course since then, including the 400-level courses. His explanations do not clarify anything.
was so bad.  no personality, unapproachable.  A very strange guy.
his jokes are not funny. he strongly believes students should learn by themselves instead of from lectures. poor clarity.
Horrible, biased towards asians, unclear lectrures

Worst professor. Instead of trying to teach you well, he devotes classtime to enumerating reasons why he thinks he does not have to teach you. His communication skills are appalling, his tests badly worded, his handwriting illegible, he mumbles.
Zucker is incredibly difficult, not easy to understand, and hard to deal with. Good luck.
i despise his teaching style
Queer professor, horrible lecturer, makes tests difficult for his own pleasure

Quite a strange human being actually.  Impossible to communicate with and easily the worst lecturer I've had... That being said, he was organized enough and the exams were possible if you can learn from the book.  Just don't expect to be taught anything.
terrible lectures, didn't learn a single thing in class. unhelpful enough that I eventually stopped going, if you have him you'll have to depend on your TA and math help.

Good for nothing lectures.  Basis his entire style of teaching off of the opinions of 3 or 4 students  who say it works.  He believes firmly in letting students learn for themselves.   Which translates into not actually teaching any subject mattter.
Who's worse? Zucker or Howald?
Has no communication skills whatsoever

Worst professor ever!  I had to get permission to get a tutor for the class, once I learned that he clearly was not going to teach me anything, and when i asked him he said "no, you dont need one."  well i failed the class, so i guess i sure sho
Great Prof...
the reason he's so hard is because he doesn't teach, which (incidentally) he states in his teaching philosophy... if you're the self-taught type, get ready. multivariable isn't that easy alone.
Taking his course was a life changing experience.  Hard as hell, but worth it!
Actually a nice guy in person, horrible lecturer, barely got a C-
No Comments
i'll make an exam that none of you will get a single point on.
His ego can barely fit through the door.  Calls class stupid.

The tests are very similar to the backtests, so with the PILOT + OCI office hours, you have a solid chance of getting an A. Lectures don't directly align with the test content, making attendance less crucial, though they may be mandatory for iClicker participation. The class has a textbook, but it's not particularly essential for studying.

Professor Falzone really struggles to contain his passion for Organic Chemistry, not being able to simplify complex topics. His lectures aren't very helpful, but he offers plenty of practice and previous exams to self-study. He is a great guy, but not an amazing teacher. Back tests are exactly like the exam.

80%< guarantees an A- or higher & he gives A BUNCH of reliable backtests. He's not a good lecturer, so this class is easier if you go off the textbook. There's no homework, so your grade depends on 3 exams and one final, however, he gives generous partial credit & you can replace your lowest exam score with the first 100 points of your final exam.
rating_tags: Clear grading criteria--Test heavy--Graded by few things

comment: If you're a self-studier or have prior O-chem knowledge, take Falzone. i am not either so i struggled in the beginning. His lectures are absolutely useless so you'll teach yourself everything using the textbook. Backtests r only reason i pass. TAs werent very helpful. if u get a 100/125 or higher on final, ur lowest exam will turn into a 100
rating_tags: Clear grading criteria--Test heavy--Graded by few things

comment: Dr. Falzone is caring and he's always trying his best to help more people get an A by sometimes lowering the grade line or offering extra iclicker opportunities. His tests are fair, not too hard, and there's always back tests to review. Grades are mostly based on tests and quizzes and there's no homework.
rating_tags: Get ready to read--Caring--Graded by few things

comment: Falzone is a great professor. His orgo is one of the easiest courses I've taken at Hopkins, and is a very enjoyable and interesting course. Grade bounds are generous, exams are very reasonable and lots of study resources are provided. Lectures are great, as long as you read the textbook beforehand -- you can tell that Falzone knows his stuff.
rating_tags: Get ready to read--Clear grading criteria--Respected

comment: Professor Falzone made getting a flat A, 80%, in Orgo II very doable. I personally did not have to try as hard as I had to in Orgo I. As long as you do his backtests, go through his slides, and ask questions if you are confused you will do well. He is a better professor for those who like to learn on their own, because his lectures are not the best
rating_tags: Clear grading criteria--Test heavy--Accessible outside class

comment: Freshman taking orgo, had him for I and II. Very straightforward exams, and while the lectures weren't the best, crash course, PILOT, and backtests are all you really need. Went to almost every class for Orgo I and probably went to 5% of them for Orgo II and got an even higher overall percentage second semester. Makes an 80% a flat A, very doable.
rating_tags: Clear grading criteria--Graded by few things

comment: I had Professor Falzone for Orgo 1 and chose not to take him again for Orgo 2. Students that should take Falzone, are the "self-studiers" type, this is because you will have to learn majority of your Orgo knowledge outside of his lectures. Now, his exams are very similar to the backtest, so you can pass the course despite his inability to teach.

Dr. Falzone is a kind, enthusiastic professor who gives challenging yet fair exams. A funny, engaging lecturer who may veer off the topic at hand, but more than makes up for it with generous grade boundaries and several backtests. Make sure you study them! Some questions tend to repeat year after year. Falzone truly cares about the students
Chris Falzone is simply a god amongst men. Look upon his works, ye mighty, and despair!

Very bad lecturer. Better off getting explanations at his office hours. TAs won't help you. He offers a generous grade line and offers extra credit quizzes from time to time. The exams are really similar to the backtests so best bet is to study those first before exams.
rating_tags: Accessible outside class--Graded by few things--EXTRA CREDIT

comment: While I think that Dr. Falzone has a very generous curve, I did not find his lectures helpful. The lectures were sometimes very hard to follow and he tends to go off topic and rush through the actual material. Be prepared to teach yourself using the textbook because Dr. Falzone tends to assume that you already know the information.
rating_tags: Accessible outside class--Get ready to read--Clear grading criteria

comment: Going into Orgo as a freshman was terrifying, yet it's now my easiest class. Falzone's grading makes an 80 and A, and you'll likely do better than that. He drops 3/8 quizzes, replaces lowest midterm with final if that helps, gives extra credit and has tons of backtests. Your grade will be reflective of how well you understand orgo, with wiggle room
rating_tags: Get ready to read--Clear grading criteria--EXTRA CREDIT

comment: Took him for orgo I over the summer. Super fun guy and his lectures keep you engaged, but make sure to read the textbook for his exams and final. Honestly, he could keep up his happy quirkiness despite the class's dismal enthusiasm.
I had him for freshman ochem section. His tests are very doable and he gives you chances to improve your grade. Only annoying thing was his nearly weekly quizzes.
rating_tags: Get ready to read--Clear grading criteria--Hilarious

comment: Falzone might not be the best lecturer, but his tests are FAIR. No unexpected twists or turns, if you read the textbook and work hard for class, you'll pass with an A! Your lowest midterm score is dropped, that made me go from a C to an A. Bless this man. He has a sense of humor and you really learn to love him.
rating_tags: Skip class? You won't pass.--Clear grading criteria

comment: Very personable guy and a good lecturer. He goes over everything you need to know - maybe not super clearly, but all slides are posted online. Office hours are great too, he really cares about the students and the class.
One of the best professors at Hopkins, really cares about his students.
Falzone teaches the freshman section of orgo. The tests were really fair and a majority of the class got an A. If you take this class, plan on doing PILOT too, since he collaborates with it.

Pretty friendly guy, but not a great lecturer. Especially when it comes to NMR- he speaks on a level that his students aren't yet equipped to understand. It's not hard to do well in the class if you work hard, however. His tests are consistent and he gives tons of practice. The course is pretty interesting too.
Great professor, always eager to answer students' questions. Occasionally cracks jokes. Interesting character.

First, Prof. Falzone is a great guy. He does want his students to be successful.  You only need to get an 80 to get an A. He doesn't  want hostile competition. Instead, he wants people to actually get the course material. However, on the other hand, he is not a clear lecturer. We had a substitute and most people think he is better at explaining.
rating_tags: Get ready to read--Skip class? You won't pass.--LECTURE HEAVY

comment: He is a great lecturer and a great person in general.  He knows the material well and makes it very clear what you need to know.  He is also super accessible and if he knows you're genuinely trying, he will take a personal interest in your success.
Falzone is an amazing Professor who is ridiculously fair and an amazing lecturer, if you take orgo at hopkins, try to get him or Greenberg

Remember to write every reaction he puts on the board and understand them thoroughly. Office hours are essential. He notices when you try and will always be there for you.  Don't take too many courses along with this class. Scores around the high 70s to 80s are usually in the A range. Try your best and you'll reap the reward.

Organic chemistry is a tough concept, there's no getting around it. That being said, Falzone's class emphasizes independent studying. Pre-read the material before lecture, or be prepared to sit through class not knowing what's going on. Falzone assumes you've read.

He obviously knows the material very well and has a very good grasp on it, however, he is not as good in transferring this knowledge to his students clearly. I found practicing and studying myself much helpful than lectures. He's really helpful and Office hours are VERY helpful. He uses clickers so attending class gives you a few additional points.

Intelligent guy. Thinks deep. Exams can be tough, typical average is between 60-70. His office hours help a lot and he has plenty of respurces in his website. It can be quite intimidating to ask questions, but he's a really nice guy who sincerely cares for his students.

Falzone is definitely a very smart individual, but he's not the best teacher. He flies through chapters of the textbook within minutes, and goes through examples very quickly. In fact, if you don't read the textbook before class, odds are you'll be behind. He's not the best at office hours either, and can be very condescending. I don't recommend.
Don't take his class. he is not a good lecturer at all. he tries to be funny but he's not. Take Klein over the summer

Falzone makes an effort to have everyone know what's going on. He understands that everyone wants to do well and adjusts his class accordingly. There are sometimes where he is a little confusing, but if you go in and ask questions when you just think you don't understand, then you'll be good.
Helpful and approachable. His office hours are really useful, definitely attend them. His TA's are also excellent, but make sure you read before you go to lecture or you may get lost.
Cares about students and is very helpful, but be warned: you must read the book before going to class. Do NOT expect to be spoonfed the material.
Great professor, cares about his students. Very approachable. Warning: students need to take the initiative.

Falzone really wants his students to learn a lot and do well. He is very approachable and quick to respond to emails. Make sure you know how to do every single problem on the old exams, and read the book before class to do well. If you work more than an hour or two a week, you'll get an A easily.

His exams are very difficult with hardly any partial credit. Instead of making orgo more simple during lecture, he tends to make it more complicated and tends to mumble his important points and go on to the next slide. He assumes certain points are obvious to students when they aren't.

I don't know what everyone is talking about, saying he's a great professor. He always assumes that you know things that you may not, so some days it's like he's telling a story from the middle and you don't know what's going on until you can get home and read the book. He mumbles some pretty important points as well. Overall not very clear.
great
A righteous dude. Very approachable and interested in the students' progress. Make flashcards. can make tricky exam questions though...

Great prof. Very approachable, concerned about students-wants class to do well. has grade boosters (if you go to class (CPS pts) and pay attention, conference quizzes are easy). Also he provides A LOT of online material (tutorials, powerpoints, outside references, past and practice exams, advice on taking tests, class summaries) to help you learn.
If you go to his class and pay attention, you will do fine. Make sure you also look for a good TA though. That could make a big difference.
Falzone is a great teacher to have for Organic Chemistry.  The class is hard but he teaches it well and really looks out for you as his student even if he doesn't know your name.
Falzone is a great teacher to have for Organic Chemistry.  The class is hard but he teaches it well and really looks out for you as his student even if he doesn't know your name.

Pretty good teacher.  Nice guy to go to if you have questions.  Very approachable.  He really wants everyone to do well but you have to put in the work.  Exams are tough.  Read ahead of time and do lots of practice problems.  Also, don't skip lectures.

There are two papers, which are easy to do well on and 4 exams. The exams are difficult to do really well on, and I got ~90% on them. Attendance is optional and lectures are recorded. Not the most interesting class, but it was pretty easy.
rating_tags: Tough grader--Test heavy--Graded by few things

comment: Professor Drigotas is an amazing lecturer. Some of the material might be confusing at times, but with some review, it is quite easy to grasp. There is no homework, but there are two papers you have to do. They are very easy, and quite fun and interesting. The exams aren't difficult. Absolutely loved Social Psychology and would take again!

Lectures are often droning and full of tangents that go on for 10-20 minutes at a time. Tests are based entirely on lecture material (no textbook!) and are usually made up of short essay questions-- so if you don't know a term, you're screwed. Attendance is optional, and lectures are recorded.
no busy work; engaging and interesting lecturer
Tests very vague and confusing. Do not take social psych with him.
Tests are very unfair.
rating_tags: Skip class? You won't pass.--Test heavy--Tough grader

comment: This professor was horrible. Tests very specific to personal anecdotes told in class. Do not test your general understanding of the information but what he wants you to know about his life. DO NOT TAKE ANY CLASS WITH THIS PROFESSOR. you will not get anything near an A.
rating_tags: Skip class? You won't pass.--Test heavy--Lecture heavy

comment: Dr. Drigotas is a nice man and an ok professor, but his tests are ridiculous! His multiple choice questions cover the most minuscule details of the lecture and his essays are impossible to answer for full credit. There is no clear rubrik which leaves them up to his own subjective (and often overly critical) interpretation. DO ALL EXTRA CREDIT.
You need the backtest answers in order to pass this class. Questions are worded very strangely and his lecture style leaves you confused about what information to study.
rating_tags: Skip class? You won't pass.--GRADED BY FEW THINGS--LECTURE HEAVY

comment: Great professor that makes class rather enjoyable. Drigotas consistently relates key terms to his personal experiences as well as specific case studies, which further enhances one's understanding of the material.  However, it is essential to write down every word that he says or else tests will be extremely difficult. No need to buy the textbook.

I took intro to Psych with Drigotas. His lectures where interesting and there was no homework. The tests were all multiple choice, but weirdly worded. Back tests will SAVE you. Not very helpful if you go to him with concerns about your grade. The class was easy if you managed the tests (there are 3 + final).

While he does a good job of teaching the material, the test are very poorly written. There is a line of 10-20 students wanting to ask him questions about the wording of the test, ambiguous options. etc. at all times. The tests are all multiple choice, and the material is fairly simple, but his poor word choice makes the test much harder.

While the material is definitely a cake walk, his exams are just as unclear and wrought with poor phrasing as his lectures are, making them very difficult for those who don't study his old tests. If you do, you're golden.
Great presenter and clear lectures, but terribly when it comes to one-on-one. Tests are all multiple choice and very easy to make mistakes. Tests don't test knowledge of material.

engaging and funny professor. take notes WORD FOR WORD and you will do fine. otherwise, good luck. super funny during lecture but kind of an ass when meeting with him outside of class. overall, a good teacher though, again just be sure to get thorough notes!
No doubt the laziest professor, which is good and bad. You will not get the grade you deserve based on effort. Makes it so that people with connections (back tests) do best.

Very good at explaining concepts, and at doing so in an interesting and entertaining way. Unfortunately, his tests are VERY poorly written. His command of written English grammar is such that merely comprehending his questions is often difficult. At the same time, he peppers them with ambiguous questions that demand rote memrisation of his stories.

Great class...because so many people enrolled he got rid of the writing portion on his exams, making them super easy if you went to class and took good notes. The course should be easy for you if you have a good memory. The material was great and there wasn't really any work outside of exams except for a 2 page paper. Also Experimetrix was GREAT!
very good at explaining concepts with examples

Excellent professor. Lectures are easy to understand and interesting when highlighted with examples. Tests aren't extremely difficult, but can be tricky. I took about 5-6 pages of notes per lecture, so he doesn't give an overload of info. You don't really need to buy the textbook though (he says he uses it, but no question on a test has come from i

almost impossible to do well unless you go to class and listen intently/take good notes. questions on tests can be very ambiguous unless you write down everything and memorize it.. or remember the answer coming out of his mouth: doesn't post lecture notes, book is useless. if you  memorize everything this class is a breeze.
He's a pretty good professor. Lectures are interesting.  If you go to class and listen to him, the class isn't that hard.

Drigotas is a pretty good teacher, and I actually did learn something from his class. He gives very unfair tests with ambiguous questions. One of the best teachers ive had at hopkins, which isn't saying much.
Dr. Drigotas is an awesome teacher.  His psych classes keep me interested and he gives really fun examples.  The class isn't a lot of work, just mainly a lecture and tests. No homework.
great teacher; really funny; tests are straight from lecture notes so if you study tests aren't hard
He was so good I took his second semester class just to get taught by him again, made me want to take Psych as my second major!
Drigotas is an excellent lecturer and really cares about the performance of his students.
Drigotas is a great professor. Hes funny, interesting and you learn a lot very easily because he keeps the lectures very engaging.
awesome prof... my fav. class at jhu (and i'm bme)
This class was easy, and if u do the extra credit it boosts your grade a lot.  however, you have to go to class, because lecture material isn't always in the book.

Most entertaining class I've ever taken. The material is innately interesting, plus Drigotas adds to it with his engaging lecutures filled w/ anecdotes and descriptions of unique experiments.  Tests are moderately difficult, especially essay portions, but still not too bad if you know the material.
Good lectures, hard exams.  Extra credit doesnt help.
Driggy is super awesome.

Great lecturer.  This is a great course if you're humanities and looking to pick up an (N) credit, since he mostly focuses on social psych.  Tests can be challenging, though.  Everyone says the course is easy, but I don't know anyone who got an A.
great class
awsome class
interesting lectures, funny.. however, kinda scary during office hours.
great prof really funny
No Comments

No Comments

prof lectka is amazing!! his lectures make so much sense, and it is literally all the material you are expected to know.
he's amazing, i would take a bullet for this man

Dr. Letcka has such a unique way of teaching- it actually made me look forward to going to class and learning! I never walked out of class confused. Exam expectations are very clear, and the curve is VERY generous. Would take this class again just for his teaching! Wish more profs were like him
rating_tags: Respected--Skip class? You won't pass.--Amazing lectures

comment: Professor Lectka is an amazing orgo professor. He only teaches you what you need to know in a clear and concise manner. He always gives examples and problems in class that he goes over step by step. This is one of his main teaching methods so class attendance is highly encouraged. He is hilarious and made me want to go to class to learn.

Professor Lectka is an incredibly engaging professor, who guides the class through the course content in a clear and easy to follow progression. His teaching style and wit make the challenging concepts covered in Orgo 2 easy to digest. If you engage with the lectures and practice the concepts covered in class, you will be successful.
rating_tags: Respected--Skip class? You won't pass.--Amazing lectures

comment: Prof. Lectka's class for Orgo 2 was delivered in a very refreshing style, and he emphasizes a lot on understanding concepts instead of purely memorizing. Highly recommended to take orgo with him!

Great guy, nice professor. Knows everything about organic. You have to show up to class as notes are not posted.  He uses chalk board rather than power point which is nice

Hilarious dude, great prof.  Good with the chalkboard.
Excellent teacher and friendly guy, should be on TV!  Very fair tests.

Professor Lectka is extremely passionate and he really cares about the subject. I switched from pre-med to a chem major because of him!

This was the best class ever!  EVERYONE LOVED IT!  What a great person!

Content was definitely more challenging than Chem - I. Thanks to Dr. Sunita I had self awareness of my chemistry unawareness
Solid teaching and informative lectures. Very approachable outside class and during office hours and is willing to help you succeed.

She was a great teacher. She is very accessible outside of class and I highly recommend going to her during office hours if you are confused. It is easy to get a good grade as long as you put in the work. I enjoyed her lecture style and would def have her teach me again.

The exams were difficult, her chem II exam was my first in person exam and I got a 27% and was forced to withdraw from the class. She wasn't really willing to help. I personally found all the quizzes difficult. I'm retaking chem II with tolman instead. Avoid taking her if you can!

This class was for me this semester was absolutely horrible. The content itself is not hard, but the way Dr. Sunita lectures is utterly confusing and hard to follow along. On our midterm exam, the most heavily graded portion of the exam was content we learned 2 classes ago, which was extremely unfair. Don't have enough space to write more, but BAD.

I don't even know where to start with this class. Lecturing was awful and poorly paced (which messed up lab). Grading was unclear and she would go off syllabus. The grade scale for the class is AWFUL. Averages for quizzes and exams usually in the 70s, but still need a 92 for an A. The content isn't difficult, but the class is. Take Tolman.

I took a lab with this professor. She made the criteria clear but was not very accessible during class time. Mostly relied on the TAs for feedback. This had more to do with group effort for labs than with understanding the lab skills we were learning.
rating_tags: Accessible outside class--Group projects--Clear grading criteria

comment: Hard midterms and exams. gives too much work and quizzes. Tolman/karlin is better

Dr Sunita is a very informative lecturer. Others have said that her quizzes/exams are very hard, but theyre very similar to those given in class, so I think theyve been fair. She makes some computational errors during lecture and does move quickly through the dense topics, but since the lectures are recorded, I can go back and watch them again.

Professor Sunita is pretty cool but the subject matter is pretty dry. The ideas that she goes over aren't really difficult at all but may be difficult for incoming freshman. What I find rather funny is that you can get a good grade in this class with absolutely no knowledge in chemistry. 80% of this course is computational meaning its mostly math.

Mediocre Professor and her lecturing has gotten much worse in the past few years. She will practically mess up her calculations for almost every problem in class. She's goes too slow on the easiest topics and zooms through the harder topics. Be wary of Thermo; she's struggles to teach that unit. Overall, just don't slack off and you can get the A.
rating_tags: Skip class? You won't pass.--Test heavy--Clear grading criteria

comment: She is extremely willing to help, I would strongly recommend going to her office hours. As long as you work hard it's pretty easy to get an A
Solid teaching. Went to slow at the beginning and too fast at the end but otherwise lectures very well
rating_tags: Respected--Skip class? You won't pass.--Amazing lectures

comment: She is AWESOME!!

Dr. Sunita is truly amazing. She really wants students to do well but you need to work for your grade. She is accessible outside of class. I feel like the people who rate her poorly are those who feel entitled to getting an A or B in this type of class. Chemistry is hard, we get it. But you are going to have to work extremely hard to get a good gra
rating_tags: Gives good feedback--Skip class? You won't pass.--Inspirational

comment: Study hard and meet with sunita often and you'll do great! If you can, take this class over the summer- the class size is much smaller and it's easier to do well!
rating_tags: Gives good feedback--Participation matters--ACCESSIBLE OUTSIDE CLASS

comment: Good lecturer, pretty good representation of intro level chem class. Fair tests and very accessible through office hours.
rating_tags: Gives good feedback--ACCESSIBLE OUTSIDE CLASS--Clear grading criteria

comment: Only had her for chem lab. She doesn't do much in lab, but if you study and understand the chemistry concepts from lecture (whoever you have) and practice the problems, you can ace it. Takes a lot of effort that isn't worth a 1-credit class though.
rating_tags: Skip class? You won't pass.--LOTS OF HOMEWORK--TEST HEAVY

comment: I've seen multiple negative reviews here that have been removed.... This class brought so much anxiety to my first year of college. The lectures are nearly impossible to follow and the exams are unbelievably difficult for someone who has never taken chemistry before. Avoid if you can

Professor Sunita is extremely kind, nice, and generous. She is a very fair grader. If you put in the work, go to office hours, and pay attention, then an A is feasible. I really enjoyed having her as a professor this semester. She definitely made me feel welcome. 10/10
rating_tags: Gives good feedback--Respected--Skip class? You won't pass.

comment: The tests are fair and lots of practice problems and worksheets are available. Prof. Sunita works through a lot of problems on the board in class, which is helpful, and she posts lecture slides online as well. She is a caring professor and is helpful during office hours.
Take Goldberg unless you're really into chem

I had Prof. Sunita for chem 1 and chem 2. She is very helpful, especially in office hours. Tests look exactly like in-class problems, and both chem 1 and 2 are easy A's if you pay attention//try at all. Con: her class full of entitled freshmen who expect A's for no work/disrespect her/talk through class--I think that's why her rating is low.

For chem II she started out as a really great lecturer but as the year went on we would cram a bunch of topics into one lecture and breeze through them without going in depth much. Honestly just do every single worksheet/powerpoint problem and make a solid cheat sheet and you'll be good on the midterms/final. Easy A if you're above the average
Take Goldberg instead for the easier grade but learn more .
Homework is straightforward, tests are challenging, but she's extremely helpful during office hours (she wants you to succeed in her class). The class curve isn't the greatest.
Good teacher, tough grader.
excellent professor but doesn't curve well
Awful.

I had Goldberg first semester and Sunita was sooo much better than him. Her tests are fair and you just have to study, don't expect it to be too easy since a lot of 102 topics aren't covered in high school. Regrades are fair, do the OWLS, don't bother with the textbook, you'll be fine.

I'd first like to clarify that I got a good grade in the class (so this is not about revenge). She did not respect the students and would not admit when she was wrong. When it came to grading, she was stubborn.  Lecture was also poorly taught.

Sunita's class is hard and requires you to work for your grade.  My worst grade, but the curve helped. Homework is fairly easy and not too overwhelming, but tests are hard and heavily weighted. She's willing to help you find ways to succeed if you seek her out. Not overly friendly, but her lecture is huge so she can't be everyone's best friend.

Awesome professor! Great at explaining concepts and encouraging students to think deeply and in a scientific manner about the topics covered. He is also really nice and was willing to offer advice on topics outside of the class. 10/10. Would recommend.

Get ready to get kachowed by the one and only McQueen. He helped me enforce a gambling mentality considering that tests were equivalent to rolling the dice to determine your grade. He's awesome on partial credit but again, won't help much if you can't decipher his drawings on the board. But he has an adorable personality

He was a nice person but disorganized lecturer. The exams were really hard, and I didn't feel like I knew the content compared to peers in other sections since he didn't really teach in class. The curve is generous, so you'll probably get a good grade but not a good grasp on the content.

McQueen was an alright professor, the only problems were the lack of detail in slides, and that he taught at very fast pace, so it could be overwhelming a lot of the time. The exams were VERY difficult, but were curved very well so ended up being alright. Be prepared to work!
rating_tags: Get ready to read--Participation matters--Group projects

comment: Very difficult exams averages ranged from 50-upper 60s. 83% became an A. Tests require a deep conceptual understanding. McQueen cares, but be ready to work. Not the easiest choice.
do not select his class if you have to, he's a physicist not chemist

I had Dr. McQueen for the "Fact Behind the Fiction" FYS. It was easily my favorite course I took first semester. He's so knowledgeable in different fields (quantum mechanics, chemistry, physics), and the course is tailored to the students' academic interests. Quirky, funny, and deeply caring professor.

I had Professor McQueen for a first year seminar, so the workload was very light, but he's a great teacher and really personable. Knows so much about so many different subjects and its really evident in his lectures and teaching style.

DO NOT TAKE THIS CLASS!!The tests are so hard that the class average would always be around a 60 percent. He would not go over many topics bc he expects you to already know it from APChem(even though that material is not covered in APChem) Chemistry was my easiest subject in HS and I got a 5 on the AP exam take my word and dont take this class.

Applied chem- The tests are hard as they are conceptual, include real-life problems. Still, tests have a small effect on total grade, the final is 14% vs hw is 20%. You really learn in this class and get a deep understanding. He really cares, and I really liked the course! Great curve too- B+ became an A. Great professor- tons of resources offered
He's fine. The tests are definitely rough, but not impossible. Do well on the labs to get a high grade!

McQueen is approachable, but his lectures are too fast, like "this should be review from AP Chem" and skipped. The tests were kind of hard but inspirational and focus on application. Just don't be afraid and put down as much as you can. His gradings are super nice. The textbook is super helpful, even if you totally don't get the lectures.
Excellent professor. I learned a lot and would take another class by Prof. McQueen if I had the opportunity to .

Prof McQueen is a really nice dude. If you have any questions, McQueen will help you out. You can always email him for help - imo, one of the most available professors here. His exams are difficult but they're engaging and stimulating. If you just memorize content, you won't pass... You actually have to understand it. Lectures are great.
his exams are actual aids
rating_tags: Tough Grader--Skip class? You won't pass.--TEST HEAVY

comment: Office hours were very very beneficial for me. Tests are very CONCEPTUAL, so learning how to do the mathematics and doing the homework is not enough to do well on exams. Office hours were helpful to learn things on the fundamental level and get rid of misconceptions. Very quirky man. Is willing to help students.. just dont be scared off by quirk.
rating_tags: Tough Grader--Skip class? You won't pass.

comment: McQueen is overall a really great guy and always willing to help his students. The tests are hard and dont really reflect lecture but the curve is very big which compensates for it. The lectures can go off on tangents but are engaging, and he always takes time to make sure you understand the material or answer questions if youre curious.

Professor McQueen is a wonderful educator, with generally fair exams and a reasonable amount of work. If you want to understand how things work on a fundamental level (and many things about poisons and explosions) then make sure to take his class!

I found Professor McQueen to be incredibly fair and clear in his explanations and lecture. Exams tough but fair and curve was generous. Does not deserve the low rating from people salty their grades. The point about not having answers in slides is valid, but there is a reason he said to print out lecture notes before class and follow along.

His exams are fairly difficult. His teaching style is fine, but the class itself is very messy - labs and lectures are almost never coordinated, so you need to stay on top of both separately in order to keep up. Given the difficulty of his exams, paying attention in class is not only necessary but also often not enough. Do the work and you'll be ok
Uses an active learning style and likes to give students practice problems in lecture. Prelectures before every class.
rating_tags: Participation matters--Skip class? You won't pass.

comment: The tests are definitely much tougher than the homework. A lot of buffers are placed into one's grade to make sure it reflects effort rather than the two midterms one may have failed. Overall, for his first year, Tyrel is very responsive to feedback and makes the effort to improve his class. This man is a genius in the most stylish hawaiian shirts.
Please post solutions to the questions you have on your Powerpoint or at least write it down during class. Learning chemistry by listening to you go over answers doesn't help at all.

Tyrel Mcqueen is great! He is clearly very knowledgeable about chemistry  and his legendary Hawaiian shirts (most importantly the monogramed one) have helped me bond with people in my class more than any orientation activity. 10/10.

For his first time teaching a new class, he is doing a fine job. While I was at first blindsided by the formatting of the first test, and he made it difficult to understand what grade you had in the class, he has picked it up in the second half of semester and learned from his mistakes. He is quirky, but a good guy with a cool fashion sense.
rating_tags: Skip class? You won't pass.--Caring--GROUP PROJECTS

comment: This course is different from other classes in that the professor emphasizes on the development of skills that are important for the future instead of regurgitation of facts. It is definitely a course that takes up time, but if you are willing to stick with it, you get a lot out of it. The professor is helpful and wants everyone to succeed in class
rating_tags: Get ready to read--Skip class? You won't pass.

comment: It's a tough class; you'll need a solid knowledge of the basics in order to keep up with his higher level explanations, and he moves fast. He is very easy to talk to though, and always willing to re-explain something. Tests are very conceptual; long and hard but his curving is very fair. Put in the work, don't just memorize and you'll be fine.
rating_tags: Skip class? You won't pass.--ACCESSIBLE OUTSIDE CLASS--EXTRA CREDIT

comment: He's a fine professor. Overly fair on problem sets (it's tough to get less than a 95 on each one), the grades are fairly distributed, and the tests aren't THAT bad. You're in college now, expect it to be more challenging

LOVE TYREL. Great man. He's so smart and does a good job explaining concepts. Very flexible if you miss class, and notes are easy to find/use from online if you miss something. Wears Hawaiian shirts and slides without socks to class if that means something to you. Can be spotted playing with his kids on campus. Overall, Tyrel is an amazing teacher.

AMAZING lecturer and such a nice guy too. He doesn't deserve the hate he gets. Yeah,  his tests are difficult and conceptual, but the grading is incredibly fair. And his hawaiian shirt style is iconic!
rating_tags: Skip class? You won't pass.--ACCESSIBLE OUTSIDE CLASS--Caring

comment: This class is hard; he covers a lot of content very quickly. He's also not the best at explaining things. It's probably because we have the brain capacities of monkeys compared to him, so he struggles to convey information to such low-intelligence creatures.  That being said, I can't hate on him. His Hawaiian shirt + goatee combo is too dope.
rating_tags: Skip class? You won't pass.--TEST HEAVY--LECTURE HEAVY

comment: A course that is structured and organized very efficiently. The professor is not only flexible, but also ensures that students benefit the most from the material taught in the class.

I learned a lot in the class and appreciated his hard work. He is kind and helpful if you make the effort to speak with him. In applied chemical equilibrium, there is the option to go to office hours and learning den.
rating_tags: Tough Grader--Skip class? You won't pass.

comment: The material is tough, yes, but the lecture notes are really helpful, and if you make an effort to stay on top of things in the class and really try to understand why and not just memorize and plug things in, you'll do well. Exams are hard but fair in that they're very conceptual. You can tell Professor McQueen really cares, just ask.

Professor Mcqueen brings a refreshing brand of style and enthusiasm to his morning lectures. He is always ready to teach, and while the material he presents is challenging, a strong work ethic will go a long way. Material is covered in a straightforward, logical fashion, and typically well represented on the exams. Overall, just a really nice guy.

He was an awful professor. Tests are way beyond the scope of the lecture and he seems to ignore the course curriculum and only discuss what is relevant to his research. His office hours are during class, so the only way you can talk to him is if you finish your exam early which is nearly impossible.

Breezes through lectures expecting we know everything on the assumption we learned it in AP Chem. Terrible test makeup policy. Useless homework assignments that don't even show up on the test. ALSO writes stupid tests that don't even address what was learned in class.
rating_tags: Tough Grader--Skip class? You won't pass.--LOTS OF HOMEWORK

comment: He's honestly so bad at teaching this course. He overcomplicates everything and gives you super hard tests that you cannot do. He also expects you to do prelab quizzes and homework assignments on things you haven't learned.
rating_tags: Tough Grader--TEST HEAVY--GRADED BY FEW THINGS

comment: Great lecturer and is very clear. He just is a little bit unreasonable sometimes. Under no circumstance will he let you make up a quiz/midterm even for medical emergency or a sports competition, he just drops it from your grade and weights the other ones heavier which in some math classes is make or break. Pretty inconsistent test grading as well.

Really nice and considerate. I didn't go to lecture but he let me submit a homework a week late with no penalty. His tests aren't too hard and he curves nicely at the end. But you really need to understand the material (like have a solid geometric understanding) of the concepts to do the best. Other than that, start portfolio EARLY.

Super active on Piazza, he really wants to make sure everyone understands the content. Homework sets can be a bit exhaustive (not math-wise, but just writing stuff down), and the TAs take forever to get them graded. Exams are pretty easy imo, easier than problem sets. Seems like such a sweet guy, wish I had him for more classes.

Differential Equations with Professor Brown has been one of the best experiences I've had at JHU. Diff Eq is not an easy class, but brown definitely made it one of the most enjoyable. He has an extreme understanding of the subject and I cant wait to take his dynamical systems class. Professor Brown, "we will talk again very very soon"

Dr. Brown is an excellent professor. If you have the chance to take his class, do so. I feel like I learned so much this past semester; Dr. Brown really cares about his students doing well and he has a fair grading system. Differential equations is no walk in the park, but you'll feel satisfied when you've completed the course. Highly recommended.

Brown is a pretty nice dude, but his Calc 3 class is HARD. The written homeworks were impossible unless you had a really firm grasp of the concepts taught in class--they were all proof-based. However, he makes up for it by having tests that are purely computational, which is pretty nice. Great lectures and interesting class, but definitely not easy
Dr. Brown was an insightful, passionate professor and he made Calculus 3 very enjoyable.

Dr. Brown is the most amazing professor I have ever had in this school so far. His lectures are inspirational and well structured. The creative problems sets make you work for them, and I enjoy working with people and reaching the final solutions. The textbook is good for review and preview. His tests are relatively easy.
rating_tags: Skip class? You won't pass.--Inspirational--Amazing lectures

comment: Nice Guy. But a ridiculous class. Unclear grading criteria, tells ppl that he will give out "subjective" grades. Exams are all computation- with TERRIBLE numbers. Just an exhausting class.
Really funny and nice guy and knows his content very well. Really good teacher!

Had him for differential equations. He helps you truly understand what differential equations are and how you can study them. His exams are very doable if you attend class consistently and study your notes. Only complaint I can think of is his terrible handwriting.
rating_tags: Skip class? You won't pass.--Amazing lectures

comment: Best math teacher/class I've ever had. Really passionate about the material and does a fantastic job explaining how everything is all tied together in a way that allows you can get a good understanding the first time through.

Class could have been easily considered way too difficult for a calc 1 class. Homework and tests graded very harshly with points being deducted for not explaining every theorem used correctly or how you got the right answer. Weekly homeworks appeared short until you realize each problem had multiple parts. Hard class, but very very generous curve.
rating_tags: Tough Grader--LOTS OF HOMEWORK--Tests are tough

comment: Dr. Brown is a great, very personable teacher. His lectures tend to go from a deductive standpoint, rather than inductive, so keep that in mind if you learn better from examples. His tests were fair, and though they are not curved, the class is. There are only 2 midterms and a final, but a LOT of homework!
Hard class, but Prof. Brown's lectures were undoubtedly helpful. Fair amount of homework, although it's only 10% of the overall grade...

He is a good guy.  Teaches in a very general sense, which I honestly did not appreciate.  I had to do a lot of outside studying because that is not how I learn.  However, his tests are extremely fair.  If you know the material, you will succeed.

Dr. Brown is a fantastic, captivating lecturer. His class did talk mostly about theory, but he listens to what the students have to say, and adjusts his teaching style to fit the class's needs as a whole.  His tests are fair, very doable, and follow the structure of the homework. He is always there to answer questions and wants students to succeed.

When I started my semester with Dr. Brown, I was initially dismayed that the class was very theoretical in nature during the lectures, but I really think this class has made me enjoy math as an actual subject rather than a tool used to manipulate other fields. Would easily take another class from him.
He is one of the best professors I have had!

The man made me love math. His lectures are passionate and interesting. He is an inspiring force in a typically insipid education system, teaching a frequently misunderstood subject. Put in the work, and ask him loads of questions. He loves teaching, and he will make you love learning.

Prof. Brown is very easy to talk to and actually wants to help students who are struggling. He knows the material thoroughly and hopes that each of his students enjoys the class and learns the material. He is a fantastic professor. The homework assignments help in preparing for the tests.

Dr. Brown is a great teacher. He focuses a lot on the theory of mathematics, so there is a lot of writing in the class. Most of the times I think it is not helpful because he barely gives examples in class. He spends most of class proving a theorem. His tests are pretty difficult. First exam class average was a 68. Learned most from textbook..
Loves to teach and is really interested in your progress during the course.  Wants the students to learn as much as they could and get full potential out of themselves.  Great professor!

Professor is extremely interesting, funny, and engaging. He has a real passion for math and this shows. His lectures are very clear, concise, and his notes are very helpful. However, the exams are pretty hard.
What a great teacher. He really helps improve Hopkins's reputation because he really loves the topic and loves teaching people. Very professional also.

He has a very theory-based teaching style, which I'm not personally a fan of. The tests are based on homework problems so if you do those & have a good TA you'll be fine. He was very attentive to students & tried to answer questions as well as he could. I personally just had a hard time w/ his teaching style & think didn'the lectures were helpful.

One of the best professors in the department. His explanations are clear and concise and he presents the information in a logical fashion that is conducive to learning. He is also genuinely concerned with your understanding of the class and fosters a passion for the subject. Top reason why I'm a math minor.
Awesome, awesome teacher!!  I absolutely loved having him.  : )

Runs a B- curve, so beware. Says he'll take into account upward trend, but doesn't. Doesn't teach well and gives out way too much work (6 problems asking you to do the exact same thing). Lazy -- won't do things you ask him to. Doesn't really understand questions people ask. Overall, sucky professor. Don't take his course.

He doesn't actually teach all that well, but the textbook is quite helpful. DO THE HW because the tests are exactly like the hw. He does, however, like to assign incredibly theoretical questions but with a good TA and a few hours in the math help room, it is possible to do well. Fair class overall, one of the best in the department.
He dismissed automatically a few complaints about a course I had without listening.
Good teacher, really concerned with how you do in the class
His vocabulary is pretty small, but he manages to explain concepts very well. I thought his exams/final were very fair

Very easy-going prof. He really understands and loves the topic that he teaches. He encourages students' questions and seems to want everyone to pass based on their understanding of the coursework rather than just a couple of test letter grades.
The only examples he uses in class are the ones given in the book.  He is unable to teach new ideas; he just explains things as if you know them.  The book is readable tho.

Brown is great. His lectures are very clear, and he explains both the background and the use of what he teaches. Don't listen to the two reviewers above. He tries really hard to get you to understand what he does. A really cool professor.

While people have said his Calc III lectures were useless, his DiffEq lectures were very helpful. He was very helpful in answering questions and was overall a great professor. Homework was reasonable and tests reflected homework and lecture material well (and weren't extremely difficult, meaning no curve)

As someone already stated, his lectures are useless and boring. However, attending the sections is what matters. I decided to choose him for Diff. Eq's since his teaching style is "predictable" in a bad way. (No need to attend lectures)
Though class, the lectures are boring, and useless, just read the book and you will do fine.
Great class. Very efficient in lectures and covering content.
i like his accent

Absolutely amazing professor - hosted thousands of office hours, answered all lab questions with patience, graded strictly but fair (with final exam being worth only 15% and the three midterms being worth 5% each), and plenty of opportunities to collaborate with classmates and obtain a high grade.
such a king

ACER has such a negative reputation at JHU, but Dr. Young made it so much better! Lowest midterms are only 5% of your grade and the lab has more weight than your two lowest midterm grade combined which are better than midterms if you go to office hours!! (35%) Best professor at Hopkins! If you don't want to take Intro Chem, TAKE THIS CLASS WITH HIM
super friendly, helpful office hours, lots of different assignments count towards final grade. exams aren't curved but are fair

Great professor and will help if you go to office hours. Lab practicals are really fair in my opinion and post labs are hard but can be done quickly if you go to office hours. He helped me a bunch with regular chemistry content too.

very nice prof and was willing to help a lot in office hrs. only thing though is that chem lab has too much work for a class worth 1 credit (especially the fact that there are tests in this class, but maybe that's a requirement from the university).

Dr. Young is amazing and has a hilarious personality! He loves Chemistry, and is committed to helping the students out. Loved going to his office hours, he was super helpful and chill. He even helped with the Chemistry course sometimes (that was besides what the lab held). Definitely recommend taking him!

Experience in class is heavily dependent on TA. Dr. Young was not even seen during some classes. He is usually helpful but will make you feel dumb before you understand. Much better during office hours than during class but go early because everyone goes. Learning how to use the software and equipment is the hardest part of the class.
rating_tags: Tough grader--Gives good feedback--Accessible outside class

comment: Dr. Young is an amazing professor. Anything you take with him is guaranteed to be a good time. He's funny, and is also incredibly smart and talented at explaining chemistry concepts to anyone.

He is an amazing and hilarious person. Beware of all the work for post and pre lab but he will help you a lot if you go to office hours. Favorite professor because he will help with topics for chem lecture.

Great personality but quite distant. Large class size stretches him thin so you'll hardly ever even see talk to him. Doesn't really teach much in class. Relies on premade videos and lab guides. Uses horrendous outdated lab software that makes the course so much harder. Would have liked to get to know him more because he does seem nice and helpful.

He gives a lot of work to do outside of class but honestly, if you don't try to cut corners in the work it isn't that bad and he is always really willing to help in office hours and understanding if you need extensions or extra help. Super funny guy just don't misuse his kindness.

Dr. Young is an all around great professor. Chem lab is a lot of work for a one credit class, but none of it is too difficult. Very straightforward with the grading of the class and ensures as many people do as well as possible. He is a great introduction for freshman who haven't taken a lab before.
Professor Young cares so much about his students! He is so good at teaching chemistry. He works so hard and is always there to help students if you go to him.
Way too much work for a 1 credit class but I like Dr Young
rating_tags: Tough grader--Lots of homework--Accessible outside class

comment: Pretty overhyped. Has a twitch and cats, which is cool. But doesn't actually do much to teach the class. I took it online during covid, so I can't speak for the in-person experience. Just was a lot of assignments per week for a 1 credit course.
rating_tags: Clear grading criteria--Lots of homework--Graded by few things

comment: Great teacher! Young's lectures are clear, although sometimes too in detail. He is very accessible and informative in office hours and through teams. If you put in the time and go to office hours when confused, the A is well within reach.
rating_tags: Amazing lectures --Clear grading criteria--Accessible outside class

comment: This class isn't easy and will make you work. That being said, Dr. Young is undoubtedly incredible. He strives to help his students and ensure they all excel; he is able to empathize with students and understand their needs; and he curves/adjusts grades to ensure everyone gets the grade they deserve. He is funny, passionate, empathetic, and gifted.
He truly cares about each and every one of his students. I learned more from him than I did from Sunita's lectures. We really need Dr. Young to be teaching lecture. He is amazing!
He is so helpful and understanding. He cares about his students, is brilliant at what he does, and is always willing to help.
Best chem professor

I LOVED chem I lab with Dr. Young! He truly cares about each of his students and goes around to check in with all 100 or so of us during lab. The only complaint I would have about his class is that it is a lot more work than 1 credit. But, if you prepare for the labs, ask for help, and do well on the lab practicals you can definitely earn an A!
rating_tags: Gives good feedback--Lots of homework--Accessible outside class

comment: Way too much work for a 1-credit class
He's really passionate about chemistry and very fair too. Once everyone did really badly on a section on the lab practical, and he still rewarded us all points.
Offers good office hours and supplementary materials but the post lab assignments are too time consuming for a 1 credit class.
Came into the class expecting him to be as chill as everyone said he'd be. Nah.

Dr. Young is one of my favorite professors at Hopkins. Chem Labs I & II are very rigorous but he makes it worth it. I highly recommend getting to know him better personally and going to him whenever you have any questions. He's super nice and passionate, and really knows his stuff. He even streams on Twitch, which is absolutely legendary!

Professor Young is a phenomenal professor. Not only is he passionate about teaching, but he is also one of the most supportive professors I have ever had. He is also incredibly enthusiastic and charismatic!

Dr. Young is a gem among Hopkins Professors. His passion is teaching chemistry, and he does it better than anyone else--with loads of enthusiasm and support. He really cares about the well-being of his students and is dedicated to his career 100%. He is not only an amazing professor but also a fantastic friend. I would definitely recommend him!

I had Dr. Young for both semesters of Intro Chem lab and I'm really glad I did. I don't like chem in general, but his energy + enthusiasm made me enjoy being in lab every week :) plus he's always available to talk to students about chem and non-academic stuff! The grading can start a bit rough, but I definitely improved through the semester.

Great and charismatic professor. Always willing to help the numerous students and get them to think about what they are doing rather than just going through the physical motions of the lab. Great chem lab professor. Lab and outside work will take 8-10 hours a week; should be worth more than just one credit. Doing all readings and practice questions before lab is the key to success. Do not procrastinate on post labs, some can take 2-4 hours to complete.
Amazing professor,I had him for intro Chem lab 1 and his enthusiasm and commitment to teaching made my lab experience amazing

Best prof at Hopkins! I was in his Science of Color class and it was so fun and interesting. He REALLY cares for all of his students, and goes out of his way to make sure everyone's doing well. Definitely the best professor Ive had at Hopkins. I took Chem Lab 2 with him and hes very passionate about the topics and cares about his students. Legit the best professor I have had at Hopkins. I had him for Science of Color and does a great job of teaching new concepts. He is not test-heavy at all, but does grade the homework pretty harshly but is not bad at all. I WOULD RECOMMEND!

Prof. Young is a great guy! He is super funny and really knows what he's talking about when explaining complicated chem lab topics. He's extremely caring and truly wants his students to succeed. Zero effort into this class. Routinely 5-10 minutes late to each lecture. Can't even hear him talk sitting in the fourth row. Mumbles and provides no additional information past the slides. Honestly the worst professor I've had while at Hopkins. Rambles on about irrelevant nonsense during lecture, which is pointless. Tests are not impossible though

Worst Professor ever, he comes to class 5 min late then spends 15 more mine trying to fix this worthless camera to project transparencies on the board because he's too lazy to make power points. Read the textbook, study back tests, do practice problems and you should be okay. Class is pointless

incomprehensible, useless, not worth going to class, cross your fingers and study the old exams and hope to God you pass

The man is a rambling, incoherent waste of time. I cannot comprehend how he is a professor. In addition, to mumbling, I have no confidence in his grasp of the subject material. In all likelihood, I could learn better from a TA who does not even speak english.

Worst professor I've ever had. At all costs take the other section. His tests have no relation to study material or previous test. You can not understand him in lecture and does an awful job teaching. Have to rely on the textbook, but even that is barely enough to pass this course.

Kit is incredibly hard to understand.  he has a thick texan accent and i could never read his handwriting. class time was often spent simply trying to figure out what the figures on the board were.  if you read the book, you were pretty good, but the trick is to look at his old tests on the library website.
Class sucks

If you can find any othewr source of information, use it, because the lectures are not helpful if it's your first time seeing something...and if it's your second time seeing it, you'll understand why.
Ugh. He has that Forrest Gump accent thing going on..
Useless bag of crap.  Study old exams, and the class will be an easy A.

Yes, he mumbles. But really, if you go see him during office hours you realize he's a genius and loves chem. I suggest visiting him, at least for the heck of it and looking at old exams. This class is a breeze.

Kit Bowen is inept. He can not teach. Lecture is worthless; he mumbles and says nothing useful anyway. difficult to understand

remember milton from office space? yea thats bowen. dont bother going to lecture, just study old exams (and i dont mean the night before the exam- keep on top of things)

comment: Gets a bad rap, but coming from someone who had to take Orgo 1 twice, he's actually great. Townsend is the best chemistry teacher I've ever had. He is very approachable and explains the reasoning behind reactions and mechanisms. In retrospect his tests were pretty easy and as long as put in the work you'll do well. I hope he teaches Orgo II.

Lectures quickly...do not attempt to listen and understand...just take notes and review them  Approachable BUT not accessable.  Absent entire week of Passover however felt it was fine to "substitute" office hours prior to exam on Easter Sunday at 10am as only "makeup" time available!

Funny guy.  At first he seems unapproachable, but he's actually very understanding and probably the best teacher I've had at Hopkins.

comment: Dr. Principe is the most knowledgeable, enthusiastic, brilliant professor I've had at Hopkins. He's taught this class for decades, including a student who later wrote an orgo textbook (Klein, highly recommend it). Fantastic professor. I had him for his scientific revolution class. Lectures are engaging, clear, and concise, and the section really helps solidify the material. If you go to lectures and do the readings the tests and papers are a breeze. Fantastic professor

I took this class not got Organic Chemistry, but for Scientific Revolution. Principe was a great professor, honestly. comment: What can I say? He's clear, concise, funny, kind, brilliant, and, above all, a kind person. He is, and will likely remain, my favorite professor at Hopkins. 10/10.

Amazing teacher.  He gives funny antidotes throughout his lecture that help you remember what was taught.  His tests mimic his notes and it is very important to go to his lecture.  The best professor I have ever had!

Orgo. He is a good lecturer, but his tests are ridiculously hard. You must to completely understand every concept he teaches you and memorize all reagents and mechanisms. I will repeat so you don't forget. You should attempt to completely understand every concept he teaches you. Also put every effort to memorize all reagents and mechanisms.
The Best at Hopkins. If you study his notes and read the text, you will be fine. whatever class he teaches in the future, I'm definitely taking it.
One of the best professors at Hopkins. Teaches so well you really have no excuse if you do poorly on his tests (although they are hard).
GREATEST PROFESSOR EVER! The class isn't too easy though
principe is the best ever

Lectures very easy to understand, extremely clear handwriting and voice, and by far the best at explaining concepts. Makes even the boring topics quite interesting, and exams are very fair and sometimes even fun (believe it or not).

An absolutely incredible professor. He makes difficult concepts crystal clear, writes extremely fair tests, and inserts his incredible sense of humor into every lecture. There's no need to read the book, his lectures make a lot more sense and are incredibly well-organized and interesting.

The only chance you have of making an A is if you are in constant communication with her about improvements.
Does not care about her students as professor or as an advisor.
