comment: I like how Dr. Donohue kept the course relevant and interesting with research papers. Her communication and teaching style was perfect for an online course. It was enough to keep things on track and stay focused.
rating_tags: Amazing lectures --Clear grading criteria--Accessible outside class

comment: Best first semester of grad school! Lots of material but lectures and animations were super helpful. Would highly recommend!
Do not take this professor; if she is your advisor, I would suggest you switch advisors as well. She is not here to help you.
rating_tags: Tough grader--Get ready to read--Test heavy

comment: I met with Dr. Donohue a few times during the semester and the feedback was helpful. Exam essay questions are tough but not unexpected or unreasonable.
Tough class but I like how everything was posted from the beginning of the semester. It made scheduling easier. Weekly announcements also made it easier to see what was due and stay on track.

If you are not a good writer I would not recommend taking this class. She is not accessible to her students. She is a tough grader and very short with her answers. Her lectures are way too short for stem cell biology. There needs to be more information involved. She won't give you any extra work if you have a C she will not help you improve.
rating_tags: Tough grader--Get ready to read--Test heavy

comment: Tough class - textbook is heavy in molecular pathways. Lectures and rubrics gave good context on what to focus on, though.
rating_tags: EXTRA CREDIT--Clear grading criteria--Accessible outside class

comment: I had her for stem cell bio. Lecture material was HS level (e.g. lecture videos featured built-in Khan Academy videos like about mitosis). Rules were harsh (e.g. you get a 0 on exams if you have internet connection issues during). Docks pts on essays for "rules" that weren't in guidelines (but not many pts). Would not recommend but it's an easy A.

Loved this class! The course covered a lot but I feel it really gave me a strong foundation in cell bio. Dr. Donohue was super kind and supportive. The organization of the course and weekly announcements also helped me stay on track each week.
Dr. Donohue encourages discussion of real-life applications and promptly responded to questions I had. Textbook was detailed but course discussions narrowed down what we needed to know.

Complete waste of time taking this class, but you get out of it what you put in it. The textbook for this class is old, outdated, and totally useless. Dr. Donahue isn't very responsive to email and there is little engagement between her or between the students in the course. Easy A, though.

Dr. Donohue has clear expectations for the course. If you follow the schedule, put in the work, and ask questions when you have them, you'll do well. Dr. Donohue was always available to meet with me and is very knowledgeable. The class was dense but relevant and engaging, even in the online format.
rating_tags: EXTRA CREDIT--Gives good feedback--Accessible outside class

comment:
This professor does not teach in favor of the students. She does not distinguish clear grading rubrics for the discussion portion which leads to unfair grading. 

If you have to take her class, review her presentations and read the textbook. She will not be present at all during the duration of your semester. I would not take her class again.
Easy class but the professor's personality/attitude is terrible! She is not very understanding. She belittles students.

Dr. Donohue was very responsive and her class was set up as I think a Cell Bio class should be. If you learn the material, you will do just fine. She is very personable and lectures aren't too lengthy/monotonous, but you will likely have to read quite a bit from the textbook (once again, cell bio..). Highly endorse her altogether. She "gets it".
rating_tags: Get ready to read--Clear grading criteria--EXTRA CREDIT

comment: Get ready to spend an entire semester with your textbook. There are a lot of opportunities for gaining points in this class, but the exams are tricky and you have to know your stuff to finish on time. Dr. Donohue is somewhat AWOL when it comes to email, but when you can connect with her, she offers great feedback and is super nice.
rating_tags: Get ready to read--Lecture heavy--EXTRA CREDIT

comment: Good guy, genuinely likes the subject, is really good and somewhat easy over the summer. Summer class goes even slower than semester class.

Very thorough lectures and quite clear on what is expected on the tests. Some test questions come directly from book exercises. Meyer is pretty laid back as far as chemists go and his sarcastic humor is amusing at times. Great class overall.
Study previous exams
Meyer is uninterested in his students and hides this disinterest behind an "extreme" knowledge of Chemistry. No need to attend class and prepare to be confused.

Meyer was a good professor, but his tests were kinda hard. They weren't hard to do well on if you know your stuff. He doesn't recycle old questions as much cause some kids complained about that. Why, I don't know. But if you know the material, his exams are straightforward. Good lecturer too.

Meyer is a wonder professor and he is very nice. He covers everything that is relevant and is very clear about what will be on exams and what won't be on exams. He emails you back within a day and cares about the material he is teaching. I am so sad that I won't be able to have him next sem. Study the old exams cuz ALL the questions are recycled.

Definitely cynical and sarcastic during lectures. He'll pick on students who ask questions. But at the same time, extremely funny and entertaining. No textbook for this class. Lectures are useful but sometimes often Wikipedia supplement. Midterms come straight out of the HW packet. Class is easier than most ECE courses.
Taught half of the the semester but was a good professor. Jerry is the man.

Prof. Meyer is the most useless professor in the department (if he even shows up for class).  He is uniterested in his students and is extremely aloof!  He takes him home life out at work and all he seems to care about is running.

The most absolutely ridiculous professor at Hopkins. Would stand there after the ENTIRE class had failed an exam and lecture on how we had not taken the time to learn the material. I highly doubt that 300 people all didn't take the time to learn the material.

He was friendly and approachable. He definitely cares about whether his students learn the material. Some of the problems in this class stem from the TAs and the size of the class. Meyer ultimately doesn't grade the tests and figures out how the class is doing based on what the TAs say which is slightly problematic. He does try to fix any problems.
Covers all material clearly and effectively.  Overall, a great professor.
Most heinous prof ever. Very unsympathetic and unapproachable. Arrogant... I'd rather stick a pen in my eye than ever take his class again.
nice teacher, responsible
Make no mistake, Meyer hates you and everything you stand for.  He is entertaining and brilliant though and respects brilliance and little else.
great professor- take classes with him

AWESOME. Best chemistry professor at Hopkins. And he's a real human being- you can actually talk to him like a normal person (how many other professors are like that). One of the best professors overall, in fact...
Cynical and patronizing on any given day.  He has no respect for anyone or anything...especially microsoft and java.
Professor Meyer is a decent professor.  He is very very cynical (as mentioned before), he is also funny at times.  Tests are fair, and his lectures are clear.  He also hates M$, which is a plus.
No Comments
the material is not that hard but he is mean.
He's sort of mean and irritating.  Sometimes funny with his cynicism though.  if you can understand the accent, he teaches decently though.
i really enjoyed his class. test were very fair. just make sure u understand and can replicate the old tests
No Comments
No Comments
Good guy.
No Comments
Wonderful.  A real human being (<5% of professors are like him)
All he cares about on tests is dumb calculations!
Terrible teacher. Material is easy but he uses outdated overhead slides and on top of that doesn't let you take notes!!!
rating_tags: Participation matters--Skip class? You won't pass.

comment: Lectures weren't helpful, but the in class questions are a portion of your grade. I found the exams to be difficult at times, but overall not killer. Barnett seems to really care about how his students do  so if you have issues, just talk to him.
Does boring demonstrations, which are completely useless. Awful and teaching material. If you have him, READ THE BOOK AND TEACH YUORSELF!!!!
I found the class material to be rather difficult, but I would say that he does a good job at teaching and relating with the students. I would recommend taking his class if you get the chance.

He doesn't curve the tests, but the class itself is curved, where an 80% is an A. That being said, if he writes a particularly hard test, you're screwed because he won't curve it even if the average is low. Homework takes time, but if you have problems email him and he'll explain the problems. Lectures weren't helpful but attend for the clickers.
HE IS THE MAN!!!!!!!!!!! GREATEST TEACHER EVER!!!!! EVER!!!!!
while i'm not the best at physics, this course is my favorite. His demonstrations are extremely awesome!!!

Dr.Barnett is a bit monotone with his lectures, but goes the extra mile through his memorable demonstrations (fire extinguishers for propulsion, suspending himself from the ceiling for pendulum motion, etc). Tests are crazy long for the time allotted, and the online homeworks are real time suckers, but he grades fairly.
He is without a doubt, the best professor I have ever had. He is clear, concise, and is extremely nice. He makes me extremely confident that he knows the material and much much more.
HE IS THE BEST PROFESSOR AT jOHNS hOPKIN uNIVERSITY.
Instead of office chair, package contained bobcat. Would not purchase again.
No wonder Dr. Barnett has won a number of teaching awards!  He is extremely dedicated to helping students learn physics.
Great prof who really cares and hates failing people.
Great demonstrations, and overall a great teacher. He tries to keep the lectures interesting with his experiments, he wants the students to learn, he really loves physics.
Barnett is the shiznit
nice guy. makes physics understandable. whens everyone to learn and succeed.
Hard to get an A, though A- and B+ are possible. Attendance practically mandatory cuz of the damn clickers, everyone sleeps thru class anyways.
This man is made of demonstrations. The class is pretty easy and the constant demonstrations makes it easy to pay attention. Hes a good teacher.
Lectures boring, but hes a kind old fogey
He is your average teacher. He seems to care more about teaching than other professors.
go to him for homework help and he'll give you the answers. he's far easier than wyse and definitely cares more.
horrible, horrible teacher
Is not a good teacher, makes u feel inferrior for wanting to learn
No Comments
HE'S SO MUCH BETTER than Dr. Chien (teaches 2nd semester 171.101) where I failed
the average on the last test was 1 point above failing.  Be warned.
Seems to care about the class, but lectures are really boring
Very Challenging Class, If you aren't a physics major, don't expect an A
Claims to want to help, but makes you feel stupid for asking for it...

Super kind & there's A LOT of external assignments that can help your grade if you do bad on exams. Additionally, the exams are curved/normalized, and the curve can never damage your grade. This class is strictly memorization, so if you know the material on the lecture slides & in the pre-class videos, you'll do great. Least stressful class for me.
rating_tags: Gives good feedback--Lecture heavy--Accessible outside class

comment: She's so nice and it's not hard to get an A if you try
Dr. Pearlman is amazing! It is clear that she cares a lot about her students, and enjoys what she does. She is very kind to everyone, even if she does not know you personally.

she is amazing. the lectures can be a bit boring but she explains everything perfectly. Her office hours are great and she is always there for you for questions. She loves what she does and I recommend everyone to take her

I love Professor Pearlman. She explains concepts very clearly and demonstrates her willingness to help her students. She responds to questions in class, over email, and during office hours with incredible patience and care. It is clear that she has a passion for teaching.

One of my favorite professors by far. It is clear that she cares about her students and wants them to succeed. She makes the lectures interesting and interactive, but what stands out is how helpful she is outside of class. If you get the chance to take a class with her, DO IT. You won't regret it.
She is kind, tests are straightforward.
Always willing to answer questions during class and office hours

She is super sweet and is genuinely willing to spend time talking to you. Explains concepts relatively clearly and always gives suggestions on how to improve. I ended up doing somewhat poorly on one of the midterms and went to go talk to her about it, and she was extremely supportive and encouraging.
She is a true bae, anyone who doesnt love this pearl of a woman has issues and needs to take gen bio I with her because she is the bestest sweetheart one could ever meet.
Gen Bio Lab is pretty clear cut. Just follow the guidelines and an A is extremely feasible. Lab was very fun and short. Pearlman is very kind and fun to talk to.
She's a really good professor and you can tell she actually cares. She teaches thing in a really easy way to understand. Don't listen to all the haters. One of the few nice people at this school.
Yay! Thanks, Prof. You rock!!!
Jolly woman.  She's really nice if you go and talk to her.  Class is not very good though.  Bad organization but easy A.

PowerPoints are a mess, but Dr. Pearlman places emphasis on what could be on the exam. Does a lot of CPS questions, so go to class. Almost 50% of her exam questions are from previous years, so STUDY PAST EXAM QUESTIONS. Posts helpful Bio Workshop questions, which are on the exam, exactly in the same format. Do past exam questions!

She is very unprofessional and it takes her forever to reply to email or post grades. It's easy to do well in the course (esp. considering that half the test questions are repeats from previous exams), but she doesn't take her work seriously. Summary: She is an embarrassment to an otherwise excellent JHU Biology Department.

This class is incredibly unorganized. There are three different professors with different teaching styles. Pearlman's lecture slides have obnoxious color schemes and are hard to keep track of. They take very simple material and make it confusing with poor organization. Not to mention, she skips material when she is in a rush to finish a lecture.

Why are people complaining about Dr. Pearlman? She is an friendly and devoted teacher who wants her students to understand the material and do well. One thing you should though, if you have any pressing questions email McCarty or Shingles. Pearlman doesn't give quick replies.

Dr. Pearlman certainly teaches like a high school teacher, but it truly helps us understand the information.  Pay attention in lecture, and you'll do fine.  She explicitly states what you will and will NOT need to memorize/understand for the test.  She is also very understanding when it comes to being sick/having family emergencies.
Super friendly.  One of the nicest and most lenient profs ever!

Dr. Pearlman may teach us like high school students, but it's not because she disrespects us. She actually cares whether or not we understand and learn, unlike most other professors here who couldn't give a damn about us.

I agree with everyone.  She would be a great high school or middle school teacher, but with Hopkins students in her class, it's just insulting.  Like someone already said, what professor asks questions to a 300 person class.  She is also great at coming up with busy work projects that waste students time and dont teach them anything helpful.

Talks down to us sometimes, but overall she is a good lecturer. She's extremely helpful and concerned about her students. She'll say every other slide, "this could be on the exam," so just know everything for the exams and you'll be golden. The course is easy but there is a lot of material so break your studying into small pieces and do old exams.

I love Dr. Pearlman.  She's really friendly and shows a true interest in her students and an excitement for her subject.  She is extremely helpful and patient  and shows a genuine concern for her students.  I loved her class!
shes mean
She teaches us like high school students.  I would respect her if she would respect me.

She is a very nice teacher.  However, she teaches to much like a high school teacher.  She aks questions in a 300 person lecture.  A good proffesor could teach as much in 20 minutes as she does in an hour.  I have begun to hold the class in contempt.  Why should I be taught like a 14 year old at one of the best universities in the world?
No Comments
She's nice.  I think she explains things well and is always willing to help.
very nice professor, always smiling. she is interested in helping students, which may be why there is a large line outside her office when she has office hours.

Lectures are clear and entertaining, and note templates can be useful. Homework is challenging and can sometimes be time consuming but TAs are always happy to help. Exams are difficult especially with the allotted time but curve is generous. Overall, a good grade is doable if you put in the work and you will learn a lot from this course.

Really great professor; never feel resonated to those negative comments; it is a difficult class but he teaches really well and he genuinely cares for his students. If you show that you are making efforts, you'll probably gonna get a good grade.

Very nice grading policy for this course: The homework and 3 midterms each takes 25% while the final is a voluntary make-up exam for one of the midterms. There are also several opportunities to earn additional points. He holds long office hours and are always happy to answer questions. A very nice person and a clear lecturer. STRONGLY RECOMMEND.
Poor course structure. Not easily accessible outside of class times. Not very forgiving on exams and homework assignments.
rating_tags: Graded by few things--Test heavy--Tough grader

comment: This prof is just ridiculous, and he is not understanding his students at all. He will get his cost.

The grading for this class is ridiculous! For example, I had misread a question on the final and put my answer for part c in the wrong spot. He was not understanding at all and eagerly did not give me back any points. I was one point away from earning an A! His responses on Piazza are also VERY rude! If you can get another professor, DO IT!
He is very moody. Be prepared to see very different sides of him depending on the day and/or semester. Exams were hit or miss. A lot more material in the class than is possible to be tested on.

Lectures were decent. Sometimes, they missed the bigger picture of why we were doing something, but going to office hours helped a lot. Dr. Torcaso is great, but the TAs for this course are excellent. The exams tended to be fair. Seriously though, go to office hours!
While his class was very hard, I greatly appreciate how he cares for his students.
Great professor cares about your grade if you care

Torcaso is a great lecturer. And Math subjects are really hard to teach as lectures. But Torcaso can do it. He will make sure you understand the material. rating_tags: Gives good feedback--LOTS OF HOMEWORK--Amazing lectures

comment: At first I was thinking about dropping this course but I'm so happy that I did not drop it! The lectures are very helpful, make sure you take good notes. The handwritten notes by the professor are also good materials to study. Textbooks are okay but it's not mandatory to read them. The exams are very fair, not hard if you understand the lectures.

Some people say he's a nice guy, some people say he was rude, mean, and unnaproachable. I saw both sides. On the whole he didn't seem very interested in us. There was way too much homework for it to count for such a low percentage of the overall grade. The tests had wordy questions. ZERO partial credit. Felt like he was just trying to dock points.
rating_tags: LOTS OF HOMEWORK--TEST HEAVY--GRADED BY FEW THINGS

comment: I don't know why everyone said he cares about his students - he literally screamed at this one girl for no reason,and  snorted dismissively while handing back tests to the students that apparently didn't do well. I came out with an okay understanding of stats and better understanding that there are rude people out there.

If you only expect to memorize formulas you won't do well. Tests are based more on understanding than memorization and are structured around examples given in class. not helpful at office hours, teaches the class content in a confusing and incoherent way, does not give partial points in exams, makes his own questions that are wordy and unnecessarily complicated
His class is fairly easy, however, he does not curve at all and does not care about his students whatsoever. His tests get progressively harder throughout the semester.

Horrible.Ignore other ratings. His class does not have a curve and the avg is like a C-. Do not take it if you don't have to. Book is useless. Study the lecture notes and do all/study over the homework. Then you might do ok. Otherwise prepare to get destroyed.
i really hated this guy. He didnt teach the class well, and the homeworks did not repressent the exams well.

Dr. Torcaso is one of the best professors I've had here. He explains all of the concepts really well and is genuinely interested in helping his students learn. After the last class, he even thanked me for working hard; he's a really nice, quirky person, who also does a really good job teaching the class.
A really nice guy, but class is pretty boring because of the easy material.
Teaches well from experience. Better than most LADE teachers. I wish that I had gone to class more, but I did okay without going. Section is pretty useless. He is interested in his subject
Fred is the best teacher I ever had. He makes difficult subjects seem crystal clear, easy.
Great guy, very clear. Boring class, though. TA's are important.
Good teacher but the subject is too easy to not teach well. The class is so boring and only half the people show up except on Fridays, when we turn in HW. YOu learn better from TA's
One of the best professors Ive had at Hopkins. He is actually a really nice who respects and cares about his students.
Great professor. Nice guy, good teacher, funny quirks.

Extremely good teacher and all around nice guy. I've never heard anyone whisper a bad word about him in 3 classes i've taken. Fred runs class very straightforward. He lets you know from day 1 what you need to learn and do, teaches it 1 step at a time each day very organized, and tests you on nothing more/nothing less than what he tought you in clas

This guy genuinely shouldn't be a teacher, you can tell he's smart but he clearly doesn't want to teach. I don't understand how his lack of a desire to teach made him an unempathetic person though. Poor teaching skills but the final was very fair, the average score was a 38/40 with 4 buffer points were awarded. Honestly since his first class which was online I straight up knew it wasn't worth attending any of his lectures and decided to save time for my sleep. Content and exams are easy though, it's actually unbelievable that people get an average of 55 on midterms. Huajie has responsibility of course, but there is a student intelligence issue here too.

comment: Being a professor is not for him, but he did make sure to answer my questions during office hours and show everything on the board. Other reviews are too harsh

Actually god awful professor, makes the course exam heavy then gives no back test or useful knowledge on the exams, only by Gods grace will the TA's MAYBE give a review exam literally the night before. L prof but it could b worse

Nice guy, just not meant to be a professor/teacher. Sometimes confusing, but the textbook and other online sources in addition to the learning den and TA sessions helped. comment:
Huajie Li is an unempathetic human being for subjecting his students to this. Reviewing for his final without help from Pilot or TAs should be used as a CIA torture technique. This school is wrong for allowing this man to essentially the same as throwing us in the deep end without teaching us to swim first. 
We deserve a refund.
Terrible terrible teacher, incomprehensible, and I had to teach myself and my classmates the whole course. DO NOT TAKE HIS CLASS.

Hi, Professor Li here. I know you're all probably excited about my class! I mean, who wouldn't be thrilled about two insanely hard midterms with some questions that I didn't teach about? I pride myself on keeping things interesting. Why settle for clear explanations when I can just read the textbook? It's all about problem-solving, right?

Public Service Announcement:
Avoid taking a Huajie Li math class at ALL COSTS. The only way you will pass this class is through the TAs, Textbook and Tutors (I recommend Organic Chemistry Tutor). 

Unfortunately, Prof. Li's impeccable style and fashion sense will not save your grade..

BUM. Reads straight of the textbook, very inaccessible outside class and provides practice exams that have nothing to do with the actual exams. Takes long amount of time on singular questions which leaves most of the learning to the students own time, passive aggressive towards students in the class, refuses to curve.

A unique professor with an interesting teaching style! Unlike other, overbearing professors, he allows his students a lot of leeway and independence. Prof. Li's students get to teach themselves the whole curriculum! I recommend this class to students who:
- have a lot of free time
- already know the material very well
- are free Sunday night

On MULTIPLE occasions I have taught myself the content AND gone to TA and Learning Den sessions to make sure I understand. Then, somehow, he manages to read the content STRAIGHT out of the textbook and still not make any sense. It's not because of his accent, either. He. Just. Can't. Teach. Hopkins Math Dept: let this man do his research in peace.

Some statistics from our last midterm: 
Minimum = 17.5%
Maximum = 97.5%
Mean = 59.35%
Median = 57.5%
Standard Deviation = 16.5%. 
We need 70% to pass this class (and move on to Calc 3). 

Huajie Li is an "or" because he does NOT profess, he only regurgitates/reads the textbook. 
Why are we paying for something text-to-speech can do?

This guy makes it too obvious that he hates teaching. He has a knack for getting on my nerves when says "this should be obvious" or "moving on" immediately after someone asks him a question. Worst teacher ever.

Do not ever take a class with his name associated with it. I pay tuition to learn in class not get tortured by it. It's one thing if the tests are hard, but the professor teaches well. Yeah, bro, I can't teach at all good luck.

grading rubric for tests are poorly created and designed to give you as little points as possible
he wears great shirts

comment: As a guy, he's kinda an icon. A sweet + unintentionally hilarious PERSON. Don't take his class though lmao. No exam relief or cushions. Midterms are 20 points each which screws you. Dr. Li is bad at teaching and is unfair with his exams. I'm not sure if anyone can understand him with his thick accent, which is why less than half of class show up for his lectures. BAD when a big portion of midterm is explaining thoughts

comment: terrible, terrible teacher. gives an exam problems on a chapter he did not teach, and told us to prepare for. who does that? and his lectures are trash. this is hopkins education that is ranked so high? ridiculous.
taken for calc 2. grades were 20% homework, 20% midterm 1, 20% midterm 2, and 40% final. Lectures are unhelpful so you're gonna have to learn everything on your own

Karlin is a prettty average professor. Lectures are long and monotone, but otherwise are pretty well built around topics you need to know for chemistry. I'd recommend doing a lot of practice problems on your own if you don't want to get lost.

Dr. Karlin's class is easy to study for with the practice problems given in powerpoint presentations and test reviews. There is a good curve in this class and as long as you listen to his directions, you should be in good shape for this class.

Dr Karlin was not the worst professor but I would hesitate to say he was a good one. His lectures were hard to follow and we didn't finish the material by the end of the semester.
