It's not the easiest class out there but he's an awesome professor.  He really cares about his students.  I think he curves to a B+. :)
Runs class at a challenging but do-able level. A very interesting teacher who is concerned that everyone learn the material and succeed.

Went to almost every lecture...  The lectures were complex, yet followable.  He engages the class, and it very excited about teaching.  Great guy and fair in his exams.  Interested in students learning the material.
No Comments
Very nice person

She now teaches Philosophy at Boston College and is honestly one of the best Philosophy teachers ever! Her lectures are so animated and logical(?). She is one of the few professors who understands that she is teaching a bunch of undergraduate students who don't know much about Philosophy. Her lectures are relatable and make sense.

The most fun and engaging class I've been apart of so far. Class discussions are super engaging and she leads them expertly. She seems to really want to know what your opinions are and for you to be as informed as possible to make your own decisions. She has one of the best feminism related courses at massart.

Great professor. Smart as hell. You might just have a different outlook on life if you take her class seriously, she really takes you on a journey. Some subject matter is not easy for the narrow-minded to wrap their heads around. Lots of philosophy, lots of testing of theories.

Took her WritCom course at MassArt -- while it was nominally a class on essay writing, this was an advanced placement class and the bulk of the material was focused on philosophy and utilitarian ethics. Class was engaging and involved debate. She is very critical of your essays and doesn't just hand out As, but is fair and helpful. Good humored.

- Always interested in your questions   - Review sessions or at least gives you review notes so that you do well on the test.   - I took the class in a very small room and with few people, so I got tons of attention both inside and outside the class.

She is ery available outside the class and very interested in all of your questions, even the little and stupid ones. I def recommend any classes with her. She also has review sessions (at least she had when i was taking her class) and you go to the finals prepared.
She is a seriously awesome prof. I highly recommend any class with her. Her lectures are extremely organized and she's ALWAYS available outside of class for any help you might need.
She's clear, knows her stuff, and wants you to understand. Cool teacher.

Dr Schwartz is a great teacher and is always willing to help you understand the topic/material.  I took this class freshman year and to this day, Dr Schwartz still remembers my name and says hello to me in the halls.

A great prof...fair exams..generally nice and approachable, tries to get students involved in the discussion, passionate about the subject..only downside is that you get a final exam and a final paper.
Easy-to-understand, interesting lectures. A lot of reading, but not hard. Tests not difficult--very similar to practice exams.

The class is awesome and he's really into his subject. He's easy to understand and makes it clear what's expected of you. Never try to answer his in-class questions: you will always be wrong. Only Schwartz can have the correct answer!

Attendance isnt mandatory, but if you attend class regularly and do the reading, you should be well set for the exams. Sometimes he can be mean and unhelpful (he hates undergrads), but the course is really interesting if you want an introduction to Near Eastern Studies.
Good lecturer, he seems genuinely interested in what he is talking about. Very knowledgeable.
very enthusiastic
Seemed annoyed at having to teach the class.
I loved him, I think he's great! Really nice to listen too and not hard to look at
Terrific professor! Great small class.
Has he taught a class here this century?  I guess he's too important.

Lectures were pretty decent. He would put the lectures outlines on powerpoint slides that were available on the web, so you only had to take notes of the finer points. However, was not anything special.
fun to listen to; smart; clearly enjoys teaching. I really learned a lot and I think the other people who rated him are way off the mark
Not the nicest guy. not that interesting lectures.  maybe he's more interesting in his specialty.
He just liked to hear himself speak and his lectures don't have to do with the readings
Extreme arrogance gets in the way of his teaching.

I graduated JHU in 1977!  I am still in contact with Dr. Knight.   He was inspirational to a kid back then, and is still a sane, savy, and thought-provoking man today.   I would say his humor and knowledge are a unique combination.  And he CARES about his students and their own successes.
Great professor, very much helped me and expanded my knowledge of Caribbean History. One of the best at Hopkins.

This Prof is my best ever.  I consider him amongst one of the best Profs I have ever had.  Years later I still appreciate all he taught me. Interesting class. Information has held me in good stead. Smart Prof. I highly recommend this class to all who can fit it in their schedule. Never boring. With a changing America this class is a must.

Very demanding (readings often hundreds of pages a week), challenged students to go beyond what was covered in class. Clearly he's a very intelligent guy who knows it, in an effort to reach his students goes overboard with anecdotes.  Sometimes blase about teaching an undergrad class, I accepted the challenge and got a lot out of him.  Yes he rants

I've had several classes with Prof. Knight and while I agree that sometimes he goes of on tangents during lectures, he seems to know what he's talking about and was often readily accessible outside of class, even though his office hours were early and limited. I've had several lunch meetings though.

terrible class. the professor was absent and unhelpful most times. i felt like he looked down his nose at us. he had funny anecdotes and talked about liquor...but veered off topic and shot down answers from students. participation was discouraged...his demeanor was arrogant and negative

By far the worst professor I have had at this school. His Cuba class is a train wreck. hes arrogant, told one girl her comment was a "wasted thought." he massages his own ego in class, goes off on too many tangents. what a jerk
extremely knowledgable. very kind, has many anecdotes. however, he tends to make too many jokes and has to rush to finish lectures.
Great professor. Very kind person.
Awesome professor!

Professor Meng is humorous. His class was interesting and inspiring. Moreover, he is caring for his students. He is always ready to answer our questions. I went to his office hours many times, and it was quite helpful.
Fantastic Professor!

Yeah don't take calc II for engineering. His class setup was just essentially Calc BC but every problem just had excessive algebraic manipulation making it easy to mess up and lose a lot of points. Did bad on like one exam and was finished. Curve was also pretty tough, and lectures were also not super helpful.
rating_tags: Tough grader--Test heavy--Graded by few things

comment: Funny and always shows up to class with the best drip. He is really caring and occasionally says some super inspirational stuff to the class. He also knows his stuff, hes insanely good at math. Class is difficult, but he is really generous with the curve. Just make sure to attend all the lectures and take notes.

The professor was a very clear and concise professor and very kind. He explained the content very well and gave inspirational speeches to the class as well. Overall a very nice and funny guy and definitely recommended.

Meng is absolutely hilarious! He says the funniest things during lecture which makes it all the worthwhile. It's also clear he cares deeply about his students. One time, the class avg for a midterm was 55%, and a student asked if he was disappointed in us. His answer? No, he wasn't disappointed and that our happiness is what matters most.

He does not go over everything you need to know in class. The TAs often contradicted each other so it was hard to tell what you were supposed to do. Sections frequently go over time so the TAs can make sure you have all of the information needed for the HW. HW is 25% of grade and you must do all of them or you fail. Bad at answering questions.
Peter Achinstein is one of the best philosophy professors that Johns Hopkins has to offer.

Don't take intro to logic. I went to this guy and both of the tas when I was failing the course and they offered no help. Makes you buy his own book which doesnt have an answer key for non homework problems like any normal math book. This makes it so you can't do add. practice outside of the ridiculous hw grades you on for 25% of your cumulative.

He fails you if you miss one homework assignment. There is no curve and the homework assignments (worth 25% of your final grade) are difficult. The tests are straightforward but he likes to make the final hard. Not very many As...

Intro to formal logic. Great teacher, quite funny at times, but it irks me so much when he misses a spot while erasing the blackboard (which is ALL THE TIME). Make sure you have a good TA because the HW problems can be HARD. He likes to challenge you with HW problems harder than any example done in class. Tests are doable. Little to no reading.

Awesome teacher. I've never seen a prof encourage so much discussion while always keeping it on topic. Encourages serious thinking and really challenges his students. Best of all - he's really there for the students... caring and always willing to give his insight.
Definately only means for Philosophy Majors.  Do not take without at least a BA in philosophy.
Awesome teacher, just make sure you do the homework,; if you miss just one, he fails you.

Does not make expectations clear. Disorganized class run by TAs. Professor hardly showed their face the whole semester except at the end to terrorize students who had any questions about the highly disorganized, mistake ridden and confusing post labs.

Her lab course was often disorganized, as were her exams and post-lab questions. When I asked her questions in class, she was often abrasive, impatient, and unapproachable. Would not take a course taught by her again.

She was super disorganized and unclear about grading. She didn't give our course grades until more than two weeks after the final exam and took several months to grade a one page essay. She kept giving us the wrong instructions and then getting really mad when our data was unusable, and she also managed to kill all of our worm plates.
rating_tags: Get ready to read--Lots of homework

comment: Her lecture is somehow disorganized. But she is a very approachable professor. Took genetics, dev bio and Evolution with her and definitely recommend Evolution. She'd like to discuss the concepts taught in-class and materials beyond the class with the students. She also provided lots of useful resources when I wrote my evolution term paper.

Didnt submit my final grade in a timely manner and almost prevented my graduation. She was very disorganized throughout her class and became more so after the Covid-19 pandemic. She doesnt respond to emails.
so unorganized and seems like she does not know what she is talking about

Really chill and approachable. Understood that experiments sometimes didn't work out, so she changed the lab write-ups to focus on concepts and scientific literature. Willing to try out new teaching/evaluation methods (i.e. end-of-year project).
She is a very approachable professor. She is fun and carefree. She cares about learning her student's names and making everyone's life relatively easy with respect to workload.

Okay, had such a horrible time in this class and learned nothing from it! THE CLASS IS SO BAD THAT I WANT THE TEACHER TO JUST RETIRE ALREADY. so many suffer all because the class is so badly organized. everything we do is so pointless. homework is dumb. worst class in the CS department

I know if I type "WORST CLASS EVER" then you won't take me seriously.  But seriously.  WORST CLASS EVER.  Sometimes that's all you can say.  But it's required for CS so all you can do is read this and be unhappy.
terrible lecturer, 80 problem homework assignments. lectures are worthless and exams are insane. do not take 600.333 with masson unless you have to!
taking it now. can't teach. don't inspire. waste of my summer money
possibly the worst class i've ever taken! this would be the kind of class you take absolutely because you have to. the prof absolutely can't teach.

Worst teacher I have ever had. Class is a waste of my time and the homework assignments are not related to class discussion at all. No grades matter but two tests which are impossible. Having to take this class made me hate Hopkins CS Dept. Test average was a 46, have fun guessing.
His classes are boring. Lectures arent much help either. Amount of attention kids are paying to him is miniscule
No Comments

Had him for Medieval Cities, which is really his thing.  Lectures were interesting, got a bit of everything and he's passionate about it and it makes you want to take it in.  Not stodgy or lame,papers are medium challenging, homework is just reading, usually pretty interesting.  He isn't too happy when people don't participate in discussions though

Has reputation at JHU (even outside of the department) for leveling severe accusations of plagiarism, and almost always are completely unfounded.  Readings are irrelevant to course and unnecessary toward the final grade.  Ask him about the Red Sox.
Very interesting lectures!

Great teacher!. Always happy to answer questions and stay after class to talk. Remember students who care, I sat in a different spot one class and when I raised my hand to ask a question he said " O there you are". He really cares about his field and will look up extra material for you on any particular subject if you ask!

INCREDIBLE lecturer--passionate, clear and very well organized. Wonderful to visit one-on-one--will answer any question you have and is open to discussion in many subject matters. One of those rare professors who actually gives a damn about his students, not matter their field.

Worst professor I've had at Hopkins. He did not review literature before discussing it with us and was blatantly wrong with some if his ideas and statements. His questions are designed to trick you and his attitude discourages people from participating. I was interested in medieval history before taking his class, but I really learned nothing.

Gardner's class is great if you're interested in history at all.  His paper topics are fairly easy and your grade basically depends on how nice your TA is.    The final was a complete breeze.  He pretty much recycled questions from quizzes.  He wants his students to do well so he will make every effort to make the course easy, but also useful.
No Comments

Reasonable workload + generous grading! An (extremely) easy A, but also an interesting class. I learned so much I was ignorant of before about African history. Professor Larson works hard to ensure that generalizations and popular fallacies about Africa are destroyed/corrected in his class. Nerdy, but kind. Great TA!
rating_tags: ACCESSIBLE OUTSIDE CLASS--Clear grading criteria--Would take again

comment: one of the best profs at Hopkins, very fair, clear, and accessible. great teacher
AWESOME guy. Knows his stuff.. interesting in general also. Just go to lecture. Notes are important for the midterm and finals which are usually 2 essays for each.
Very nice man and really takes an interest in his students.
Easygoing prof, knows his stuff. He has high expectations & assigns alot to read. I enjoyed the discussions. Fair amount of work but well worth it. I learned a lot about the Indian Ocean!
No Comments
the subject is interesting, but the lecture is kinda boring. there's a lot of reading, and response papers every week. prof. larson is a great guy, but the class makes people so sleepy and bored.
Great guy, very nice, grew up in Madagascar. Extremely helpful and cheery. His lectures were interesting too. Overall a great teacher.

Had a horrible experience with Dr. Smithling. He sure knows his math, but I believe that's also his downfall. He explains content quickly and in ways that expect you to already have the majority of the content down prior to coming to class. He is not very caring and will in fact increase the workload when you're at your worst. No accent though!
rating_tags: Lots of homework--Skip class? You won't pass.--Test heavy

comment: Brian is one of the best professors in the math department. While calculus may be difficult at a college level, Brian is the best prof to have for this class. His lectures are clear as long as you stay engaged and take good notes. Confusing topics can be learned outside of class using the textbook.

Brian is an extremely difficult professor. His lectures do get easier to understand as the semester goes on, but his exams are always extremely hard. If you are not good at math, I would not recommend taking his class because you will most likely struggle terribly. If you easily understand math concepts, this class is for you.

Brian's a great professor and super easy to talk to. His lectures are overwhelming at FIRST but he explains complicated things in very easy to understand ways. The backtests he provides are extremely useful and his exams are fair. The exam averages for his class are low but THERE'S A HUGE CURVE (if you average a low B, you'll get an A).
rating_tags: ACCESSIBLE OUTSIDE CLASS--TEST HEAVY--GRADED BY FEW THINGS

comment: While initially "Brian" made Calc1 seem very confusing with his use of math jargon and symbols. It becomes easier to get used to them and see that he has very well planned and organized lectures laid out. He without a doubt knows the topic like the back of his hand and is easy to talk to outside of class. Somewhat hard class but not impossible.
rating_tags: LOTS OF HOMEWORK--Clear grading criteria--Amazing lectures

comment: Brian was an engaging and energetic professor. However, I will say that it is very necessary to read out of the textbook and make sure you understand the homework problems. He provides plenty of backtests that were very helpful if you complete before exams. You have to study if you want to pass, but overall, it was a rewarding experience for me.
rating_tags: Tough Grader--LOTS OF HOMEWORK--ACCESSIBLE OUTSIDE CLASS

comment: Initially, I loved Brian. He's an energetic and engaging lecturer. However, his class (Calc I) was a disappointment every other level. The HW problems were questionably chosen, the TA was awful, and Brian missed multiple lectures which had ABYSMAL substitutes. Tack on poorly designed exams and the class has become my least favorite ever.
rating_tags: LOTS OF HOMEWORK--GRADED BY FEW THINGS--Amazing lectures

comment: Brian (we call him Brian) is AWESOME. He's sarcastic and encouraging and, best of all, actively disavows math that he doesn't think we need to know. In his words, "I hate partial fractions, so there's no way I'm going to make you do them." It's not an easy class, but it's one in which you want to go to each and every lecture just to hear Brian!

I took his Reintroduction To Writing course this year, and I absolutely loved it. Professor Oppel is hilarious, and an amazing lecturer. He always cares about how his students are doing, and the essays you do in the course are quite interesting and easy to do, if you follow his structure. He inspired me to continue writing; I recommend this course!

Prof. Oppel's class was amazing! He has really good taste for assigned readings, making them less of a chore to read. I have to say that Prof. Oppel really transformed my writing. He does a really good job sitting down with you to revise your work. There was some anxiety around grading, but it worked out in the end! Would definitely recommend him!
rating_tags: Gives good feedback--Get ready to read--Tough grader

comment: Politics and Violence with Oppel is a fun class and highly informative if you are interested in the realm of political science. He gives interesting reading material (a lot of it) and your grade is based on 3 essays. In my opinion, the grading was quite fair, but it can seem a little harsh if you're a premed or care deeply about your GPA.
rating_tags: Get ready to read--Graded by few things--Amazing lectures

comment: He's a tough grader and when you have meetings, he'll tell you a specific list of things he wants fixed. You'll fix them, turn in the final, and he'll point out that you got a B because of something he never mentioned in the first conference! Thats the most annoying part of class. Expos is a joke and there are easier classes out there; find them.

Best teacher I've had. He is entertaining, intelligent and everything you can ask for. Classes are riveting and engaging, and he genuinely cares about his students. He'll take time out of his day to sit down with you for as long as you need. He engages students in intellectual conversations and makes you think on another level. Take his classes!

Best professor I've had at Hopkins. Genuinely cares about his students and really improves your writing. Writes really helpful feedback. Class is not little work - 4 essays (each at least 8 pages) based on sources, but is definitely worth it if you enjoy writing and are interested in the subject. Professor Oppel's feedback transforms your writing!

Great writing professor. He knows precisely how to help you improve overall in writing essays, and his conferences are extremely helpful. Grading can be tough, but not extremely so, and he does take into account improvements in essays. Put in the effort and you should do fairly well.

Had him for expository writing - crystal clear presentation, very humorous - but hard grading. Even if you think you wrote the best essay of your life ever, you'll get a B+. His conferences are awesome though - he has the gift of seeing things in your essay which you thought weren't there, and showing you what's wrong with your essay.

Professor Bevan makes Thermo, an otherwise boring topic, interesting.  His dry sense of humor always seems to make the class laugh.  The course itself is relatively difficult and relies a lot on test grades, but he is a fair grader and seems to genuinely care about how the students are performing in class.

Professor Bevan consistently inspires me to pursue thermodynamics. His in-depth knowledge of the field, desire to help students, and passion for teaching all contributed to him being one of the best professors I have ever had.
Bevan is unquestionably the worst instructor I have had in my life. His lectures are useless, provides absolutely no feedback on assignments, and makes it a pain to ask for outside help
This class was uninspiring and even though I wanted to love the subject, it really didn't happen!

The Worst Professor ever. I pity the students who take this course. The classes seemed like an exercise in proving that he knew much more than the class. I don't think this is the point of teaching a course.
I hated this class. His Exams have nothing to do with the HW. Doesn't answer a question; infact talks about everything else and makes me wonder if he knows anything about thermodynamics

He's a nice guy, but Bevan is the worst professor I have ever had. The only thing you do in thermo is solve problems, yet he did not do a single example the entire semester. He just shows a PPT full of  useless equations. The HWs are required, yet his tests include material not in the HW.  He didn't give an actual answer to ANY question asked.

Bevan is  really nice, laid back, & organized. However, he insists on using PP, his hws can be ridiculous. Exams are unrelated to lectures. He wants you to learn the theory of thermo, so he fails to teach you how to solve problems, which make up exams and hws. He'll get better over time, but isn't quite there yet. You'll have to teach yourself.
really dry lectures. no one comes to class and the assigned reading is absurd. sometimes he assigns a full book as 1 night of homework. his lectures consist of reading from pages.
rating_tags: Tough Grader--Get ready to read--LOTS OF HOMEWORK

comment: Katz does not take the time to invest in this class at all, he comes in reads an essay in a monotone for 50 minutes and leaves. Grades only the papers, which even then he does not do- he will give rude and insulting comments attacking the students in ways which a professional and professor in an academic institution should never do:1 word-tenure.
Professor Katz has a wry sense of humor, and is very approachable outside of class.   Don't expect to be "mothered" though. You'll learn a lot from him.

Prof. comes to class, tells a bad joke then reads a 10 page essay and leaves. Not very concerned with how much information students absorb in the class. Exam questions can include obscure references to readings on syllabus not discussed in class.
Class makes no sense
Class makes no sense. No one shows up. No sense of humor. Boring.
lectures unclear and messy. exams are alright though. professor REALLY dry

Immpossible to take notes.  Exams are way too difficult.  half the class doesn't even show up to lectures.  the reading is way too much. around 1700 pages for the semester of confusing and redundant information.

Honors Lin Alg is way too fast paced. After drop period ended, prof doubled workload and difficulty, which threw me out of control. Although he is caring, his explanations are very confusing. Homework is very hard and lengthy, although participation credit is given. Tests (besides the final) are oral, and grading isn't that harsh -- TOO MUCH WORK.
rating_tags: Get ready to read--Lots of homework--Caring

comment: People got sick, needed medication & therapy. If you're not willing to take Cs in other classes don't take with this prof. Stuffs 2x amt of material as other profs' HLA. Don't take if don't have >30hr/wk. "Flipped classrm" but pretty much correspondence course, expected to learn from txtbk but in class doesn't answer your Qs, answers his own Qs
rating_tags: Tough grader--Get ready to read--Lots of homework

comment: I can not begin to describe the amount of torture this professor put the class through. Let's clarify: he has a great personality and I believe he is a great person outside of academics. But he can not teach. The way he goes about the class is redundant and you'll have more luck watching the organic chemistry tutor than whatever happens there.

Absolutely atrocious professor and class. I and many have taken and passed AP Calc BC/Calc 3 and still suffered in this class. His lectures are confusing/disorganized, and projects are worth so much that if your TA is a harsh grader you're screwed. The final was also ridiculous. Save your time and take a class that doesn't make you want to die

Loves to make his quizzes and exams difficult, then adds a strange curve later. I took Calc 2, only had the option on here to put some other class. Some of the questions on the final had us laughing at how difficult they were, and required a very complicated curve that gave some students 25% back and others near to nothing.

The class with some TAs that don't know calculus any better than the students do. My problems: practice exams don't represent actual exams, final exams have difficulty much worse than previously, and grading metrics on practice material that is consistently incorrect.

Makes topics way harder than they needed to be. Instead of learning formulas, he expects you to derive all of the simple equations the textbook gives you. People stopped attending lectures, and I can see why. I would end up more confused than when I went in. I started just reading the textbook, which was more informative than professor Sakellaridis

This class definitely was substantially more difficult than Calc 1. That said, the class was still fair too, I didn't feel like I was always being cheated out of my grades. The homeworks also do take a while and you may need to learn from the textbook, but he does a good job lecturing! He's a tough yet fair professor
rating_tags: Tough grader--Get ready to read--Group projects

comment: Lectures were not very helpful and most students stopped attending after a month. The quizzes were fairly difficult in comparison to calc 1, and homeworks can take a while. Not crazy difficult but you will probably need to learn some of the material on your own time to fully understand.
Lots of very substantive material, but the professor is a good lecturer and takes the time to make sure everyone understands the content covered. Heavily logic- and proof-based.
rating_tags: Get ready to read--Caring--Accessible outside class

comment: A ridiculous amount of both reading and participation. If you have a lot of time to dedicate go ahead, if not pick a different professor.
rating_tags: Get ready to read--Group projects--So many papers

comment: Amazing professor. Dr. Selbie responds very quickly to any emails and provides a ton of valuable feedback in case students needs any help. A lot of research articles to read, leading to weekly discussions. A couple of group projects and few quizzes with a final exam. I would highly recommend taking her class if you want to learn Cell Bio.
rating_tags: Gives good feedback--Get ready to read--Participation matters

comment: Makes you work for it! Wants perfect answers after a lot of reading and research. But if you've put in the effort, the exams can be cracked. Perfectionist. But this course makes sure that you learn a lot!
rating_tags: Gives good feedback--Get ready to read--Participation matters

comment: Would recommend taking this teacher for Cell Biology at Hopkins. Was good class
rating_tags: Lots of homework--Get ready to read--So many papers

comment: Dr Selbie was an excellent teacher who stressed critical reasoning skills and problem solving, rather than rote memorization and regurgitation. All the tests where open-book, gave partial credit on the multiple choice, and was very fair in the grading. Yes there is lots of reading, projects & quizzes/tests, but if you want to learn Biology take her
rating_tags: Get ready to read--Group projects--So many papers

comment: This class is based heavily on weekly discussions and group projects. The midterm and final are take home, essay based exams. There is quite a bit of work required in this class. Memorization is required but using the textbook for quizzes and exams are crucial. This class also focuses a lot on experiments. An A is possible but needs a lot work.

Dr. Selbie is very personable 1:1. That approachability sort of stops in class though. The group projects are pointless papers and there is no accountability. The lectures are dense and boring. The book graphics are designed by amateurs. I struggled through this class because it was so uninspiring, and classically dull.
rating_tags: Tough Grader--Get ready to read--GROUP PROJECTS

comment: Probably the best professor I have ever had! Took Stem Cell and Advanced Cell Biology with Selbie - very good problem solving assignments, good overviews of material (rather than worthless memorization) and group assignments help you learn the material. I would recommend her for the JHU Biotechnology program!
rating_tags: Gives good feedback--Respected--Get ready to read

comment: Most people hate Dr. Rodgers because they are accustomed to rigorous, by-the-book biochemistry problems. He will make you think on your feet. You can't look up problems online. Highly recommended, if you are interested in learning how to think about biochem in a pragmatic (read: industry-ready) way.

His problem sets are hard but once you do them all, you will never forget biochemistry! He is very approachable & a good teacher. I was always bad at biochem and put it in the same category as orgo, but after taking his class, I changed for the better and am no longer scared of the subject.. all thanks to the problem sets that cleared many concepts

If it is your first time taking any type of biochemistry class, I would suggest getting a tutor or someone else to help you.  Luckily, I have taken a biochemistry class before, but if I hadn't I'm certain I would feel very lost.  He is a good lecturer and excited about the material but his class is not for the faint of heart.  You will work hard.
He was a good teacher but his teaching style is mostly based on his notes.
His homework questions are very tough. I found out that the questions he asked were not related to what he taught in the class. He is not helpful at all

Not a very good teacher. Knows his information, but expect you to know it, too, without him needing to explain. Do not bother readng the book thinking it will prepare you for class. I basically passed this class with help from my Post Doc friends.

Expects masters candidates to have the knowledge of postdocs, covers things that aren't in the book (if you need clarification, you're screwed), just generally unrealistic expectations, and you won't really learn anything except how to do certain homework questions.

I like Prof. Wang?s style of teaching, attempting to engage the whole lecture with questions, which I am sure is very difficult. There were some issues with midterm, but she has little to no control over some of this system. There are some of us who hold her in very high esteem.

Wang is a horrible instructor and lecturer. She doesn't know the material she teaches (she thought that the Democrats never supported unions)!She completely messed up midterm grades and everyone had to submit their tests for regrades. We got our first grade 4 weeks before the end of the semester! She has no business teaching an introductory course.

I took her intro to comperative politics in spring 2010 and honestly it is one of the worst taught classes I have ever taken. Her lectures sound like she just googles basic info about a country and reads it aloud to the class.

Worst class I have taken at Hopkins thus far.  Wang does not know how to teach a class, let alone one with 120 students.  Do not, I repeat, DO NOT take this course with Wang.  You will be sorry if you do. This course is the worst excuse of a class offered here at Hopkins.  There are way too many textbooks for the class too, costing over $200 used.

Worst class ever. Have learned nothing. As a new professor she teaches like a TA and attempts to lead a discussion with a group of 200 people. It wastes time and makes it look like she is covering up a lack of knowledge by firing questions to the students. She did not have the TAs grade the tests fairly so everyone must have their test regraded!

I took ICP for spring 2010. I will never ever take her class again in my life. Level of difficulty is extremely high considering it is an introductory course. It doesnt make sense to have the class so difficult. I hear 6/9 people failed for midterm in one section.
Juan is very intelligent and enthusiastic.  Hopkins is lucky to have her!

I took DiffEq and Calc II w him. Most def my favorite professor at Hopkins!! N by far the best Math prof in this school! He is absolutely AWESOME! He is a really good teacher and you know what to expect for exams. He's a really cool guy too and his personality comes through in his teaching. If you can take any of your courses with him -- do it! =)
awesome

Salch is a really special person. He is in academia not to accumulate awards or accrue status, nor because he likes punishing unsuspecting undergraduates. He does math research because he enjoys solving problems. This kind of person is far too rare these days in higher ed. I suspect he will do great things in mathematics.  -N.O.

This guy is hilarious!!! He always seems really friendly and is good about answering questions. He really seemed like he wanted everyone to learn the material. Probably one of my favorite professors that semester.

Solid teacher. He can connect with the kids because he kinda is one. Has big gauges in his ears and is tatted up from head to toe but hes the man. Fun and easy class if you do all the work which is not much.
Amazing. So so so nice and helpful! He is really easy too, so don't hesitate to join his class :)

What a wonderful professor. He always stopped to answer EVERY question in a huge lecture, and explained things well and often. Always stayed after class to answer more questions. Very nice and I never fell asleep in his class because he kept things moving, and his voice wasnt monotonous. he was great, esp. for his 1st yr at jhu.

Honestly the worst professor I've ever had. Extremely rude/disrespectful, especially with emails or feedback. He expects 100 pages read before each class. There are many essays with very short deadlines. Don't send him an email. It takes him at least 2-3 days to respond (after the due date) and it will be a sarcastic remark.
rating_tags: Tough grader--Lots of homework--So many papers

comment: I has certain expectations for short stories and poems.

Dr. Hubbell is super understanding towards your situation as students. As an example, we once thought that the grading was harsh, after talking with him about it, he almost immediately listen to our voice and change grading criteria. Super reasonable and nice instructor with respectable personality and great teaching skill to really make you learn!
Dr. Hubbell is a really nice instructor who asks you to call him by his name (though I still stick to Dr. Hubbell haha)

comment: I take his class for writing workshop in mica, hes really chill and give us really high credits.

Tony is the reason why I decided to be an English major.  Love him!
Totally challenging and well worth being challenged by.  Whoever said he's boring is probably bitter because he pushed them outside their comfort zone.

He rocks
His class is very boring.
Ignore those 1 point ratings. If you really want to learn something please take Professor Han's class. The class is not so easy but you DO learn a lot of things in this class.
Lectures aren't necessary since he reads straight from the textbook and is hard to follow. PaulsOnlineNotes are a necessity to do well since you won't learn much from class alone.
Hes honestly not that bad. Had a generous curveprob half the class get an A. Nice choice if you dont wanna show up for classes while maintaining your gpa I guess lol.

Really hard to understand. He holds his office hours when everyone has class. Also discouraging to his students in general. Ive had bad professors before, but he is seriously the worst. Do not recommend having him as a teacher at all.

comment: Don't take him. Pretty much no one can understand him and good luck trying to go to his office hours (which is right after the lecture, right when most people have other classes to go to). Grading is based on your rank in the class, and he lets you know (reminding you how difficult/impossible it is to get an A in the class). 1st midterm avg  50%

Practice tests were exactly like the real thing, just with different equations. That's about the only good thing about Prof. Han's class. I couldn't understand him and he refused to write in anything except for math notation on the board. His examples were less than helpful. Just skip class and study in the library instead.
The textbook is more helpful than the lectures.
rating_tags: Graded by few things--Test heavy--Tough grader

comment: Professor Daniel gives great lectures. He's very personable and available for questions outside of class. Lots of reading, a play a week, so block off a few hours on Saturday or Sunday morning, get an audiobook on Youtube, and make sure you read before class because lectures definitely assume you know the basic plot.
rating_tags: Get ready to read--Skip class? You won't pass.--Lecture heavy

comment: Drew Daniel is one of the most brilliant and interesting professors i've ever had. He's somewhat eccentric and I feel that he's gotten even weirder as the years have passed, but I love his courses anyway. He's one of those people for whom you immediately know you're in presence of something special, and I'd recommend anyone take a course with him.
Prof. Daniel holds high expectations and is a fair grader and interesting lecturer.
Super interesting lectures. Seems like a great guy. Class calls for a lot of reading, but the exams aren't too difficult if you study. I would absolutely recommend this class and this professor!
Very smart and funny. Sometimes too smart.

very good and engaging lecturer, so fun to talk with, always willing to help. must read a shakespearean play a week, so keep up with your reading. his ideas are clear and well-explained. thoroughly enjoyed this class!
No Comments

Gem of a professor who cares about students' well-being. Learned more chem here than in other science classes, and topics were very intriuging! According to Hedy, the future class replacing this one will be more design-heavy. For tests, be sure to read the PDF notes thouroughly and listen in class versus relying on lecture videos and the textbook.

Most important class I took as this class built a foundation for the other engineering classes I took. Hedy is a great professor and really cares that you learn. He's easy to approach and gives really great lectures--but you must do your part.
rating_tags: Gives good feedback--Get ready to read--ACCESSIBLE OUTSIDE CLASS

comment: Hedy is knowledgeable, attentive professor toward his students, and a good and caring mentor.  You definitely have to put you effort in class to succeed.  He us a fair grader, yet, expect earnest effort.  He will let you know if your performance is subpar.  Good professor!
rating_tags: Gives good feedback--Get ready to read--Clear grading criteria

comment: Hedy is my favorite professor here at Hopkins. He's extremely caring, and on top of that, an amazing professor. EnvE is a lot of tough work, and he always makes sure that his students understand the material.

Although EnvE is a lot of work, Hedy is a great professor for the course. He's so funny, easygoing, and really cares about his students. He always greets his students when they come in ("Hello,  I missed you!" or "How are you doing?"). He makes sure his students are paying attention and truly cares that they are getting a good education.
Dr. Alavi is very knowledgeable and helpful. Though, to have a good grade, you need to do your part.

Hedy is wonderful with Intro to Environmental Engineering. Definitely more work than I anticipated but he definitely just wants you to be interested and learn the overall concepts not the equations and numbers. Great class when you stay awake...

Highly recommend this prof! Interesting class, makes lots of dad jokes and shows interesting nature documentaries as well as some goofy animal vids for morale. Not very fast when it comes to grading or responding to emails, but overall a really good guy.
Awesome professor! Such a nice guy. Not the quickest grader.

Hilgartner is a fantastic guy and professor.  He cares about his students and the material.  Very friendly, easy to talk to and understanding.  I would most certainly recommend him. If you work hard in his class and communicate with him when you need help you will  get an A.  He's awesome.

Was incorrect about several topics, used poor language in tests, and clearly never checked his assignments. Do not expect him to respond to you by email ever, or to receive your readings on time.  Plus side: Tells "Dad Jokes" all the time and plays videosmovies often.

YES YES YES. Had him for biodiversity. Open note midterm and final and he only tests on what he writes on the board. Homework is a piece of cake. Lectures are great because he talks for max 30 minutes and then plays nature documentaries, and he's really smart and can answer any question. Took it two years ago and I still remember stuff I learned!
He is not the fastest at getting back to you via e-mail, etc., but he is a really good professor!
Bill is a serious teacher.  Always willing to help. Very knowledgeable about his subject. his tests are HARD, but if you study hard, you will do well. be prepared to take lots of notes!
Amazing, very clear, very passionate about what he teaches. A great guy, also quite funny.
Nice. Conversations with the Earth was easy. Guided Tour of the Planets was harder than expected.
Freshman Seminar: Conversation with the Earth.

The class was Conversations with Earth, a freshmen seminar. Mostly, I never got to hear the professor lecture. He left it to TAs and guest speakers, but when he did come in, he was enthusiastic. He made sure everyone understood the material and he added humor to it. He really did try hard in his lectures. He's very approachable and friendly.
No Comments
This guy is pretty funny and makes the best of dry material.
Very nice, but dry....
I hate physics.  But the professor is okay, bland though listening to the voice for a whole semester.  Doesn't help since the material is pretty hard.

He isn't interested in the students and does not explain things clearly.  Much learning will be done out of the book.  His test grading schemes are weird and you end up losing too many points if you don't write EXACTLY what he wants.  Also he would not grant me an extension when I had to miss a test to go to a funeral.  Just not a good experience

His exams are difficult but fair. Knowall the questions portion of the book (not the practice) and checkpoints. Thats what all his exams are. And major concepts and you will do fine. Lecture isn't a must and review sessions are pointless.
Good class.  Very clear.
Made a tough Intro Physics class as interesting and as clear as it could be made.

Its hard to give a good, 1.5 hour physics lecture, but he seems to do a pretty good job of it.  Lectures are clear and will usually help you understand the material (though you can do fine even if you dont attend).  Tests are very conceptual, which I like
Good lecturer, manages to keep students' attention on a boring subject for a 1.5 hour lecture. Approachable and much more helpful than the foriegn speaking TAs.
awesome TA
Great guy!

He's not brilliant, and he used a lot of formal approaches in a basic linear algebra class. Other schools don't use nearly as much formalism in linear algebra. He was immature, emotional, poorly organized, and uninterested in student success.

Best TA any of us had ever had. Absolutely brilliant, to the point where he could always find a concise way of explaining things that would make sense to you. Very friendly, always willing to help. The absolute best.
Best TA I've ever had.

His lectures were very unclear because he skips steps and doesn't define all of his concepts. His subsequent clarifications don't help much. He also lectured out of the assigned textbook a fair amount, so it was difficult to clarify unclear points. As an older student, I felt some discrimination by the teacher. Very immature. Hyper.

He almost never uses the assigned textbook which includes a lot of linear algebra applications, but instead uses formal proofs drawn from other textbooks. His lectures jump around from point to point, so it's difficult to follow the logic of the proof. He doesn't return homework in a timely manner and is very unhelpful outside of class.
Would highly recommend taking AS 410.602 with Dr. Hollier.
rating_tags: Group projects--Clear grading criteria--Accessible outside class

comment: Dr Hollier is a great teacher. The Molecular biology course covers a lot of information. His course materials are detailed and sufficient to learn what you need without buying the textbook. He responds to emails quickly, grades quickly, and understands when life happens if you need an extension. Work is structured consistently each week.
He is helpful, but the quizzes are based on the notes and lectures. It can be a lot, but he is willing to speak with you.
rating_tags: Tough grader--Get ready to read--Accessible outside class

comment: The class has weekly lectures, multiple choice exams, and essays. Multiple choice is 10 questions (5 true/false responses each). Essay is 1-3 questions, and his grading is fair. His extension policy is forgiving. In addition, he has a journal assignment about every other week which is fun. Read his transcripts VERY thoroughly prior to the exam.

This class has two different grading options which is great for those who aren't strong test takers AND for those who are and would rather avoid busy work. The only thing I didn't like about the class was the that grammar and spelling errors in the tests made for unnecessary confusion. Emails were replied to, but not always read before doing.

Highly recommend this Professor. Work is spread equally through the semester with weekly tests. Expect to work on this course each week. Tests cover 1-2 chapters. Make sure you post your journal assignments in the correct time frame or you will get a zero for that part. Grading criteria is clear & feedback is good. His extension policy is amazing.

Take this professor. Sure there's a lot of busy work and tons of material, he covers everything you need and is very compassionate towards working students who are full time employed. Lectures are 2 hours long, but he provides transcripts too which are amazing resources to have and read over. Definitely suggest him. Grading is very fair & generous.
awful teaching, easy materials

Teaching Accident and Discriminating Graduate Students.
He did not monitor the midterm well, so he asked all grad students to retake it. He also congrats to the undergrads for their good work.
Terrible teaching
very hard to follow in lectures. hard to understand the homework questions.
Lectures are difficult to follow. Tests are easy enough but showing up to class is a waste of your time.

Easy for an upper level AMS course, but his lectures are hard to follow and not necessary to succeed in the course. Both tests are used to test basic coding comprehension rather than material from the course. His office hours aren't very helpful since he is condescending to students struggling to learn concepts.

Due to online class behavior, the lectures are not as excited as they could be as if we were learning in a real classroom. However, the materials are quite comprehensive and easy to digest if you really dig in some time into them.
Extremely boring lectures
Very good professor

He was kinda funny, but I had trouble understanding him and he would constantly gloss over topics from Calc I expecting us to have them mastered and he'd just say "long story short" and skip to the next part of the problem.
rating_tags: Lecture heavy--Graded by few things--Accessible outside class

comment: Couldn't understand dude. Like at all. Seems like a decent fellow but has no business teaching (in English anyways).

His lectures were often confusing, and I often did not follow what was going on. Doing homework and asking questions helps with understanding. His midterms are on the easier side in that they are exactly like all the homework problems. Additionally, he always posted his lecture material and homework solutions etc. online, which is very helpful.
Super nice guy and always very helpful during office hours. Calc III is a hard class but the lectures were pretty clear and HW/quizzes were at a reasonable level

Very down to earth and approachable guy but lectures can be quite difficult to understand at times. Reading textbook before lectures was very helpful in understanding lectures better. Homework difficulty/quantity was very reasonable. Exams/Quizzes are easy and heavily based on previous HW/examples/quizzes. You can also drop 2 lowest quiz/HW scores.

Lectures were proof heavy but the tests were all caluation heavy. I learned mostly from the textbook and homeworks. Grading also took a while to come in so you didn't know your grade until the very end of the course
This is definitely not worth your time. He never responds to emails, doesn't give feedback, and doesn't teach. By far the worst professor I've had during grad school.

If you can, please avoid this instructor. His resources are pretty much outdated and you will have hard time to find your answers for HW, Quiz, Exam. His lecture is useless, it's all powerpoint and pdf file; most importantly, you can just google the content pretty much. He ignored questions and no feedback on anything. 
DO NOT WASTE YOUR MONEY!!
This man probably spends 5 minutes per week remembering this class exists. Thatll be $5000 please - Johns Hopkins
$5000 for pdf lectures, homework and tests with outdated websites and info, terrible English, and takes forever to reply to emails, if at all.

Easy A, but not worth $4k, given how little you learn. Rahman puts in 0 effort. No lecture - just hands out pdfs/powerpoints written in poor English. Could get same education from youtube vids. JHU online classes have mandatory discussion forums. Rahman does not lead them or participate. No feedback on grades; seems to all be completion based.
Homeworks every week and a big project every 3-4 weeks. Easy grader too
rating_tags: Participation matters--LOTS OF HOMEWORK--Clear grading criteria

comment: Uninspiring. Very little feedback. Questions are answered with the minimal words possible. Dates for assignments are changed without notification. Assignments are not graded in a timely manner. Lectures are unclear and do not have enough detail to explain subject.

Unfortunately, Professor Riehl is not very nice when it comes to accommodations. She can be really mean sometimes and her tone can be quite rude. It seems like she treats some students really well and some students really poorly in an arbitrary fashion.
I LOVE U EMILY RIEHL

She focuses on concepts and really genuinely wants students to understand. She is super understanding and met with me when I was considering dropping the class and convinced me to stick it out, which worked out well.

Emily Riehl is a true genius, and perhaps one one of the most intelligent professor's I've ever had. She is inclusive and kind, and really likable. However, she is fluent in math, which makes it extremely difficult, especially for freshman/non-math majors who are not. Study well and make sure you understand what you are doing, not just how to do it

She is brilliant and hilarious--this Calc III opened my mind to think about math and how the world works in so many new ways without consuming my life.  Also, she's a really reassuring grader (on tests: "don't worry about showing all your work, just show what you know"), and she has great shoes. Challenges your brain, but makes it easy to get an A.
Definitely a memorable class. She is awesome.
Incredibly accessible and warm. Her lectures are very conceptual - depending on what kind of thinker you are, this might affect your understanding of the class.
