comment: Emily does a great job with Calc III. Normally a subject that has a horrible reputation, she has made it accessible for us to learn and, while the problem sets are challenging, the tests are fair and are exactly what you've learned and studied for.
rating_tags: Gives good feedback--Clear grading criteria--Amazing lectures

comment: Good professor but the final was worth a lot in my opinion. Also, the last couple of projects were really difficult and not very reflective of ability
The professor lacks the basic ability in traching
AMAZING. I love her, if you can take a class with her, 100% do it. Amazing lectures, really wants you to understand the material and fair examinations.

I'm not a math person, but Sara made CS231 Automata manageable despite all of the proofs. Don't misunderstand; this wasn't an easy course, but Sara was patient and stayed after her office hours ended to make sure I understood. I stuck with it, and really liked Turning machines and computability by the end of the semester. Cool class!
In Databases, Professor More taught the information very well. She clearly knew her stuff and cared a lot about her students and the fact that they learned.

Professor More explained all of the concepts very well in class and the homeworks were very fair and tested us on all of the things a computer science class should test you on. My only gripe is with the exams in that handwriting code and obscure programming facts take center stage. Is handwriting code still a thing in interviews? I haven't seen it.

Sara is awesome!!! Mom energy, funny, accessible, never condescending. I found her CS220 lectures extremely clear, she is wonderful at answering questions. She guided me through my partner abandoning our team project, and believes in the potential of CS majors that arent Cool Coders Who Already Have Startups. A ray of sunshine in the CS Dept!
A wonderful lecturer who understands both the content and how to teach it.

The class is not easy, but that's true of any university physics course, especially at a school like Hopkins. If you have the right mindset and know how to study, then you can definitely do well in the class even if you struggled with physics in high school. Grading is also curved generously.

Dr Rajendran is a very intelligent scientist which can make it difficult for him to dumb things down for us and explain concepts at a level that we can understand. His handwriting is also basically illegible. Tests are quite doable if you have prior physics experience, but for others they can be very difficult.

just avoid him at all cost. barely anyone goes to his lectures, bc his lectures are mostly useless. tests are extremely difficult, especially if you don't have any prior physics experience. probably the worst way to start learning physics

The lectures and workload are very fast paced and doing the problem sets is crucial. Tests are difficult but TAs are generous with partial credit. If you did well in physics/math in high school you should be fine, but if you have no prior physics experience this class is extremely difficult.
rating_tags: Lots of homework--Get ready to read--Test heavy

comment: Tests are 10x harder than the problem sets that were assigned in our section, which are already pretty hard to begin with. Messy handwriting and lectures are hard to follow, doesn't do any examples/practice problems during lecture but only theoretical stuff and derivations. I have already hated physics since high school and this class didn't help.
Don't take his QM if you have the chance. Problem sets are confusing and not self-explanatory. No syllabus posted until almost the end of the semester.
Michael Williams humiliated my friend in front of the whole class and got away with it. Never even an apology
What a character

Good man. One of the few professors who I can say I would rather give a 50 minute lecture than a 50 minute student-to-teacher interaction. In fact, you couldn't help but keep your mouth shut and watch his three inch dilated pupils bore into your soul while he maniacally laughs at one of his deep metaphysical jokes.
Fantastic. It is obvious that he loves the subject matter, and his lectures are both entertaining and informative.
He is a very good professor. Very knowledgable and enthusiastic. A bit quirky and has missed around 5 lectures.  We had two papers and a final.
No Comments
Very enthusiastic and informative professor. His lectures are lively and helpful for exams and papers.

cannot teach, Is not even confirmed on what he is teaching, and gets confused.
Wants maths to be written exactly how he described, e.g. case where he deducted points: since, 5^6 is equal to 5^3*5^3, but since I didn't write as 5^6, got marks deducted. in what world they both are not the same, I don't know.

This is one of the worst professors to take at JHU. He literally argues with you in office hours and is very heavily penalizing. It's either his way or the highway. Moreover, he is just terribly hard to understand. No practical examples, all theory. What a disaster!
rating_tags: Beware of pop quizzes--Lecture heavy--Tough grader

comment: No grading criteria. Takes off 20 marks just because he couldn't understand your method of solving and won't discuss it with you. Doesn't like being asked questions and is aggravated easily.
rating_tags: Tough Grader--Skip class? You won't pass.--LOTS OF HOMEWORK

comment: He skips over slides and expects you to understand without fully solving equations. He grades hw badly and he expects things he never mentions in class. Dont discuss why he butchered it he'll fight with you and don't bother going to him during office hours, he will degrade you to your grave. Don't take this class. He doesn't teach at all.
rating_tags: Tough Grader--Skip class? You won't pass.--LOTS OF HOMEWORK

comment: Elementary materials. You can take this course online.
rating_tags: Tough Grader--LOTS OF HOMEWORK--Tests are tough

comment: Communication is a major problem. Hold on subject material is dubious
Pl don't waste your precious time by taking this class

He was really disorganized; he'd tell us he'd post something one day, but it wouldn't be up until a day or two later, which was really frustrating for exam study guides. Some of the readings were confusing, and he did a poor job explaining the content. Also, if you're thinking of taking intro soc for the MCAT, it will not help you at all.
rating_tags: Get ready to read--Hilarious--Graded by few things

comment: Professor Calder's lectures are awesome--he always has jokes and examples, brings in his own experiences, gets students to contribute and engage, and invites a ton of guest lecturers from different sub-fields to share their expertise. He also seemed to genuinely enjoy teaching an into-level course, which was super refreshing. Highly recommend!

Prof. Calder is amazing! He has a great way of talking about information and you can really tell that he is passionate about his work. He wants every student to learn and understand and ensures that you do so. Readings are not heavy at all and exams are exactly what he gives on the study guide. Best class ever!

Professor Calder is a phenomenal teacher. He has incredible knowledge of Islam and his lecture-style makes his delivery easy and interesting to follow. His class is one of the best I have taken at Hopkins and has taught me so much more about Islam. He is very accessible and helps those who ask. A great guy and a great class!
rating_tags: Get ready to read--ACCESSIBLE OUTSIDE CLASS--Amazing lectures

comment: Really good addition to JHU. Keep him and have him be tenured before he leaves for another institution. Smart and funny - will teach students more than we could possibly think. Also, very great at explaining concepts and makes us do great analysis. Good job at also controlling echo-chambers. Great assignments that are fun and lots of read/writing.
great teacher quirky youn cool guy very interested in his field super helpful
My new favorite professor at Hopkins. He is so smart and taught me so much! Not to mention he is HOT HOT HOT!

Prof Shore is a very enthusiastic Econ professor, perhaps my favorite econ professor at JHU. His class is hard if one does not pay attention in class and take good notes. The textbook is not too useful/necessary. His exams were hard, but he gave a decent curve, meaning that if you knew about 80% of the material, you'd get an A.
I had him for microtheory and although the class was terribly difficult he was the best teacher I have had at Hopkins hands down.
The class is hard but Professor Shore is the greatest econ professor I've ever had. No joke, awesome. People failed his midterm, but they probably didn't study much. It's Hopkins, it's hard.
Easy class if you have any ability to do math. The professor may go through topics very quickly, but he makes the material very basic to understand.
Doesn't teach the information well and is notorious for giving one of the hardest tests at Hopkins.  His class makes people switch majors.
I had Shore for Micro Theory, and it was the hardest class I've ever taken. He tried to teach, but he was too arrogant.
Awesome professor but hard class.

Took Shuster for Cinema and Philosophy. We watched movies and read philosophy, what more can you ask for in a class? Shuster is very funny and definitely got me to think about things in a new way. He expects a lot from you, though--a paper and a final project, but he grades reasonabely.

Martin is simply the greatest professor I've ever had, really.  He's *extremely* clear and to the point, insightful, and a subtle reader of complicated texts.  I highly suggest taking courses with Martin.

Great class!  Never taken anything quite like it...has sort of strange final project, but class overall is fantastic...good lectures, great readings.  Seems to take an interest in his students, would take again.
Great lectures, funny, but sometimes too philosophical
Great prof, funny.
Other rating is way excessive. But Martin's good and very relaxed.
No Comments

Very chill guy to talk to. The classwork is very straightforward but not boring. The class's grading is very fair and the labs are actually pretty interesting and help with some of the lecture content. Easiest class I've taken at Hopkins so far
He doesn't do anything.

You will never see this man in class after the first day, but the class itself is super easy. Even if you mess up and lose points, you can get them back. Very easy to get an A even if you consistently get 80s on every assignment.

Physics 2 Lab is varies very much by who your TA is, since they solely run the lab. My TA was very helpful with feedback and not very stinge about our lab reflections which made the lab overall much less stressful and more interesting. Some of the labs feel very tedious and long but overall was an interesting time. Lab reflections take an hourish.

Professor Mumford's Physics Lab is pretty dry (I think the 6-9 PM time is a little miserable), but you can't complain much. The class is easy and corresponds pretty well with the lecture content. One-on-one, Professor Mumford is actually really nice and happy to help students.

The course was designed extremely fairly with lots of chances to improve/ redeem yourself. The actual labs were really fun and engaging. I was dreading this lab, but wound up really enjoying it. TAs also super helpful.
rating_tags: Gives good feedback--Accessible outside class--Clear grading criteria

comment: He's fantastic!

There are weekly discussions you need to participate in, 3 exams, and 3 problems sets along with 1 paper. the workload is generally manageable, but you will spend a lot of time on the problems sets. Her lectures are very good. she DOES NOT respond to emails in a timely manner, typically taking 7-15 days so good luck if you need a quick response.
Awesome professor would take take them again.
rating_tags: Get ready to read--Clear grading criteria--Respected

comment: The material isn't hard. Three weeks in a row, the lectures failed to be published and unfortunately the professor rarely checks email/Canvas it seems. Fortunately, she was accommodating. Doesn't include rubrics in her grading on Canvas. Slow grader. I use my undergrad biochem lectures vs what JHU provides, but the text and supplementals are ok.

Dr. Das is no longer at JHU (i think) but her biochemistry course was an easy A. all of the questions are online. She gives feedback - but not on all assignments - just the first post and your midterm paper. She gives feedback only when it matters most. She is somewhat responsive but will definitely give you resources.

Very easy to get full credit in this class if you're willing to utilize external resources. A decent amount of the tested material is from the textbooks, which is annoying to flip through. The lectures are ok, not great. If you want to actually learn the material then you will need a significant amount of self study.

Loved this class. Dr. Satarupa Das is so good at teaching. She provided .ppt's (with her own narration + copies of the .ppts with separate text transcripts), many websites with videos and interactive info, answered my questions quickly/thoroughly, was organized, prepared, and stayed on topic. Wish I could clone her for all my classes.
rating_tags: Skip class? You won't pass.--Clear grading criteria--Amazing lectures

comment: Really solid choice for Biochem. Very straight forward class and very manageable work load. Expects weekly discussion participation, but it's difficult to achieve. Lectures cover whats expected on HW and exams and no surprises there. Definitely recommend.

she really cares about her students and is one of the best math lecturers ive had at jhu. you need to attend all the lectures and actively ask questions to get the best grade you can, especially with a math class at hopkins. the more you participate, the more she helps you, and the better you do in the class.

The group projects aren't so bad - they are mostly there to balance your inevitably low quiz scores (4 quizzes + final). Just make sure to read the criteria. Especially pay attention to target audience and writing style. It feels like an English assignment rather than a math assignment. Also go to OH and learning den. They are extremely useful.
rating_tags: Group projects--Lots of homework--Accessible outside class

comment: Her voice strikes discordant harmonies within my brain. Lectures mostly consist of beating dead horses, and the grading system is uniquely awful.
Lectures do not cover content on Quizzes and Finals, thus many students ended up skipping lectures..
Poor grader
She is really kind, but her lectures are boring. The grading is extremely unfair, just work hard and you can get an A.
rating_tags: Group projects--Lots of homework--Accessible outside class

comment: Based on group projects and biweekly quizzes. The grading is strange and the homework and lectures dont prepare you for what you need to know.
rating_tags: Skip class? You won't pass.--Graded by few things--Group projects

comment: Not a fan. Class was super boring, and she was weirdly judgmental towards students. Always felt like she was sneering down her nose at us.

Prof. Agarwala is truly amazing! She dedicates a lot of time and effort to help her students succeed both academically and personally. You should be prepared to read a lot and engage deeply with the materials. Also expect to think about things in new ways, which might be challenging + take getting used to but that's a part of intellectual growth!

Professor Agarwala's class is mostly discussion-based, some led by her and some by students. The material is challenging but she's super smart and a fantastic teacher and I learned a lot, even though it was a lot of work. Would and will take a class with her again!
rating_tags: Get ready to read--Group projects--Amazing lectures

comment: Best teacher I've had at Hopkins. Worth taking a class to have her as a teacher.
Took Issues in International Studies.  Great class.

Excellent teacher, great lecturer. Make sure to go to class since she does not post slides online. Also, her biggest pet peeve is people not doing the readings so make sure to do them even though there's a lot. Her classes are really well organized and interesting.
Great teacher, very organized class and very helpful through email and office hours. Top on my list for sociology professors.

Although a lot of work outside of the lecture, her lecture videos are actually quite helpful when reviewing for exams. If you finish everything on time, you should spend zero to little time studying for her test and it is an easy A

Flipped class style so gives tons of outside work (prelectures, homework) and then doesn't actually teach anything in class. Classtime is entirely dedicated to participation clicker questions or graded group worksheets, so attendance is mandatory and she doesn't allow you to make up work. Also extremely hostile to students. Really do not recommend.

While she does give a lot of homework, it's all topics she has thoroughly explained. I did little to no studying outside of class due to the step-by-step videos. She's friendly and wants to help. I would much rather fully understand chemistry with lots of work than be lost.

Gives a very large volume of work to students, but makes nearly all of the grade dependent on 3 assignments. Very stingy with partial credit, and is extremely hostile/passive aggressive to students who approach her. She is not actually bad at teaching chemistry, but she makes the experience of taking her class absolutely terrible.

She requires you to watch lecture videos before class to understand what she will teach in the lecture. She has an active learning approach but she barely even teaches during lecture time and often assigns group work to be done during it, which are often hard and very time constrained. Said group work cannot be made up if missed.

By far the worst professor I've had at Hopkins, she has zero respect for students other classes, assigns at least 50 homework problems a week (up to 100), expects students to watch an hour of pre-lecture videos each class, then gives worksheets graded on accuracy each class without teaching the content, and her exams feature content not on the mock

She will give you CONSTANT hw. 2 problem sets per week, daily online quizzes, and consistent in class group ws or quizzes. She is SUPER annoying and will never explain material further than surface level, and then she will test you on the most minuscule details (not mentioned in lecture). DO NOT TAKE THIS PROFESSOR. DO NOT. You will regret it.

Lots of homework, all lectures are to be watched before class, but this meant less studying for exams. This course gives heavy weight to in class activities, some of which are very difficult and shortly timed. She is the rudest professor I have ever had and very unforgiving, she will not give you a break. Worst of the 3 chem 2 professors by far.

Professor Latty applies his extensive real-world experience to help students bridge the gap between a biotechnology concept and a biotechnology product. 

Some of these concepts developed in this class have manifested into companies with real opportunities to bring their technologies to market. 

This has been one of my most memorable classes.

Professor Latty is an amazing professor. 

He is very responsive through email, in class, and he provides recorded lectures if anyone can not make the classes. He always gives feedback and corrects incorrect questions.

I appreciated his encouragement to treat our project as a real life venture opportunity. He truly wants students to succeed.

Ed Latty is by far the most unqualified professor I've ever seen. He has no idea what he's talking about. At the time of posting this, I saw two great review comments on this site that seem to be definitely written by him. As angry as I am of having such an unqualified professor, I am even angrier at the hiring staff that accepted him to work here.
Avoid this guy, you have been warned. You will learn nothing and receive no support in any way.

Ed Latty is the worst professor I've had ever. He makes it his goal to deduct points wherever possible when he's stated, and I quote, "No one should ever receive 100%." He messed up a question on our midterm, he blatantly made a mistake on his answer key, and was proven wrong as we referenced his lecture slides, he refused to change our grade.
DO NOT TAKE THIS CLASS. You will not learn anything. Do not waste your time and money here.

Stay away from this guy; he's sketchy, and he'll waste your money. I had him in my biotechnology enterprise class at JHU; he's the worst teacher I've ever had without a doubt. He doesn't prepare for lectures, and he is completely unqualified to teach. He cannot communicate at the level expected of a university professor.
I kinda liked him ngl

worst professor ever. never made any sense in lectures. test problems are ridiculous and made only to fail students. it's painful to witness him butcher the subject. he never learned from his mistakes
Please don't take any courses with him.

Have fun doing Krolik's homework, because he won't teach you a single thing that will be on it. The book that he uses is equally useless, and is also hard to find not in an e-book form. 10/10 would not recommend.

He's never once done a problem with us on the board and instead tries to explain everything using  complex powerpoints with symbols and derivations.  Tests are impossible. All of the physics pilot leaders who have taken multiple physics classes before don't have any clue how to do the problems and the average  grade is an F. Don't ever take him

The only reason I go to lectures is to get my clicker participation credit.  He's horrible at teaching the material in a way that we can understand.   I always leave the class having no clue what he was talking about. And to make things worse, the questions we go over in class are nothing like the homework (thank god for yahoo answers and chegg).

Don't take this class unless you just want to sleep for an hour. Lectures are boring, and this is unaided by his soporific voice.  Homeworks make up much of the grade, yet there is no textbook to aid and his lectures are purely unhelpful.  However, there are no exams.
Doesn't really care about students, but at least makes efforts to teach the material. Improvements could be made, but I still respect him as a professor

I had him for transport II . Try your best in his class. The guy simply doesn't care. He lacks a certain professionalism as a professor. His tests were no way near the materials discussed in class. Average in his class would be in mid 40's. His final was multiple choice and he did not even tell us that the format would be this way. He simply sucks.
"The sugar cubes"... Had him when he first taught the class. Now he's teaching Transport II. Oh boy...
No Comments
he is a very sweet man. however he needs to gain some experience as a teacher and maybe next year he'll be better.
he was horrible
He's really not that bad. His class is pretty easy, and its interesting as well. I don't know why people thought he was unclear. I found him, his lectures, and assignments to be perfectly clear.
His occ civ class is really not that hard and it's required for IR majors

Very weird guy, very confusing/incomprehensible lectures, but the class is not very hard at all and you have to take it if you're an IR major. Let me put it this way, I did very little work and occassionaly skipped lectures and I still got an A in the class.
One of the worst professor's I've ever come into contact with. His lecture's were incoherent and the course was disorganized as a whole.

His lectures were very unfocused and had nothing to do with the readings. However, I do think that I learned a lot about analyzing historical event, despite the fact that he didn't really teach them. He assumed way too much of the knowledge of the students' of European history.
No Comments
He can't teach
He's helpful
Not interested in helping students and a bit full of himself
No Comments
No Comments
No Comments
We all love our bafken

The Buddhist Experience is the best class at this school! Completely changed my perception of the world. Bavo is a fabulous and caring professor who teaching with clarity and gusto. He is always willing to help and aid in your understanding of the material. His enthusiasm for the subject is contagious. Pretty high work load however.

Intro to Buddhism - Mind opening class, Bavo is adorable and helpful and very enthusiastic, makes class much better. I'm not a morning person so the 1030 slot does tire me out sometimes given that its all lecture, but the class is TOTALLY worth it, the workload is a lot with reading but if youre interested you will do well on the papers for sure.
Open your mind
No Comments
Professor Lievens was very clear and taught with great enthusiasm and interest. Take all his courses.
One of the best professors on campus
Awesome and interesting
Julie is amazing. Funny, quirky, she really grabs your attention, and the assignments are very easy to do, if you put in the effort, which she recognizes. Would love to take another course with her!

I took the class with the intention of not learning much and not working hard. I was wrong on both accounts because the department had just changed the course curriculum. A strict top 10%~A curve was enforced, and I ended up with a B+. She's nice enough, but grading became very arbitrary due to new department policy. Take with caution
She likes want she is doing. Her class was easy as long as you tried and showed her respect. Overall, a very nice person.
Julie's a little bit of a push over. But she's really approachable and really easy to talk to.
Saw his recorded lectures and he demotivated me

If you plan to teach yourself 99% of the content, this is the course. The audio quality of some of the lectures is awful. The stroke of the pen he uses in the video is so thick that sometimes it becomes unreadable. The homework seems small but the knowledge it required is not covered by him. If you promise big in final project, be ready to suffer.
rating_tags: Get ready to read--Lots of homework--Graded by few things

comment: Oh my goodness, this guy is inaudible. His recorded lectures sound like they were recorded when he first woke up in the morning. Not once has he reached out to the students whatsoever and even made it clear on the syllabus to essentially leave him alone unless he is truly needed. This class is basically self taught.

Took his Python intro class and it was a mess. His recorded lectures are extremely boring and his tone and speech are sleepy like he's got a congested nose. He rambles and says "umm" every 5 seconds and this really shows his lack of preparation and clarity. The sample scripts are full of bugs and most don't even run at all! I do not recommend!

Mr. Pascale is the WORST instructor I've had. Ineffective at conveying material in a digestible format. Assignments poorly worded and vague. Requests for further clarification were sometimes answered and rarely cleared things up. Grading had deductions for things not addressed in course module. Lectures were ramblings lacking direction and clarity.

Took his Intro to Python class, the videos explanation was not clear and logic behinds the codes were never explained. Yes, results matter but the logic matters most. And that is why we are learning a language.

Dr. Zahra was an amazing teacher during my Johns Hopkins Introduction to Medicine summer program. She made complicated medical topics feel understandable and interesting. She was always patient and approachable, making me feel comfortable even when I was unsure about something. I'm so thankful for everything I learned from her!

If there is one person that should be teaching courses it is this professor. She is so patient and has an amazing amount of positive energy because she loves teaching. Aside from learning the organ systems, I also know how I might be able to use that in my future career.
Awesome Professor! I had her for one semester and I learned a lot in the class. We would do presentations and active class discussions to gain a better understanding of the class material.

The lectures held by Dr. Zahra were an aspect that I loved and definitely would come again to have those lectures with her. She leads her classes in a highly professional and clear manner and the fact that she is so passionate about this field of academics made me even more engaged and motivated to learn new things.

Professor Tafaghodi presented a clear and well structured course that I believe will greatly aid me in my career. Although the class is simple with little outside of class work, I feel that I effectively learned the topic of the class without a stressful environment. Would recommend Intro to Med. Term. with Professor Tafaghodi to any pre-meds.
Dr. Zahra is an amazing instructor and she really cares about the success of her students. She makes boring lectures very fun.

Can you imagine my intro. to stats was taught by Prof. Naiman? I really like his way of teaching - writing in laptop touch board and projector to us in class. He asks questions on the proofs and derivatives during class which makes it a special experience. I build my confidence on stats from his 430.
He is the best instructor I ever had in all of my 15 courses. He is so cool. He spent a long time on the class. I never see a chairman hold office hours the whole afternoon like him.

I feel terrible about having to give him such bad ratings because he's such a nice guy, but his lectures are EXTREMELY hard to follow, which makes the tests very hard.  I would not recommend taking Stats II with him... wait for a semester when someone else is teaching it.
What a terrible teacher. He expects you to know wayy too much for the class and gives terrible quizzes that noone does well on. He says you don't need to know programming but you really do
No Comments
No Comments

She cares a lot for the BME department for sure. But she seems to care more for the name of the department than the students in it. Her lectures aren't useful, but she gets angry when people don't attend and takes action against the whole class. If you have made her even slightly angry, don't bother reasoning with her, won't work. Easy class work.
rating_tags: Participation matters--Group projects--Graded by few things

comment: I had Dr. Haase as a professor twice. It is clear that she cares deeply about her students and about the BME department as a whole. She is a solid lecturer and puts effort into designing good class assignments. She is inspiring, engaging, and warm.

Worst professor I had at Hopkins. Dr. Haase thinks her useless "revolutionary" teaching methods are the best, yet they are all about endless meaningless repetition and doing work for the sake of doing work. The exams are super long just to see who can write the fastest and the grading system is the furthest thing from smart or fair.
Shes super strict and mean and she makes me sad.
Best teacher I've ever had. Even though the material is inherently difficult, she teaches it in a way that makes it second nature. I definitely recommend Dr. Haase. She's great!

Homework is based on lectures that take place after their due date. Repetitive and monotonous lectures. Homework is graduate level testing material. She is never available outside class. Text books are never used, DO NOT BUY THEM!

I LOVED HIM!!! You dont really have to attend the lectures since they are all online, but he is a wonderful lecturer which makes going to class not bad. You can tell that he really loves what he does. Also the tests are bad if you learn the information, which includes the book! Overall my favorite teacher at hopkins thus far!

He's a great guy that is extremely reputable in the field that he works in and knows his stuff.  If you look him up he's on many truly amazing publications.  The courses he teaches are already interesting, but if you don't think so at first, I think you should just give it time and understand that he has a great passion for this field for a reason.

He's a really great teacher. Lectures while are pointless to attend bc everything is on Webct are fun. His tests are specific. It's hard to know what to study...so just study everything. Don't fall behind on the reading. Learn the specifics. :)

As someone else commented, he does mostly go through his slides, which are on webct.  He's an interesting lecturer though and tells a bunch of fun stories.  Also, he's just a genuinely nice guy who really wants to help you learn.  His tests aren't easy, but it's always super clear what you need to know.  He's taught my favorite classes at Hopkins!
fun lecturer.  tests were specific, but after you fail the first one, you'll ace the next 2 and get a b.  pay attention to the nerves of the thorax.  fun and interesting but tests hard.

doesn't really teach as simply goes through his powerpoint, which is on webct, thereby making going to lecture, pointless. is a really nice guy who knows what he's doing and has been to a lot of places, but his teaching (at least for this class) is very tedious

Good professor with very structured lectures. Don't necessarily need to attend class if you have a good TA (try to get Matthew White). Slides are organized but new additions to equations added each time so you don't know what the newest full idea is sometimes. An easy course at Hopkins due to large curve from a professor who means well.

Maccini is a good guy and means well, has some humor. Very considerate of the group and therefore moves a slow pace, which is perfectly fine. He loves economics and that helps make the class more interesting. Its not hard, would be nice if there were fewer students.

Weird, both in a good and a bad way. Material is very easy, and he moves at a very slow pace, but sometimes doesn't cover all the details while spending half the lecture on something that everyone knows. Exams are okay, but the questions can be extremely confusing and the grading is very subjective.

Maccini is fine. He moves at an excruciatingly slow pace. We didn't even come close to covering international trade. I guess he had to cater to the lowest common denominator i.e. jocks. The grading can be arbitrary and the questions are notoriously vague. They'll always bite you in the ass for not giving a definition that they didn't ask for.
Elements of Macro.  Class is easy, we didn't go through all of the material by the end of the class.
Maccini's a fine professor. Very clear, and has a subtle sense of humor. And he looks like Emperor Palpatine on Star Wars.
Although he has some accent, he is very helpful and have very good notes for students. He has passionate in the math, and wants to teach students the interests of the math, not just this course.

It was hard, and his accent was pretty bad. The tests were somewhat predictable, but still very, very difficult. There is no easy way - you have to do A LOT of practice problems to get an A in this course, which I could not do because there just isn't enough time. Good luck, he isn't easy. (Calculus III, Spring 2010)

He's the best professor you will have out of the math department with the exception of Wilson. Great guy, gives thorough and understandable lecture notes, posts practice exams and asks very fair test questions. Overall wonderful experience.
Very good notes once you get used to the accent. Tests were fair.
Great Notes,very patient
When he lectures he can be hard to understand, but his lecture notes are very clear and helpful when doing homework. Tests were challenging but fair.
her accent's hard to understand but you get the hang of it. She curves really generously so everyone does well. Open to suggestions as to how to improve the class
A lot of self-studying has to be done

Hot. Lectures are brilliant if you skim the chapter before class, otherwise confusing. Use the book for examples and simplified methods she may not teach. She looks after the students she knows/who make an effort in the class. Sit up front, ask for help. Genuinely wants to give great grades to all who deserve them.  And she IS curved generously ;)

Hot. Sit up front and she gets easier to understand. In class notes were not as useful to me as textbook, which has sufficient examples. Get your hands on old tests and review problems(she will show you where some are anyways) do the homework and her class is manageable. And her curve was generous.
She is terrible. I advise you learn French before taking her course.
absolutely useless as a teacher but pretty hot so that almost makes up for the fact she mumbles to herself in the front of class with a incomprehensible accent
Professor Armitage is great.   Nice guy and very clear.   His lectures are engaging and I really liked going to class.

Although Professor Armitage tends to be a bit scattered on occasion, if I judge this class by what I actually learned this was one of the very best at JHU.   I never really "got" physics before, but in this class I think I finally understood what it was all about.  He has a unique way of explaining and getting inside physics that clicked with me.
Professor Armitage wants the students to succeed.  The material is hard though.  He has extensive office hours which are helpful.

The only thing I would say is that although he says you can look at old exams online to see what his exams are like that is not really true.   A much better guide to his exams are the homework problems.  Some people complained that he put identical problems from HW on the exams, but I don't really see how this is a bad thing.
I took Prof. Armitage for 105.  I'd had AP physics previously, but I learned much more in this awesome class.  Great professor!
Hard class, but good.  You'll definitely learn alot, but you will have to work.  He is an enthusiastic lecturer.

The provided lecture materials were so good, I probably didn't need the textbook. The demo videos were essential because I was new to R studio commands. Office hour videos were very helpful! Grade included weekly discussions & homework, monthly homework set and quiz, 2 short exams, 2 group projects (ugh), and a huge final exam.
rating_tags: ACCESSIBLE OUTSIDE CLASS--Clear grading criteria--Amazing lectures

comment: Probably not the place to mention this but I completed Dr Lessick's bioinformatics course through Coursera.  He took time to answer questions in forums, gave very clear lectures and was most helpful.  I would certainly consider taking his classes if I went to JHU, or through coursera if not.
Good teacher, lectures were great, presents the material in a clear and interesting manner. woukd take classes from him again. Dont need the textbook, pretty easy class.

My first bioinformatics class. The class was interesting.  I am not a computer person so I was often one of the last people to leave. I left the class with a good understanding and I refer to his lectures often when performing searchs. Not to stressfull,no homework,clear material,take good notes. Open note exams/quizes. I often recomment his class.
One of the better teachers I've had so far.  Classes are clear cut, teaches material well and in a visual hands-on manner.  Nice guy, and I think his classes are pretty easy.
Work through a lot of homework problems, but in the end it helps.
Mark don't have the competence to teach ML. Lack basic math sense!

This professor is very unprofessional. He don't understand ML very well. When students pointed out errors from his slides or flaws in his teaching, he didn't take them seriously and many time ignored them. But when students wanted to demand some unmerited credits from assignments or exams, most of the time he tended to just please them!
Really bad. Not verse in topics.Avoid him; take other ML courses in AMS or BME. Those instructors are defintely better!
This professor really cares about his students, and he really wants you to learn his stuffs. Work hard and you will be okay with this course and learn a lot.
It's a great professor with a lot of home work. If you pay a lot of attention on it, you will get good reward.

a waste of time, prof avoids answering anything but the most superficial questions, can't deal with theory or anything formal.  made lots of mistakes in grading and in lecture.  assignment were riddled with errors.  class devolved into "what people do" and abandoned "why they might do it" or anything useful for serious ml students

Little bit disorganized, great professor with great intentions. Learned a lot more in this class than I expected to (Principles of Immuno). Take his class if you can, doesn't load you with busy work and focuses on guiding you through understanding the concepts.

He can be a bit scattered, but I have learned more from him in a year than I did in four years of undergraduate. He is just more focused on making sure that students are actually gaining some knowledge than focusing too much on grading. With that being said, it can be stressful if your sole purpose in a class is to get an A.

He can be a little scattered, but once you get to know him, he is an amazing professor who cares deeply about his students he wants you to learn and understand the material. Take his classes he is amazing.

I was really hesitant abou this professor because of these reviews, but it was a decent class. PROS: a lot of mini and fun assignments due every week that actually allows you to apply the material (he's really generous on grading) CONS: The Quizzes ARE WAY TOO SPECIFIC/ YOU HAVE TO REALLY READ THE TEXTBOOK. The Final wasn't so bad. Give him a try!

Professor Mahr is very disorganized. He misses posting assignments on time, yet does not give you extra time to complete them. He tells you to both use and not use outside sources for reference, expecting you to learn from wikipedia or your own searches. Low quality teaching, do not recommend.

The professor is scattered and the weekly assignments are different activities every week. I spend more time reading the instructions than doing the assignments. No exams but there are weekly quizzes. The quizzes are based on the textbook and rarely on lectures. The class was wasn't difficult but the tedious. There's always things to do each week.

Dr. Mahr is scattered. His instructions for assignments warns against spelling and grammatical errors. Yet his communications were riddled with them. It made figuring out what topics are important for tests and quizzes a challenge. Don't expect feedback. That said, he grades fairly and transparently. He's personable in his lectures and emails.

He really loves his subject and it shows. He assigns too much reading for sure but you can get away with only reading about half/two thirds of it. He's a fair grader and the discussions were interesting. If you yourself are passionate about the subject I highly recommend you take him.
Moss is inspiring and very interested in what he is teaching, and class flies by. The grading system is super fair, but there is a decent amount of reading. My favorite class this semester!
Speaks waaaaaaaaaaaay too fast and gives you waaaaaaaay too much reading; and to think this is only an introductory course...

You can tell by the way he lectures that he's smart, used big words and foreign languages, but lectured like he was trying to defend a thesis than teach us European history. Was so abstract and jumpy that it was impossible to get anything out of his class. Required wayyy too much reading for an intro class. Didn't even have a textbook, really.
Knowledgeable professor, but better for upper level classes than intro. Kind of abstract and theoretical. Grading is fair.

Professor Moss is cute, but his lectures are so disorganized-- as are his reading assignments. Instead of a textbook there are over 10 books (as well as NUMEROUS accompanying articles) assigned.. costly, immensely time consuming, and hardly helpful. I HATE THIS CLASS
Best prof at Hopkins by far. I take classes literally just bc he teaches them.

There are several plays you need to read and weekly journals to be done.  As long as you do that and memorize lines given (not too many), then it's an easy A.  Great guy.  Always wants the best for you and is quite understanding.

Astin is respectful to his students and covers material that is generally interesting to read and think about. During his lectures, he tends to get off track and go on random tangents. He has a good sense of humor and knows a lot about theater and film. Though sometimes his classes become redundant, overall I recommend.
He has a great way of making everyone feel like they're his favorite student.

Course is easy and not stressful at all.  Astin tends to go on tangents about anything, and as long as you don't mind that, you'll enjoy the course.  The classes tend to be large, so there is less stage time for everybody.  Doing scenes was the best part.
He is kind, funny, passionate and enthusiastic about what he's teaching. He is also brilliant; best acting coach I have had.

Not accessible or responsive, as she is too consumed with many different job roles. She is not around when you need her before deadlines, until too late ... and then she will tell you how poorly you did after. Her tone is sometimes off, especially can talk down to students. The only reason she became director, is our department chair's favoritism.
Dr. Logsdon is a caring advisor and competent lecturer. While she can be a bit strict, she puts effort into making her courses engaging and relevant to the medical device industry.

Extremely fickle. Gives advice that directly contradicts her grading. Is basically never present, and doesn't bother to meet with the team or show up to committee meetings. Not really sure who let this lab manager be an instructor for this course, especially when she has given absolutely no semblance of competence at any point in the semester.

I came into BME really interested in devices, industry, and Design Team, but her course ruined it for me. Her expectations are unclear, she is extremely unresponsive and generally unavailable. Grades very tough, but doesn't give any individual help to teams (hasn't even made an attempt to get to know us on a personal level). Overall terrible prof.
Dr. Logsdon gives really unclear feedback and has very subjective grading. She gives mixed feedback and doesn't add any value to this course for the position of power that she has in the course.

One of the worst professors I've had. She is usually not around, and when she is she is very unhelpful. Almost completely nonresponsive to emails and gives terribly confusing feedback on your projects. Expectations are unclear and grades highly subjectively. Stay away from this course, because while the idea of the class is great, this professor ru

He is by far one of my favorite professors so far. Great teaching and clear instructions. 

But be sure to pay attention in the beginning of the class or you might lose track.

The professor is not willing to give a standard grade to us. Everyone gets pretty low grades for different reasons, he can always find a reason to give you a pretty low grade, for sure, he is a kind of discriminator. Do not take his class anyway.

I know a lot of people hate him, but I like him for some reason. He really inspired me to be rich and successful, and what he said is actually useful in the real world. Quiz are all short answers but he graded them loosely. Plus, the question repeats all the time, so it is nice.

The worst instructor!!!! Please try to avoid taking his lecture. He only talks about himself and his stories without teaching anything during lectures.  The only related to knowledge he does during lectures is reading the slides. Terrible experience!!!!!!!!!!!
I'm a international student from China in his M&A class and he dont want to teach anything, just talk.
Try anything to avoid him. Teach nothing in the class.

Excellent professor. one of a kind. brings experience and research in a fun class. lessons are well structured, gives feedback on every assignement and teaches you how to make your reasearch material add value to your portfolio. In short the best!

The best professor ever. Meaningful classes that will serve you in your professional career, Subject matter expert in change management, KM, Project Management and Strategy and Innovation.  Well organized, fun and lively classes. Inspires you to learn complex systems from a simple easy to understand perspective.
Blends theory and practice well
Convoluted way of teaching.  Very knowledgeable but does not always translate knowledge into student learning.

Prof. Melvin one of the best . He Has his own way in teaching and he is very smart .He ask for an essay every week what you learned in week before . He is Unique PM.I will not miss any class for him .The most Prof I gained experience from him.
Project Management Information system

This class is quite a bit of work! But has added so much value to my understanding of drug development. It is very hands on and practical and tries to simulate real life. I appreciate all that I have learned from Professor Ndu this semester!
rating_tags: Get ready to read--Participation matters--Group projects

comment: Professor Ndu gets a bad rap. If you come from a heavy academia background, this course should be a walk-in-the-park. She is very open and receptive. She makes the learning of this course very easy and friendly.
Good practical class, enjoyed the team work although it was frustrating at times since some team members were unreliable. Lots of writing and research.
I really enjoyed this class, takes learning using a hands on approach. Definitely recommend
Great class! One of the best.

70% of the grade is based on 3 group projects, the groups are assigned at random and there is no ability to be individually graded. If you happen to have a bad group the only options that exist is getting a worse grade than you probably could have alone, or to do the work for the entire team. I would not recommend this class at all.
rating_tags: Graded by few things--Group projects--So many papers

comment: Actually the sweetest professor here. No graded homework. Paired with practice problems and Pilot was an easy A.
An absolute icon

My favorite professor! He genuinely cares about his students, loves teaching (and is good at it too). As long as you make the effort to learn and work hard, you will have an amazing time in all of his courses.

Dr. Nsengiyumva is genuinely the goat. He made me want to attend lectures because his enthusiasm for the class was infectious. He's super open to helping students -- he cares about people and wants you to learn. His lectures are sometimes fast paced, but he's clear about what matters and is a good lecturer. Best prof I had this semester, by far.

Dr. N was a wonderful professor! He helped explain many tricky concepts in the textbook and also cares for all his students. He provides many resources and goes out of his way to make videos to clarify tricky topics that were covered in class. Additionally, Dr. N's weekly quizzes force students to keep up with the class so they won't fall behind.

Dr. N is an amazing professor because he genuinely cares and wants his students to succeed. He goes out of his way to help students, making review videos for hard topics before our exams and doing a pre-exam review session going over a practice exam he wrote. He's also a very friendly and approachable person. Highly recommend!
This guy is actually the goat

Greatest addition to Hopkins chem department since chemistry itself. Amazing lecturer and makes it clear what's important. Exams are very fair, perhaps even easy for orgo. Do textbook problems and be prepared for weekly quizzes. Replaces lowest midterm with final which can really boost grade. Ask questions when they come up and don't fall behind.
I took Japanese 1 and I really enjoyed Yuki sensei's class. If you have any question just go ask her and she will try her best to help you

Yuki sensei was a great professor and I wish I could take her class again! She made learning fun and really made sure her students succeeded. She made learning a difficult language like Japanese easy so long as you put in the work and keep up with the class.
rating_tags: Skip class? You won't pass.--Clear grading criteria--Hilarious

comment: I took her class years ago and doubt much has changed. She made me dread class and sucked so much joy out of learning for me. I don't remember many specifics apart from how condescending she could be. I got the impression she didn't like what she was doing. Her classes didn't emphasize reading, writing, speaking, or listening. Low value.
Unclear explanations. Dismissive. Takes all fun out of learning.

Awful - Unhelpful and dismissive. Her attitude is "sink or swim" and she won't offer suggestions on how to avoid sinking. She doesn't care about students at all. Comes across as nice on the outside. Her classes have a 50% drop out rate. She's tenured so less work for her.

Professor Johnson is very lively and outgoing, she brings a lot of light into the classroom when she lectures. She comes across a little naive during lecture, but she will make every effort she can to help her students understand what is going on in the class. She's very passionate about Japanese language, and makes learning exciting and fun.

Dr. Jessica is exemplary in her teaching methods in the content and delivery of current oncology research. Assignments are well-versed and highly relevant to the real trends in the biotechnology industry. She cares about students' needs. Her class is must must-take.  In my experience, she is the most qualified professor in the field.

Easy Grade, but you don't take a master's level course for an easy Grade. It was online, so the medium may be to blame. There just wasn't anything to take away from the course that wasn't already taught better in the prior core courses.
Her lectures can be long, but cancer biology has a lot you need to go over. She helps you to get prepared for her test, and for her presentation, I really enjoyed her class.

Learn about cancer biology. Professor was thorough, and well prepared. She will prepare you for the midterms, finals, and presentations. Discussions are to help you learn more about the topic. I recommend to others.
Passionate about the subject, has guest lecturer, responds quickly to emails and grades quickly. Midterm and final were straightforward. What else could you want?
great

This professor, to start, disagreed with everything the textbook said and blatantly didn't like it. She also did not go in depth to any topics and instead just threw information at us. Perhaps most annoyingly, an A in her introductory class was a 94, and she did not round up for students less than .1% away from that grade.

Unclear instructions regarding assessments and exams. 
Minimal engagement with the class.
You might need a mask for her class
This class is crazy
dadaddadadadadada

Does not effectively explain the material or why its included in the syllabus! frequently goes on tangents without explaining their relevance, deliberately stifles student pushback to political opinions (she is openly zionist) and refuses to take questions during class if they disagree with her own views. you will be interrupted by her!
This professor was very enthusiastic but a very hard grader. She makes silly jokes and assigns readings that are almost cryptic and difficult to understand.

First of all, she was never clear on the curve (or lack thereof) and homework grading policy. She also talks into the chalkboard while speaking about and turns around briefly before turning back (so she never sees hands raised for ?'s). She is very poor at communicating the concepts in a manner than we can understand. Not good at teaching.
Lectures are somewhat confusing, but office hours will be your best friend.
The first midterm was so tough. But she is willing to help students.
She's helpful when I tried to ask her questions. However, the first midterm was so tough.
Does not know how to teach. this is not simply because the language barrier makes it difficult but because she doesn't know how to convey the information.

She's very unhelpful and gets angry when people ask questions. Very passive aggressive and blames students for incomprehension---but let me say if the average is 56 with standard dilation of 16 pts it's more than just the students.
Mark is very very lively... get ready for some pretty dirty jokes to be honest its a little much but otherwise very nice guy, manageable workload (writing for the law)
Grades a little hard. Usually gives lots of assignments, none take too much time. I had him for internet in the law. Very cool guy. Likes participation.
Classes are very entertaining. Grades reasonably. He likes participation and answers questions clearly. Really passionate about his subject.
He makes class a lot of fun. The class isn't hard, but you definitely need to work to keep your grade.
No Comments
Great teacher.  Class very good.  A lot of discussion of real world.  Fantastic guest speaker.  Take this class!
Worst teacher ever. Boring. Not understandable. Moody.
Impossible to understand. If you have to take calc, take it during covered grades because it is impossible to learn anything from him, let alone get a good grade. SWITCH TO ANOTHER PROF
worst professor ever. killed my morale and my GPA. do NOT take any class with alan, i've had to learn everything by myself. also his exams are multiple choice, which is really dumb for a math class
Hard to understand (its the Turkish accent) and not welcoming. Has a strange sense of humor probably due to language barrier.
cant understand anything he says. moves way too fast. does not walk thru new material. im dying
Can't understand a word this guy says. My TA would be a far better prof.

She is very nice and great when you go to office hours! She does not know how to use iclicker properly and it is worth 20% of your grade so if you have an issue just go and tell her and she will fix it. The first exam is always miserable, it seems really easy but trust me it is not. The second and third exams are much easier, study for the final!
rating_tags: Lots of homework--Test heavy--Graded by few things

comment: Very monotone, doesn't teach in her alternative learning physics classes. Would not recommend. Take lecture instead.

Professor Wyse is a really nice and kind lady. She teaches Stellar Physics well and passionately and she always explains the maths very understandable. Although it's a difficult upper level physics course, I was able to follow because Professor Wyse was always willing to support me, answer my questions and send out useful reading material.

Professor Wyse clearly cares about her students. She responds to emails quickly and would address questions at any time, not just during office hours and in classrooms. Her lectures can be hard to follow, but not impossible if you use resources she provides well. Also, I strongly encourage first and second years to take her intro to stars class.

Professor Wyse's lectures can be tiresome, but her resources are extremely helpful; I especially appreciated the lecture slides, ample access to past exams, and Flipit prelectures. This course is unbelievably difficult and honestly left many students with a strong dislike of physics. I think this is an institutional issue, though.

Professor Wyse is not a great teacher. You would be better off doing khan academy, because the way she teaches is through ONLY problems and examples. She doesnt teach, and has all the material on a terrible website called FlipIt physics, which looks like it hasnt been updated since 1990. If you havent taken physics please do not choose her. please
This class provided me with a space to learn about the foundations of earth and planetary sciences, and reflect on how my own experiences relate to science and knowledge. I loved it!

Taking Professor Angappan's class was one of the best moves I made this semester. The class I took opened my eyes to different aspects of empathy in the universe--something that is definitely lacking in most other science education. It is clear that he cares for his students and this class has impacted my college experience greatly.

Regu is an amazing professor. His lectures do a great job of mixing lectures with discussion to effectively convey difficult science principles while continuing to engage the class. Not only does he care about his students, but he also encourages introspection and self-reflection, concepts that are not often emphasized in science classes.

The class was the most engaging one I've taken, lectures are taught with passion & class is ran with an emphasis on empathy which shows in his teaching style. Rather than focusing on rote memorization he builds on understanding and application. I hope he stays in academia after his PhD because the field of higher education is better with him in it.

This professor took the takeaways and meaning of the class very seriously so that we always knew what the bigger picture was and how the topics would make us more learned and empathetic people. Not only were we learning about interesting scientific topics but seeing how to make the scientific community a more effective place.
Regu is enthusiastic, understanding, and caring. I love how committed he is to getting everyone involved in science no matter their background.

Professor Brown is by far the best professor I have had during my time at Hopkins. He truly cares about each student and is willing to go out of his way to help you grow as a writer and as a person. He comes to class each day with passion and energy, making his class one that I looked forward to going to. I would highly recommend taking his class!!

One of my favorite professors at Hopkins! He was super sweet and kind. He really cares about the students and is willing to help in any way he can. The Reintro to writing class was amazing and greatly enjoyed the course as well as his teaching style. He is flexible with due dates and very understanding. Would definitely recommend him to everyone!
Amazing professor! So kind and knowledgable!

One of the chillest and laid-back professors I have had at Hopkins thus far. I took his Reintro to writing class and it was nothing but a breeze. Everyone in my class got an A, all you have to do is attend class and write decently as he is very lenient on grades and cares more about helping you grow as a writer. 10/10 recommend.
Nate Brown is an awesome professor. He genuinely cares about his students and his class is fun to be a part of.

I absolutely loved taking Nate Brown's Craft of Fiction class. He is warm, caring, and considerate and really wants us all to do our best in becoming writers. I very much hope to take him again while at college.
Prof Chung is great. Very helpful and accessible. Reading is long but manageable. Her grading is fair.
rating_tags: Gives good feedback--Get ready to read--Inspirational

comment: Super passionate teacher; clearly very knowledgeable about her topic of study. Took her class as a freshman and even though I was obviously  lagging behind my sectionmates, she was super encouraging and never dismissed my views!  Learnt alot.
Very clear lecture--organized, engaging, and relevant.

She doesn't seem to know anything besides Korean immigrants in Japan. In our East Asian Politics class, she just made us read papers and barely taught. For the China part, we had to watch a three day movie because she didn't know anything. Unhelpful and unresponsive to e-mails. Loves her Korean heritage and often is ... extremely biased.

She makes you read the articles then memorize their key points. If you do not memorize the author's names, there was no point in taking any test. The problem wouldn't be so bad if there weren't 200+ pages a week to read. I made a final review sheet which was more than 60 pages long (front/back font: 10). Not an effective class. Do not take it.
She has a nice personality and has some good class discussions, but her lectures aren't very helpful for the difficult exams.
I liked taking her Financial Accounting class. There is a lot of lecture that some may consider boring, but I thought it was useful.

Professor Leps is one of the best professors Ive ever had. Although Accounting can be dry, she takes the time to make sure everyone understands the material by involving class participation. Shes very receptive to questions and clarifications without judgement. Very fair problem sets and exams, & very light HW load if you pay attention in class.
NOT EVEN FOLLOW the Syllabus. Handout is absolutely out of date and HURT your eyes so much, and the hand written notes are SUPER hard to follow.
rating_tags: Lots of homework--Lecture heavy--So many papers

comment: Good prof, Financial Accounting is boring.
She's the best. I wish she could teach other Hopkins professors how to be approachable and make the subject matter interesting.
Best professor at Hopkins
He likes to make fun of students. In particular, the tea drinkers.

Since I discovered a bug (without having taken a computer science course before), I found that him and other professors and students participate in cyberbullying students on facebook. Definitely not tolerating it :). Hopefully, the dude and others find joy.

Kaplan is so sweet as a person, but his lectures are long-winded, and take an hour and a half to summarize the 15 minute Flipitphysics prelecture. He only goes over proofs but does not go over solving or applying the concept. Homework sets are unnecessarily difficult, and the grading is pretty harsh. Assigned extra homework over spring break days.
Hardest tests ever -- Second test average was around 40, and third test average was 18 -- however, curves are generally fair so you won't fail this class if you put in effort.

Dr. Kaplan is a wonderful professor for introductory physics. He explains concepts well. Expect his tests to contain similar examples to what he uses in class. His grading system is very fair; you know exactly what your grade is at any given point in the course. The final exam is incredibly difficult, be prepared.
Good lecturer who is always using his kids as examples for motion and dynamics.  Not overly hard, but a very conceptual class.

Prof. Kraemer is SO nice. He's genuinely a very good person and cares about his students. Attendance for his class isn't mandatory, but his lectures are interesting and he's a good teacher. He is the sweetest prof ever.

Professor Kraemer does a good job with MatLab, but you can tell its not his specialty. He comes prepared to class and is open to suggestions. He can be helpful if you catch him before/after class, but is a little slow to answer emails. Computing projects are most of your grade, so start early and ask for help and you'll save yourself some trouble
Had him for Matlab, super nice and helpful, really cares about his students. Going to class isn't really required to pass but you work on some interesting problems there so I'd recommend you go.
Wonderful professor

Attempts to be fun. Will be passive aggressive, and if class fails together will blame students and not self. Is not clear on instructions and takes a long time to get your grades back. In fact many grades were not returned until the day before the final. If you can avoid him I would suggest doing so.
Easily the funniest professor I have had.  Classes are interesting and engaging, and the professor is very approachable.

Took Syntax I with Prof. Legendre. Very knowledgeable and passionate in linguistics. She cares about her students: very accessible and patient during class/office hours and would spend time in class going over the assignments. Syntax is HARD and get ready to spend tons of time --- don't take it unless you are really interested.
rating_tags: Lots of homework--Accessible outside class--Get ready to read

comment: She was passionate but doesn't know how to teach introductory level material: no one understood the rules and people fell quickly behind. Homeworks are above our comprehension level for an introductory course, and take up to 10 hours a week. Do not take this course if you want an easy class or something that will not stress you out.
rating_tags: Tough Grader--Skip class? You won't pass.--LOTS OF HOMEWORK

comment: She is one of the most passionate teachers that I ever had. Her classes are not easy, but if you try, you will do well. I love her!!

Prof Legendre has such a passion for her work and linguistics and she definitely brought that passion to class. The content in the class is fairly complex and most people seemed to LOVE class or HATE it, there wasn't much in between. I would definitely recommend to anyone  interested in how languages work but definitely NOT an "easy N credit".

Hands down, one of the best professors I have had and will have! Extremely helpful, might appear strict at first but is very easy going and warm. Takes interest in student's performance and knows her subject in and out. Highly recommend taking WOL with her!
Great Professor. When Needed help she was readily available. TA's are helpful. Great class very interesting. Just dont allow yourself to fall behind. Alot of material

The best professor I have had for this program. I would take every class with her if I could! She graded assignments/tests VERY quickly which is nice. She is also highly engaged in weekly discussions and facilitates a great learning environment. She constantly reminds the class of due dates/deadlines which is extremely helpful for busy students.
She was okay as a professor, but it was difficult to try and get a B I was really close, but she would not offer the credit but give her a try.
rating_tags: Tough grader--Get ready to read--Accessible outside class

comment: Glaser-George cares about her students and the material being taught. I learned a lot from the course and felt all the assignment/exams were fair. She gave feedback and grades extremely quick which was refreshing.
I really enjoyed having Dr. Glaser-George as my professor this past semester! She's so incredibly kind and caring, and is very accessible outside of class. 10/10 would recommend :)
She's a gem. Definitely take her if you can! Makes a really boring and dense subject like Cell bio bearable and less painful. Really straight-forward lectures and expectations.

Always offers office hours and extra credit opportunities. Lectures are straightforward (homework are a bit more complicated) and easy to review. Genuinely cares about her students' success and explains any concepts one doesn't understand.

I took Prof. Seshie's class on Gender Economics. She is one of the most passionate and engaged teachers I have had at Hopkins. Awesome professor who really cares!
Nicest professor at Hopkins. Cares about course content and her students.

No curve, no backtest, course grading changes a lot, she would right check the slide/textbook or I dont have time to write it on answer key to practice exam, she teach you material in the morning and include the material on the test the very same day without telling you. This is not a hard class, but she find a way to make it uncomfortable.
Professor Seshie-Nassee is such a sweet, lovely woman. She really cares about us all clearly and has made the grades match our effort levels. 10/10 recommend. And she knows her stuff.
Not great at communicating lecture content. Slides are very dense. Not a very approachable professor. HW sets are tedious but prepare you well for the exams

Be prepared to have 2 long assignments a week. Each assignment took probably 7 hours to complete. No need to attend lecture because he is very boring and basically reads the textbook off his powerpoint.

Very boring lectures. Most of the time, just likes to show you all the cool things he has done with his advanced programming knowledge. Assumes most or all student have programming experience, even though it's an into level class.
The actual beer is much better.  Very nice teacher but will put you to sleep.
beer rules
best lang & mind TA ever

She is one of the reasons that this is my favorite course so far. When some of the class materials are challenging, Zandi always tries her best to help everyone with anything, so that is why I have always rushed to the Office Hour -- every time her Office Hour was so crowded with all the students cuz she has the best OH!

comment: super chill
Zandi was amazing!! She helped me when I was so confused even when (especially when!) it was the night before the test.

Super helpful towards understanding the class material, breaking down content matter into easily-understood information, and making sure all students were prepared for tests. Had lots of available office time and was really friendly. Definitely a lifesaver TA!
She appears to be strict at first glance, but she is actually so sweet and understanding.

I took her course last semester as my first ChemBE core course. She is caring, always prepared, and gives us lots of opportunities to make up for the mistakes made during exams. I will definitely take her course again in the future.

One of the best prof I've had at Hopkins so far. She is super caring about students, available for any questions and provides very clear feedback. The quizes and hws are quite easy + you can resubmit every hw and quiz up to 90%. The course is designed the way so that every can get a high grade. HIGHLY RECOMMEND
rating_tags: Amazing lectures --Clear grading criteria--Gives good feedback

comment: Inconsiderate of students needs.

Dr. Zerin is one of the best professors at JHU. She explains the class material well, and is very kind, patient and willing to answer questions from students. Grading is very fair and exams, homeworks and projects are at a very reasonable difficulty. I would highly recommend taking any class taught by Dr. Zerin.
Good lectures. Confusing assignments where TAs grade your stuff poorly. Assignments consist of open ended questions that only accept one very narrow correct answer.

Terrible professor who assigns everything last minute, with the worst TAs possible. The class is a joke. He responds to nothing on Piazza, and gives zero feedback. You might as well take parallel programming at your local community college.

a really nice guy.  very accessible outside of class and is always willing to help.  tho his attempts to help sometimes get more difficult than necessary.  assignments are long but very doable, and the exams are easy.  recommended for intermediate programming.
Very friendly teacher who makes alot of jokes, even tho no one laughs. Its sad, however hes a good guy and the assignments are long but not too bad. The tests are a demon tho.

she was nice mostly and funny sometimes. very strict about showing up to class and participating. the worst part was that she never returned grades for most assignments. we only got grades back for the two papers and then the final course grade

SHE COMPLAINS TOO MUCH ABOUT LIFE.. SHES SO FAKE AND JUST OVER ALL UGGHHH .. SERIOUSLY DONT TAKE HER!!!!!!!!

He posts lecture notes but they read more like what a student's notes of a lecture. I don't find his lectures particularly well explained. Past tests and study guides are a godsend.
