comment: He doesn't really teach. He reads off the slides, and mind you his slides cover every single detail in the book.  He also expects you to do every problem in the back of the book. His tests are difficult and he doesn't curve or give extra credit.

He is definitely a super difficult professor. You are not required to come to class, but there are weekly reading quizzes. He depends on the book and his lecture notes are basically the entirety of the book. It is possible to get an A, but memorizing the book and doing every single problem in the back of the book is what you will have to do!

Super great guy! He was only my TA but I've also heard great things about the classes that he teaches on his own. He is super interested in the subject and that is very apparent. I will actively try to take courses from him in the future.

He's a nice guy who genuinely wants you to learn. He gets ahead of himself a bit though, and also can be a little contradicting. Other than that, he's a pretty good teacher and definitely knows what he's talking about.
LOVEDDD this class!!  The teacher was also really cool!
ooo, I'm hot for this teacher
super-friendly, quirky guy.  very laidback teaching approach and incredibly patient.

He's a really nice guy, but he tends to rush through lectures, and his explanations are not perfect due to the language barrier.  Use notes/lectures/HW problems to study.  Make sure you know every example he's done in class or else the exam will surprise you.  Unless it's an honors class he tends to only throw one proofy/theory question on exams.
chu's great.
Very helpful.  Willing to help you out during his office hour.  Very passionate in teaching.  His accent may cause some problems though.

Warning: small but funny accent. he's the most enthusiastic teacher here. Lectures move fast but are spent doing examples and he's greatly focused on trying to foster an understanding of the material. Homework is a lot if you wait til the night before, but great class, reasonable tests, great guy. don't take calc from anyone else if possible.
Funny professor with a good sense of fashion- love his argyle sweaters. Extremely patient and gets through lecture fast. Tests are based on reviews, so they are pretty easy. He made calculus 3 fun.
She knows what she's talking about and is passionate about CS, but she is a little bit nit-picky about things like code style.

When you ask her a question she seems very eager to finish answering your question so that she can move onto other more important things, even if it means that she doesn't do a good job answering the question. Often her answers and extremely brief, vague, and not helpful. She makes many mistakes during lecture which makes the class hard to follow.

I took this class over the summer and it was one of most useful classes. Although I am not a JHU student, I found this class to be very interesting and helpful in understanding programing. It is a tough class when taken in summer, but it's rewarding.

I found that often the professor was not as familiar with the material as she should be. She also does a horrible job at explaining concepts to the class. She teaches her intro classes at a much harder level then it should be.
She is a very good professor. I really learned a lot from her.
I miss his teaching
Hankin's a real gem.
My favourite professor at Hopkins. He genuinely cares about every single one of his students and remembers their names. If you want to go from a stickman to Da Vinci in a semester, take his classes.

Great professor with a lot of passion for the subject, and lots of personality. He  pays attention to your style, and is interested in his students' work. Overall, I had a really good experience, and I'll take his class again.

Hankin was great, he was really nice and helpful. Very understanding, and just generally a really great guy. His class was fun to take though i don't think it was really helpful in instructing me to create better. He for me was to nice in his critiques but maybe im just used to the asses at RISDI. Overall a great prof to have

He is English fluent, but when he starts lecturing his words get jumbled and he mumbles frequently. One on one, he's fine because you can ask him to repeat, but in the large class setting of our lecture--I can hear 5% of what he's saying (this also applies to online recorded lectures). This is not made any easier by his tiny/unclear handwriting.
rating_tags: Get ready to read--Graded by few things--Test heavy

comment: Kong is a humorous and nice guy. Not hard on students. But intense courses, and exams a little bit demanding. However, once you do your homework well, and understand the textbook, you will feel really easy.
Doctor Kong is an enthusiastic teacher. He is very responsible. Except his exam is a little hard. But on good thing is grading is not so strict.

Prof Kong is really helpful. He chooses the important ideas to teach in class. The homework means to refresh your memory, instead of repetitive dull calculations. Quiz and exams not very hard, basically the important ideas he covered in class.
Explain very clearly. And quizzes keep you always on track.

Prof Taylor was great, really got me interested in Mesopotamian art. Caring, funny, incredibly excited to teach, clearly passionate. Very meta about the history of the field and modern politics. Wish someone loved me as much as he loves Mesopotamian art.

Ancient art of the Near East/ Took in spring 2021. A newer teacher. Only 3 assignments: midterm, term paper, and final. Pay attention to lectures because the slides are mainly pictures, the information is given orally. weekly readings using perusal. Write a lot of notes, attend lectures and you will do fine.
rating_tags: Get ready to read--Graded by few things--Lecture heavy

comment: Professor Taylor gives great Lectures and does a great job answering questions both during and after class. Has a great personality, cares about his students, and really knows his stuff. Required readings for every class, but not too much and Professor is always available to help with understanding.

Fun professor, humorous anecdotes, great use of memes. I feel like he genuinely cared for the wellbeing of his students. I appreciated the incorporation of themes like gender and colonialism. Lots of readings, some were hard, but the professor was available to help. Definitely expects participation. Easy grader if you show up and express interest.

I loved this class with Professor Taylor. His lectures were easy to follow, he was very passionate about the subject, and his awkward humor was very endearing. If you go to class and do the readings and put in the effort its an easy A. I'm not an art student but it was a fun class for humanities requirement and surprisingly interesting.
rating_tags: Gives good feedback--Respected--Get ready to read

comment: One of the best teachers at Hopkins! She has such a gift for teaching that makes learning French such an amazing experience!!

The best introduction to a language class I have ever taken. Is easy to contact and talk to; she would gladly help you with your pronunciation, sentence structure, and grammar. Gives constructive criticism and ways to improve your assignment. Grades based on completion of work and improvement. Gives extra credit. I look forward to seeing her.
intermediate french. great teacher and really helpful

I took a class with her 12 years ago. And still remember it as one of the best of my time at Hopkins. She was also kind of sexy in that French woman sort of way.   Truthfully she is the only professor I remember at JHU that actually tried to give you constructive criticism instead of trying to divine some meaning from scribbles on the paper.
Is fun and speaks clearly. She knows her stuff. One of the few professors to actually teach a lower-level French class. Best teacher I've had in the French department.

Really hard material and he just assumes that everyone came into the course knowing rudimental chemistry so he doesn't explain things very much at all. He just reads straight off of the blackboard powerpoint. Tests are really hard, OWL problems take time but are easy. Surprisingly, he is a fair grader and my end grade was curved very generously

A boondoggle of a class. Sheer low hanging fruit. If it weren't for his interest in surface science and his love of fine wine I would have detested the course. A true Welsh character, through and through.
Not particularly good.
Extremely helpful. Teaches straight from the book so make sure you read before class. Do lots of problems. Tests are rather difficult.

His lectures are mandatory and you should not miss them. He engages with the class as best as he can. Yet, his test questions (hard)do not always reflect the lectures. You need to understand the concepts thoroughly and then be able to apply them to any question.VarietyofPractice problems are necessary. Helpful at office hours. Wants you to do well.

I literally cannot stand this woman. I didn't find the right words until I read the comments but "full of herself" is spot on. I didn't learn any new thing in her course. Feedback from her was terrible, and asking her for any kind of advice or direction would lead to me wanting to drop the course, and stop caring about the subject all together.

Professor is very full of herself - not helpful at all. All comments said are correct. Worst class ever - do NOT take it if you don't need it. I'd lean towards an environmental engineering intro class if I wanted the same material but that taught in a better way, with a less condescending nature.
For an Intro to Sustainability course, the grading was so subjective it was difficult to get an A.  Don't take if you need an easy distribution requirement.

A single worst class ever. TAs grade with incomprehensible criteria making it impossible to get full grade. homeworks complex and difficult although due every single week. TA seem to have pride in torturing undergraduates. Although the material is easy, the assignments and tests will be out to get you, not helping you learn and enjoy the subject.

She's the teacher for Intro to Sustainability. This is probably one of the easiest classes I've ever taken in terms of content. The only reason I go to class is because she takes attendance with clickers. However, her tests can be hard because there about three right answers for every question. Also, she is way full of herself.
he is awesome could not ask for a better guy
he is an awesome guy...could not get any better.
This man is just too fabulous...honestly, i highly recommend taking the course. It's SO easy for N credit and it's interesting.
He's entertaining and all... but seriously folks, I know how to use a VCR; why don't I get paid to teach the class?
GREAT class, GREAT professor!!

The course material is engaging, professor seems checked out. 40% of grades not entered at end of term representing more than 55% of the grade; all grading done by TA. Unpopulated due dates in Canvas, outdated assignment files (java app used Java 7; EOL'd 2015), no office hours (appointment only), and rarely responds to emails. Avoid if possible.

I've heard he used to be great, but now he's phoning it in. Assignments have a lot of errors--his assistant does them, and he doesn't check. Won't answer questions. Barely communicates with students. Doesn't participate in discussions. Like being taught by a rock.
One of best teachers you'll ever have! He knows exactly what he is teaching and helps the student to achieve whatever they want. His skills and papers in drone hacking are top notch!
The class was really good and we learned a lot.
rating_tags: Gives good feedback--Participation matters--ACCESSIBLE OUTSIDE CLASS

comment: Great teacher, great researcher.
engaging conversationalist; passive

Very smart man. if your not interested in philosophy then you will find his lectures boring. He writes on the chalkboard alot, which i find helpful because philosophy is a process, and one that needs to be recorded so you can keep your place--and go back to ideas

horrible. horrible. probably the most boring person i have ever come across in my life. he doesn't talk to students while lecturing, he either talks to the blackboard or the floor. No eye contact. No smiling. Its horrible.

Moyar is kinda boring. His lectures are very detailed but his presentation is pretty dry. He tries to make jokes but nobody ever laughs. The readings were mildly entertaining. I had Plato, Descartes, Rousseau and Nietzsche. The grading was kinda opaque but I still got an A. Even if you bomb the papers you can always do a rewrite.
No Comments
he cool
rating_tags: Skip class? You won't pass.--SO MANY PAPERS--TEST HEAVY

comment: He's a down to earth guy, love his class. His ideology is clear and leaves you thinking about your own life at the end of class. && yes that accent and jeans just make it easyier to pay attention! ;)
I love Marius!

Intro to Bioethics... ever seen Grey's Anatomy? He's reminded me of Alex Karev since day one. And yes, he is that arrogant. On the flip side, most sections were cohesive and he definitely progressed over the course of the year.
Ih ih, great TA, nice, helpful, very cute accent, and those jeans.... :)
No flexibility and disorganized, dropping out of this program is much more feasible than putting up with this horrible professor.
Absolutely horrible. I don't know how Hopkins still allows her to work there.

At a recent in person orientation the disdain in the room for this woman was palpable. So glad she is no longer the director. Hopefully the new person can get it back on track so that students don't feel like they're paying 120k for a piece of paper and no new knowledge or skills.

If you are assigned Laura as a mentor, you should request a change asap. She doesn't care if you finish your degree on time. You can just graduate the "next semester"...without your cohort and with extra tuition.
Shaw has run this program into the ground. Thankfully, she was pressured/forced to step down as director, but she still teaches. And unfortunately, the watered down current program is her design.

LFS is an absolute disgrace to Hopkins. She is condescending. While telling students there is no right answer, she conditions them to respond and maybe even think the way she does because her answer is the only "right" answer.

Every week is a lecture (~2x 40 min each), reading material, and written assignments. Exams are lengthy and difficult. Start early as it truly took me all week to complete the discussions/assignment. Very tough class but I learned a lot. Prof is very accessible via email, kind and gives thorough feedback on everything.
rating_tags: Get ready to read--Gives good feedback--Lots of homework

comment: Get ready to read and go through a lot of material, but Dr. Duplantier is a very helpful professor and will meet with you.
rating_tags: Get ready to read--Test heavy--Accessible outside class

comment: I was hesitant to take this course because the rating on the professor was not good, but I am so glad I did! Dr. Duplantier is the sweetest ever! He goes into length to help you understand, and is very helpful with feedback. Assignments and exams are hard, but you learn so much from him because he shows you how to apply concepts, not just memorize!

Nice guy and very accessible if you have questions. Gives feedback on every assignment. Not an easy class in the slightest though. Discussion posts take a whole week to answer, the midterm and final were challenging. Not necessarily hard, just A LOT.
rating_tags: Gives good feedback--Lots of homework--Get ready to read

comment: He's the replacement for Matt Hall who was apparently a legend. If Matt Hall is available, take his class. If he's not... Dr. D's a boring lecturer & his slides are awful. He isn't good at making clear points. He's nice but isn't super aware of what his students need. His exams can be brutal so focus more on his lectures & review concepts yourself
Excellent class.  Great lab.  I particularly enjoyed the field trips and Professor Elbert's breadth of knowledge.

He like many instructors and advisors at JHU are over inflated, pompous, arrogant, don't return emails promptly, he like his predecessor, never returned my emails about my thesis so I missed the opportunity to even do a thesis!  Frankly JHU has no business offering online education with the attitudes of the advisors!!

He is AMAZING! He puts a lot of time and energy into the course and is dedicated to making sure people understand the concepts - even going so far as to providing information on underlying concepts (such a calculus) to make sure no one is left behind. He is an excellent writer and communicator. I wish he taught all of the classes in my program!
Really smart and interesting, but demanding.  He is relaxed and funny, but don't let that fool you.  Do your work.

Elbert is a tough teacher, but very good and very knowledgeable. Go to him if you want to learn and to be challenged. If you are a lazy student, he is NOT the professor for you. Get ready to take notes!

Had him for 171.301 Upper level electromagnetism. Amazing and charismatic guy! His stories are hilarious and he makes a poor designed class and curriculum bearable. He makes lots of mistakes on his derivations and his lectures are not useful to learn the material, but he is a cool guy!
I agree with last reviewer. Prof. C.L. Chien does not teach the physics lab. He is a professor spending a lot of efforts on students.

Other reviewers who reference him as teaching physics lab have the wrong professor.  There are two Chiens in the dept., CL Chien and CY Chien.  CY taught the lab.  The class I had with CL was very interesting.  He explained not only the physics, but also took some time to talk about the people who made the discoveries. Definitely a great professor!
I gained nothing in the long run from this class
Whole lot of arbitrary grading. Expectations not defined at all.
Worst classes at Hopkins (none of TAs speak English and youre only graded on Statistical Analysis--and no, not the easy one), avoid like the plague.

He's hands down the best prof for MTH161 at UoR. His lectures are clear and it is very easy to take notes in a systematic manner for his class. Don't look at my grade, my session had the hardest exams ever for this course!

Lorman is one of the best calculus teachers here at Rochester and definitely the best MTH 161 teacher. He always asks if anyone needs clarification and explains concepts well. Very accessible outside and in classroom. Kinda funny too. Definitely take his class. He is a fair grader to say the least.

I had Lorman for Calc II for bio which is known for being the harder Calc II class at Hopkins. Lorman did a really great job of teaching complex topics in a way that is pretty easy to understand, even if you don't love math. He's a super nice guy and definitely wants to see his students succeed. Tests are manageable if you study.

I took Honors Single Variable Calculus with him.  He is one of the most caring professors I have and never judges you for having trouble with the material. He made extra office hours and class hours when students requested it and was always available to anyone who needed extra help.  The material was extremely difficult but he graded very fairly.

Amazing professor. Clearly cares a lot about his students' well beings, and is always available to make sure everyone understands the material through and through. Also treats math like its an art form, which makes the class much more enjoyable.

First day of class, Misha told us to be prepared for a lot of work, and he wasn't wrong, it's a fair amount of programming. There's a good amount of math background, but you're not explicitly tested on it. He lets you choose what to implement on the projects so long as you hit 30 points, so you choose what excites you.
Very supportive
Very nice professor.He helps a lot..he is an expert in his field and has very solid math background which can help you.. He is laid back..if you work you will go fine...otherwise i dont know:)
He is a very good teacher. The homeworks are A LOT of work, though. It is a fun class, and Misha keeps it interesting.

A lot of work but the prof is fun and very laid back.  Definatly start the projects early.  You don't really have to come to class to do the homework since the notes are all posted, but it's hard to do well on the test without his explanations in class.  One of my favorite CS profs to date.

I took Philosophy of Religion with Dr. Gross. The man is genuinely nice and explains complex concepts in an "easy to understand" way. You'll get some heavy readings but he'll review them in class. I advice you take a class with him. As a non-philosophy major, I learned a lot of cools things about how we think.
Fascinating Class about Religion.  I enjoyed it a lot and Gross is a great lecturer.  Really captivating.  TAs not so much.
Fantastic professor. His lectures are very organized and understandable, and he is very enthusiastic about the subject.  He encourages students to come to his office hours for help.
Philosophy of Language. I definitely fell asleep often. Sometimes the material was difficult, sometimes interesting. Go talk to him in office hours after starting your papers. Really helpful.
Extremely smart, utterly non-pretentious, extremely enthusiastic, and helpful outside of class.

Amazing professor! The department is small, so the class was full of students from other majors. He really cares about his students & expects participation in class. Best to be prepared. Some overlap in material with his other classes. Quizzes & tests are fairly easy if you pay attention :) Charismatic & very passionate about the subject
rating_tags: Get ready to read--Participation matters--Amazing lectures

comment: One of the best professors at Hopkins He really cares about his students and is willing to work with you His lectures are amazing and draw from the readings but with a lot of added material, so definitely don't miss class if you can avoid it He really appreciates student involvement in class and expects participation Tests & quizzes are sorta easy
rating_tags: Get ready to read--Participation matters--Amazing lectures

comment: Amazing lectures, little to no homework, manageable readings and frequent gradebook entries. Fantastic professor and person. You have to show up for class though because he introduces new material in lecture A LOT
Friendly, good-natured, generally concerned about the students and their views, and offers a nuanced, broad overlook on some of the more controversial topics.  Taking his class has been a pleasure.
No Comments

Lectures were engaging. Assignments had minimal rubrics but were graded in a way that didn't compare with guidelines. She spoke of how disrespectful it is to the teaching team and made statements like she asks herself why she still teaches when students asked about the way papers were graded. There was extra credit opportunity.

Dr. Howe is so amazing I had her for 2 classes. Shes super engaging and the sweetest funniest professor ever. You can tell she really loves what she does, and her stories about her work are so intriguing. People be doing too much just bc yall dont get the grade yall want but literally show up, participate and put in the work. You will be fine!

Dr. Howe was one of the most incredible professors I had at JHU. She cares deeply about her profession and it shows in her teaching. She is kind and understanding with her students. Her class is enjoyable to attend, and the assignments are difficult, but fun. Would 100% love to take another class with her.
Very interesting and engaging lectures. Lots of papers even though not considered writing intensive. Kind of a tough grader.
Very engaging lectures and will answer any question if people do not understand a concept
Dr. Howe is AMAZING. Her lectures are incredibly engaging and the class is so interesting.

Dr. Howe is THE BEST professor ever. She has the most interesting lectures (talking about forensic psychology and actual cases) and her assignments are actually FUN. Her assignments are mirrors of what she does every day and has gotten me so interested in forensic psychology. I would take any and all classes that she offers.

Professor Yarmolinskaya teaches linguistics in a way that is interesting and easy to understand. Her lectures were engaging and she made her lecture materials available to all students which made it easy to review. Exams are challenging but fair and she provides many resources to prepare.
I really this professor, she's really nice and she is able to explain linguistics in a way that is easy to understand.
rating_tags: Get ready to read--Caring--Graded by few things

comment: Weirdly structured course (tests were based only on the reading, homework was based only on the lecture material) which was difficult to keep up with, but the professor herself is really helpful and super nice, and her lectures were engaging and interesting.
rating_tags: Get ready to read--Amazing lectures --Clear grading criteria

comment: Great lecturer, class is a little stagnant but well prepared and knowledgable.

Prof. Yarmolinskaya is a wonderful lecturer and typically structures her classes the same (well-planned lectures along with weekly discussion posts, 2 exams, and a larger project). At times, it can be hard to apply what you are learning but such is the nature of linguistics classes of these types. Genuinely enjoyed her class and very friendly!

While the homework and tests were pretty difficult and lengthy, Bah made up for this with excellent lectures and an emphasis on students asking questions. His lectures were both insightful and entertaining, and he would often directly relate the math to real world phenomena, more so than most other professors.

Prof. Bah is a great teacher. The assignments were tough, but Dr. Bah and his TA were very helpful in answering questions. The only complaint I have is the lack of physical demos, this being a class on mechanics. 
Both of the other reviews use the difficulty of the class to detract from the course's quality, and I think this is unfair.
The exams are unreasonably hard for a 200-level course. The average for the two midterms are probably just 50% because the exams were very long, no one could finish.

The tests are extremely computationally intensive. Expect a 50% class median for exams. His style is super unreasonable for this class that should've been easy. The only good thing is that Professor Bah is caring to his students.

This shouldn't be a challenging class, but he makes it unnecessarily hard. Exam problems are confusing, ambiguous, and not self-explanatory. His command of English is clearly not good enough to make students understand WHAT HE EXACTLY MEANS! Too many problems involve an unreasonable amount of calculations.  He tried to be helpful but not really

Literally cannot say enough good things about him and his classes. I received some of the most insightful feedback on my film projects over my four years at Hopkins from him. He is funny, cares about his students, and makes sure you WANT to learn a lot just by keeping his classes super engaging and interesting. Truly stands out in the film dept.
He may come off a little cantankerous, but I'd be hard pressed to think of a teacher who cared more about his students and subject.  He treats you like an adult.
Best teacher I have ever had, will ever have. More than a professor, a mentor, a confidant, a friend.  The reason why the JHU film program is the best one out there.
Greatest teacher at Hopkins hands down.
No Comments
This class has a lot of coursework. The professor lectures for a long time and the tests are heavily focused on lecture material. The exams are not hard, but the grading is picky.
rating_tags: Get ready to read--Skip class? You won't pass.--Tough grader

comment: A bit disappointed by Phonology this year: Take it if you want low stress and easy pass, reconsider if you want to learn more about linguistics. Few assignments, extremely slow feedback, easy content since we covered many topics in phonology BRIEFLY. Felt like I didn't learn a lot and Prof didn't have high expectations for us anyways.

Taking Cognition with Wilson. Really cool guy, obviously knows a lot about the subject and tries to make it interesting. Unfortunately, a lot of the subject matter is just incredibly lofty and theoretical and nothing is really concrete, even with explanation.
very nice and approachable but class was more based on computers than I thought it would be. Lectures were often dry.

Took Phonology with Wilson. The material was interesting, though I'm not sure what the point was in most of the lectures. Wilson has no clue what his TAs do, and needs to be more aware of how they grade. I was not impressed by how little Wilson knew about the way the class was actually going, as well as about final grades.
Worst professor ever. Rude to student

Tough class, homework is long and difficult. Professor Eyink is clearly an extremely brilliant man and really such a sweetheart, and you will learn A LOT taking his class and talking to him generally.
Very difficult and too much work load

Avoid the numerical linear algebra taught by this professor. He posts lectures during weekend and thanksgiving break which must be understood to finish homework. Homework is time consuming, and the last few homework can be quite difficult. TA's grade harshly and some TA's don't understand the materials well. The course materials are also boring.

The worst class I have ever taken. The professor keeps making mistakes when giving lectures and the stuff he teaches is not enough to do the problem sets which is very hard and time-consuming. Also has unclear grading guidelines-- he told us that 90-100 is an A but he actually give A- for all grade under 95%. If you are not AMS major, avoid.
rating_tags: Lots of homework--Graded by few things--Tough grader

comment: He is OK.
It seems as though he didn't have that much interest in teaching, it was really hard to understand him and his lectures were not well organized
No Comments
Midterm was hard, most unclear lecture ever.

So nice! Very relaxed and fair, if you have circumstances that cause you to miss a quiz or something she'll be very happy to allow you to retake it and such. Overall an amazing professor and extremely passionate about China, the Chinese language, and Chinese culture. Definitely recommend her!
she's so cute and so fair....as long as u do the work and put some time into studying for the quizzes and do the compositions and presentations well, it's def. easy to get an A.
Nice and grades fairly.  Tries hard to make it fun too :)
Nice old lady. Grades very fairly.
The hardest homework you will ever do.  The saddest glares you will ever see.
No Comments
No Comments
The hardest homework you will ever do.  Period.
Too many quizzes, exams and assignments. Although there was one extra credit assignment at the end, you have to score well through the course to end up with a decent grade.

My biggest is the time it took to get feedback from assignments. I also didn't feel like anything I submitted was actually read.  In addition, questions we would post to blackboard (online learning tool) would not get answered for 2-3 days even during finals! The hands-off attitude de-motivates one participate or learn.

Worst professor ever seen in my life. Grades are based upon her mood. Gives good grades to students she likes and poor grades to students who try to raise an issue against her grading, way of asking vague questions on exams and way she embarrasses the student by making him or her feel like a dumb.

She taught Molecular Biology for the AAP program. She is the worst teacher. She asks incomprehensible questions on tests and quizzes and excepts you to know the answers. She is horrible but she is the best of two evils.
He speaks very low and in an accent, but as long as you sit towards the front you will be absolutely fine. I really enjoyed this class. His notes are very structured and relative to the material.

His accent is hard to understand and his midterms are pretty hard.  You don't need to come to lecture b/c he just puts proofs (that are in the textbook) on the board. Keep up with the homework and do his practice exams and the class is fairly easy

Overall, good at explaining things, really nice board diagrams that will be very helpful when studying later. A lot of his lectures focus on proofs of a theorem or definition. However, his public speaking skills are not the best and it can be hard to understand what he is saying because he sometimes mumbles. Sit in the front and you will be fine.

Professor Wang is very good at expressing mathematical concepts. He draws very neat diagrams on the blackboard. He is friendly and doesn't hesitate to help students whenever they have questions. He is passionate in math too.

Dr. Roller is really friendly and enthusiastic. He's sort of a picky grader on some grammar things and he's a big fan of you knowing grammatical constructions and sequence of tense, etc. The only downside is he can be pretty loud and slams books on the table, plus for Advanced Latin he assigns a midterm (not cumulative!) and a final paper 7-10 page
Prof Roller is great--he's really excited about the material and always gives interesting lectures. He is also readily available if you need help on any of the essays  or anything on the material.
Constructing Autocracy was one of the worst books I've ever read. It could be used as a substitute tranquilizer.
His enthusiasm for the material is almost contagious.  A lot of reading, but lectures are entertaining.  Fair grader, exams are passable.
Fun
He is not that harsh of a grader. If you're a good writer and you put in effort you'll do well. He's a great professor and a really chill person.
He has very high expectations, and he is very harsh in his critique of essays. Overall, not a good teacher.
Very hard to find after class.  Extremely harsh grader who has exceptionally high expectation of prior philosophical knowledge. Pretty bad@$$ person though.

Prof. Maouelainin is amazing!! She's passionate, funny, patience and smart. The way she teaches stimulates your curiosity and really makes the lecture interesting. She gives good feedback and is always reachable whenever via email or during office hours. Come to class prepared and be open to the class, I guarantee you'll learn a lot and get an A!
BEAUTIFUL,AMAZING,HAPPY,GREAT,ETC. SHE LOVES HER JOB AND U CAN TELL- WORK INVOLVED, BUT WELL WORTH IT TO SEE HER SMILE WHEN U GET IT RIGHT

Good professora!Participated in the class, she will give you a good grade.The quiz is not that hard,all you have to remember is the grammar. She is very fair to every student in her classroom, answer every single question patiently.Take her class even you have nothing known about Spanish before, you will still  learn a lot.

She is a great teacher, makes the class interesting. She keeps you engaged. She is really fair, and very reasonable. I recommend her class. You will learn alot. After a few weeks in get class your level of Spanish will increase.
Excellent professor. Very motivating Great videos for the online classes
The homework is very difficult assigned reading is far more than the video overviews Prof need to add way more videos to explain the subject and the scope of the reading

I liked the course structure and Mr. Chambers was quick to reply to questions. Class ramps up in difficulty too, so plan to increase your effort starting in mod4. Final was much more difficult than the prior 7 modules. Seems to be the norm at JHU as surveys are in mod7, and profs want a strong rating. Overall, I thought it was a good course.

I did not enjoy Professor Chambers. He is not a bad guy. He is very thin skinned and did not like dissension. I think many students do well with him, so this isn't a warning to avoid him. He is very picky on homework. The exam is a bear.

Please don't take this professor if you don't have to. The content is exciting and fun to learn. However, she is inconsistent with grading and feedback. Canvas does not align with the syllabus at all. She made the course more difficult than it needed to be.

I had technical problems with a quiz and she said she would reopen for me to take but she never did. I didn't matter how much time and work I place in doing the assignments, it was never good enough to get a good grade.
She grades hard and does not really give much extra credit to help out students.
rating_tags: Tough grader--Get ready to read--So many papers

comment: She may be nice but direct communication with her may get tough towards the end of the semester. She's very strict to the syllabus. A ton of writing and is a harsh grader. Everything is based off of the lectures. If it's a question about your grade, she won't answer even if you're confused about something.
rating_tags: Tough grader--Clear grading criteria--So many papers

comment: Workload builds over the semester, especially once long assignments hit, but manageable if you keep up and seek out TAs and office hours.

Despite being a 3 credit class, prepare for 6 assignments a week, plus papers toward the end. Post-labs and papers are long, almost requiring going to office hours. Professor's lectures are confusing, so be prepared to learn most of the content yourself. Regardless, the class is helpful for learning biochemical techniques used in research labs.

Once it reaches the Long Assignments, instructions are unclear and grading is harsh. There is a highly limiting word count, yet they expect you to explain everything in painful detail. Point deductions and feedback are unclear. Expect the professor to post homework due Monday on Saturday rather than after your 1 class/week.
rating_tags: Tough grader--Lots of homework--Accessible outside class

comment: I had Dr. Sorenson for PEBL and she is my favorite professor so far! PEBL was wonderful, and I learned so much new material even though I had no background in biochemistry. Dr. Sorenson is very helpful during office hours and during the pre-lab lecture. Course load is demanding, but doable if you put in the work. Would definitely recommend!
rating_tags: LOTS OF HOMEWORK--ACCESSIBLE OUTSIDE CLASS--Clear grading criteria

comment: R
awful af

Many readings and tedious assignments for each module. The grading is very subjective and comments and feedbacks are not helpful at all. Doesn't indicate where and why points are taken off. Hard to get ahold of when you have questions. When asking for feedback on a certain grade, she ignores your email or responds with an attitude.
rating_tags: Tough grader--Group projects--Graded by few things

comment: Prof. Ganzermiller is very hands-off and her grading criteria is very vague while the feedback is not very useful. It seems like you are doing everything correctly but you can never score high enough as anticipated. The grading curve is tough and there are many readings to do for each module.
rating_tags: Group projects--Graded by few things--Tough grader

comment: Very friendly during lectures and made jokes often, but claimed class would be curved to a B+ and so he would indicate how many points you could add to your raw score to get your curved grade on exams, but in the end the class was not curved to a B+ and was curved lower. He curved down from what he originally stated as fact.
rating_tags: Tests? Not many--GRADED BY FEW THINGS

comment: Makes it clear what will be on the test, pretty fair grading. Knows his stuff and makes funny remarks.
Good prof, awesome math jokes

Ross is the GOAT. He is so passionate, funny, and very accessible outside of class. He truly cares about his students and wants to see them do well. FBBC is a tough class and test heavy but Dr. Ross makes it extremely enjoyable. If you have the chance to take his class, you will learn a lot and won't regret it!

Dr Ross is the goat and I enjoyed his class overall (albeit lecture and test-heavy). Lots of resources offered like office hours, recorded lectures, detailed notes, etc so take advantage of them. Grading is fair and he has a policy to drop the lowest test score. Content is interesting but you need to be passionate about it to do well in the class.
Nice boston accent
rating_tags: Clear grading criteria--Test heavy--Graded by few things

comment: He obviously is very passionate about what he does. While the topics do get complex at times, the supplemental information he gives in lectures and practice exams will help tremendously. Make sure to understand each module thoroughly as his exams are very conceptual.

FBBC by itself is just so information heavy but Dr. Ross did an excellent job teaching it in the fall. Attendance is somewhat mandatory (iClicker) but you can watch the lecture videos if you miss any class. You can bring 4 pages of notes to each exam, which you will probably end up filling to the brim with lecture content.
rating_tags: Get ready to read--Hilarious--Graded by few things

comment: FBBC is generally just a content heavy class, but Dr. Ross does a great job of being an accessible and passionate lecturer. It's very test heavy, but Ross had a policy to drop your lowest score. I thought grading was fair and they are always do regrade requests. Lectures were recorded when I took it, but going to class will help with content.

Mao is one of my favorite professors I have had at Hopkins. It is obvious he cares about his students. My emails were responded to quickly and thoughtfully. His office hours are incredibly helpful, and he is more than happy to go over your essays in detail if you have questions. He is also just a profound guy, I have always enjoyed our seminars.
rating_tags: Get ready to read--Gives good feedback--Caring

comment: Hands down, Mao is the best professor that I've had at JHU. His eloquence can be intimidating at first, but once you talk with him, you realize how friendly he is and how much he genuinely cares about his students. His classes are work heavy, but he  will go out of his way to give you any help or extensions you need.

It is very rare that I am astounded by a teacher. But I am completely, utterly astonished by Prof. Mao. Each of his phrases are colored by acute insight, and he tosses off pithy bits of eloquence like nothing. He is incisive and brilliant; he adores words. More importantly, however, he is kind, generous, and one of the best teachers I've ever had.

Great professor--a bit of an intellectual snob, but you can't say he doesn't deserve it. He's basically been employed, educated or tenured by every top university in the US, and JHU is lucky to have him. I enjoyed all of his classes, and he really helped open my eyes to what criticism is and how to write it. Emphasizes the importance of good ideas

Professor Hager is an excellent teacher, very easy to understand, good at explaining, and really funny. I highly recommend his course for anyone at JHU interested in computer science. Don't play tetris in class though, he'll call you out on it.
useful class
No Comments
No Comments

I signed up for two of Prof's H classes. I wish I had taken more classes with her. She was excellent! She was the only person in the program who really taught me counseling skills. She knows her stuff so well and is so approachable that you can discuss any counseling topics with her. I recommend her 100%!

Whoever wrote those bad reviews is an exception, probably someone who resented having to earn her grade. Professor Hernandez-Wolfe is an EXCELLENT teacher and everyone in the counseling program knows it! She is the best teacher I have ever had. She has so much knowledge and experience, and best of all, she really cares about his students.

Dr. Hernandez-Wolfe is the best professor I ever had. As a mentor she expected the best of me and helped me develop excellent counseling skills. She is warm, friendly and caring. Her commitment to teaching goes beyond the classroom. She was my mentor! This professor brought high standards to the program in regards to teaching and research.

she is very critical in her style, not positive comments at all. and She smirks when she criticizes people. Not clinically tested, came from research background. She will say "I know better", but can't show she can comprehend at all. Very narrow-minded in treatment planning (came from family therapy background, only).  Will pick on petty stuff.
This professor is a very intelligent man, but his accent is too much of a barrier. Do not take his class unless you are confident in understanding the material on your own
rating_tags: Get ready to read--LOTS OF HOMEWORK

comment: He is clearly very intelligent, but he is not good at teaching the material to students.
rating_tags: Skip class? You won't pass.--LOTS OF HOMEWORK--LECTURE HEAVY

comment: I had him for calculus III, he is by far the nicest grader in the math department. He gave over a third of the class solid A's, but he didnt tell us how he would distribute the grades until after the final to make you work more (hence the bad course evaluations). Like most math classes there is a lot of HW though.

"Joey" is a good person and teacher. He's reasonable w/ what he expects from the class and provides a decent amount of resources like backtests to help students succeed. The only issue is the language barrier. His accent is very thick so it's difficult to understand him at first. However, by the end of the semester he becomes easier to understand.
Couldn't learn anything from this class.
For a pretty boring subject he does a phenomenal job in making it interesting and informative. Amazing teacher.
Prof Kociemba is a great teacher, he tries his best to help all the students.
Learn a lot from him. Very interesting class.

Dr Marshburn knows his stuff. He has a gift for explaining math concepts in a way that you can understand. He's always willing to give extra help. And never makes you feel like your questions aren't valid. I would definitely take more of his classes.

Marshburn is a solid professor. He's clear, chill, and he knows his stuff. His lectures are not the most inspiring - they won't leave you thinking "damn that was brilliant", but he covers the material, gives many examples, and is very approachable. His exams are easy compared to the homework. Pay attention and understand the examples he does.

Awesome teacher.  Very clear in his lectures, and when I don't understand something, he's amazing at explaining difficult math concept one on one.  I recommend going to his office hours regularly even if you think you know the material because he'll make you know the material that much better for the exams
Marshburn is an above-average lecturer and an overall likeable teacher (fair grading, tests that cover familiar material, etc.) Wouldn't hesitate to take another one of his courses.
Great professor. Really emphasizes thinking outside the box and being creative. Challenges you to think critically and differently. A little bit crazy but truly one of a kind.
One of the best professors I had.
Thakor acts like he hates the class, but in the end, he is a nice guy.
very very bad person
The worst class ever! If you don't have to, never get it. Teaching is full of mistakes and ambiguity; she doesn't care at all. Grading isn't about how hard you try, it's about  who knows what!!!!!!
Clear and organized presentation of the material. Takes the time to demonstrate theoretical results in details. Welcomes questions and even eventual critics.

She goes pretty fast during lectures (she does write everything down). If you ask a question, she gets flustered and usually doesn't fully answer it. Her lab assignments are vague and she teaches the material used in the labs AFTER the report is due. She made it difficult for me to learn.

Really one of the worst professors I've had she gets angry when you ask questions.  The clad had almost no structure and the lab also had no point.  She couldn't keep my attention.  The class started with 60+ people and 4 weeks in less than 20 people show up to class
Good Grader!

Kuffner is a really great professor. She's a clear lecturer and is also very helpful in office hours. She sent out a survey every few weeks to check in to see if people were understanding the material. There was an option on the survey to ask for more help and she would meet with you to talk about where you're struggling and what you need.

Professor Kuffner was one of my favorite professors this semester. She is understanding and has a fair grading policy. The exams are straightforward if you know the material. If you have questions, her office hours are a great resource.

Professor Kuffner is a great calculus professor and is clear and engaging in her instruction. Her voice is quiet, but she has a great personality when you get to know her. Definitely reach out to her during office hours for extra help if you need it!
rating_tags: Accessible outside class--Group projects--Lots of homework

comment: Dr. Ender is very passionate about the subject and brings a lot of knowledge to the table. She allows students a lot of freedom to explore topics of interest in ungraded group projects and presentations. Overall very chill class with enjoyable readings; only downside is that lecture can be a bit boring at times.
Didn't like this class. Professor made other students feel uncomfortable.

Very sweet prof, who clearly cares a lot about her students and really tries to make a effort to make her classes a good learning experience. Very knowledgeable and if you like the subject matter, you will definitely get a lot out of her class. Only knock is that she is a lil disorganized, in terms of grading criteria and assignment guidelines.

Professor Ender is very sweet; she cares a lot about her students and is always willing to help. I would recommend Heart Matters to students who are genuinely interested in the course's topics (the lectures can be quite lengthy, good bit of reading). She is a little disorganized but won't hesitate to further explain instructions if needed.
rating_tags: Gives good feedback--Get ready to read--Caring

comment: Professor Ender is a wonderful teacher. She is passionate about the subject she teaches and she is passionate about helping her students do the best they possibly can.
She was an excellent professor.  Very approachable.
rating_tags: Gives good feedback--Accessible outside class--Online Savvy

comment: Respectful to the students. Accessible.

This was not a very approachable professor. She made everyone call her Dr. and people consistently felt uncomfortable asking her questions, always apologizing for interrupting the lecture she herself seemed bored by. The quizzes were difficult and often did not reflect the lecture, which was disappointing because the whole class studied hard!

Shes a great professor! There is alot of reading you will need to do to learn the subject and practice the problems. She provides you will all the material you need and the grading criteria is straightforward.
rating_tags: Gives good feedback--Get ready to read--Clear grading criteria

comment: One of my worse experiences at Johns Hopkins is this class. I see the other ratings and they all closely align with my personal experience. It is now the week of the final yet 50% of our coursework has yet to be graded but the ones that are graded is essentially failing. Working full time this class adds on a lot of stress with no clear direction.
rating_tags: Skip class? You won't pass.--So many papers--Tough grader

comment: No clear grading criteria, barely any feedback on work yet grades harshly. Inaccessible outside of class. I personally have industry experience in Machine Learning prior to the class yet the way this Professor is teaching is not useful and things doesnt seem to tie up together.
rating_tags: Graded by few things--So many papers--Tough grader

comment: Worst experience ever. Dropped out since Professor was impossible to get ahold of and never taught what was assigned.
rating_tags: Lots of homework--Get ready to read--Tough grader

comment: Class is structured weird. Shows some math formulas during lecture without actually doing examples then hands out homework requiring 20+ hours to figure out. Projects are coding and writing papers yet no real feedback is given on either. Got 30 points off on first project for bad introduction? 7 weeks passed and first project just got graded.
rating_tags: Lots of homework--Get ready to read--Tough grader

comment: DISCLAIMER: I did not have Professor Duncan but was required to watch his recorded lectures on Calculus III topics. Hence, I am only rating the quality of these lectures and cannot say anything about Duncan himself. His recorded lectures are easy to follow. He ensures concepts are simplified and likes to add physical/intuitive interpretations!

Professor Duncan is the BEST professor I've met in the maths department. He not only has a clear teaching style (with a reasonable balance between examples and theorems), but he is also very caring to students. Also, as a physics major, I especially like the way he introduces calc III concepts with a lot of physical intuition.

Duncan's lectures are basically the same as what is in the textbook but he elaborates on things to make sure we understand. Very helpful and always willing to answer questions and help you on the material. Class wasn't curved at all but the median grade was still very high.

Professor Duncan clearly cares most about us learning and is a nice man. He is accessible, replies to emails quickly, and an overall amazing prof. He even listened to our feedback. If you put in the work, you should get the grade you deserve. Well loved by us students.

I am his student at class BU. 450, Customer Analytics. Past ratings may not have been justified. He is a good professor and does not deserve the bad rate. Past ratings do affect the professor's course selection rate. I encourage students to try his class first and then make a final decision.

You need to prepare a lot for this class (lots of readings and video assignments) but personally I really enjoyed the class! The subject (New Product Mangement) is such a difficult concept to grasp but I think he clarified and delievered it well to students. The readings were painful but also helpful.

Totally not relevant to the current world. If you want to waste your time and get some credits you should do this class. Nothing to learn for sure and the exams are a joke..  Participation matters only on paper and you will have to struggle to talk in class - Not at all recommended

You can tell that he is very enthusiastic about this class and tries to bring a lot of new examples.  However, the term project was quite tough. You have to think of a new product idea and then analyze and present how you are going to implement this idea. Make sure that you choose a good team, 50% of the grade comes from this project!

The best professor ever! When we were stressed out, he decided to bake the class some bread. He is so nice. He is also extremely understanding. He teaches really well and when we had alot of work, he was willing to move the date of the exams. He would also show us funny pictures to make the class more interesting :) He is definitely the best.
Not insightful.
great prof, very helpful, easy class
Was always willing to help, cared about whether or not we learned the material.  Really great guy.

His homework and midterms are extremely difficult and he doesn't do a very good job teaching.  I stopped attending his class back in september because his lectures didn't teach me anything at all.  His TA's this year were much more helpful than he was.

His homework and midterms were impossible.  Final was hard too.  He was an awful teacher.  He spent all class doing proofs that we didn't need to know.  I was lucky that I had a good TA, tutor at the learning den and textbook.  He was quite amusing.  Nice butterfly shirt!
No Comments

Nice guy but got grumpy a lot. Exams were ok because he gave us a lot of the problems (with general aspects of them changed), but unfair because they were out of 20 points! Homework was kinda hard at times and the final was so ridiculous. He did end up massively curving the course though so that was ok. I wish him the best in his endeavors!

She is a great lecturer and made a very abstract course tangible to students. The grading criterion is unclear in terms of breakdown making it hard to know how you were doing throughout the semester. In the end, participation became a very important grade (20%!), which lead to many crying about grade deflation when it didn't really occur.
Professor Maru is a good lecturer but deflates grades and does not grade fairly.
rating_tags: Skip class? You won't pass.--Test heavy--Tough grader

comment: Grade deflation compared to Math 202. Professor is very helpful however grading is quite unfair and deflated for an Honors course.

Her Honors Linear Algebra class was very proof heavy and she expected a lot out of students. However, she was very accessible outside of class and always ready to help students when asked. A clear, strong lecturer and great personality make her classes a joy!
Fair grader
Dr. Thomas Colonna is a great professor. I enjoyed his classes and presentations enormousely. I would take them again if I had the choice. One of the best at JHU

Dr. Colonna is a superb professor. His class is a tremendous opportunity for students to learn from an expert in the field, who is extremely talented in teaching the material in a clear and engaging way. In addition, he clearly cares about his class and students, and wants them to succeed. Dr. Colonna is excellent!

No lectures, instead he will do a few chats a semester (optional). He definitely has a sense of humor and he will demonstrate it in his case studies. Case studies do take time as you have to evaluate & assess something ridiculous.  Case studies are way futuristicsci-fi inspired, so even the FDA Center Directors can't help you (yes, I called them)
Good professor, not as tough as it seems
great teacher. took for living off the sun. great sense of teacher, very kind, very smart, goes slowly so everyone understands. great guy
He cares about his students - if you ever want to talk with him he'll talk with you, and explains stuff you need to know.

Took class spring 2008.  Awful teacher.  Lectures are unorganized and it's impossible to understand what he is saying.  If you somehow manage to understand what he's saying, exams are completely lecture based.  The textbook is worthless.
awesome
Brilliant professor, but her English isn't always the best. Once you get down to it, she really is one of the smartest, most passionate professors in the PLAS at Hopkins. By far one of my favorites.

Magda is very passionate about social issues in Bolivia, and she is always accessible to meet with students and will go out of her way to help students find grants and internship opportunities. She is very passionate about what she does and it is contagious.

Horrible professor.  Inaccessable, lectures dont correspond wirh readings, picks at students.  Also tries to cover WAAAYYY too mcuh material in one semester so that everything blurs together and nothing sticks in your brain.
Really bad TA but easy on the eyes
rating_tags: BEWARE OF POP QUIZZES--SO MANY PAPERS--TEST HEAVY

comment: I really enjoyed his TA sections. I would come in not knowing the mechanisms or reactions, and would leave with a better sense of what I should be studying and focus on for tests. He was also funny -- idk how he made organic chemistry enjoyable, but he did. Definitely take organic chemistry with Garvin as your TA. :)
Garvin was SO helpful. He really went out of his way to make sure we understood the material and spent time going over every exam question with us. The exams were tough, but fair.
He is an awesome TA! He reviews everything and explains everything very clearly!

A very interesting class led by an engaging and knowledgeable professor. Her expectations for the papers (short and many rather than few and heavily weighted -- so there's opportunity to improve) can be difficult to gauge and adapt to but don't fear it. She is very understanding and will help you. A great class overall. Laid-back teaching style.
rating_tags: Get ready to read--Inspirational--So many papers

comment: Interesting class
best teacher ever. take the class.

She was pretty nice, but some of her class discussions seemed to be thrown together right before she got there.  Fair grader, but sometimes was vague with the comments.  Overall pretty nice, I had her for a Freshmen Seminar and it was pretty much a joke.  Pretty Easy A.

Most caring, loving professor I know. He really makes sure every person in class understands everything to the fullest extent and is passionate about what he teaches. Please go to office hours, especially for the homework because it is free points. He will also recognize that you haven't gone to class and called me out on it once during TA session.
Professor Ratanalert is definitely one of the best in the ChemBE department and wants you to succeed. He is reachable outside of class and wants you to understand the material.

The professor is great, he's one of the best in ChemBE department. He tries to make his lectures interesting and he really cares about his students' success. Class is also super easy in general, just don't miss homework and show up to exam.

Dr. Ratanalert is everything a professor should be. He cares about each one of his students, is open to any suggestions about his teaching style, cares about the material, and he conveys it in an "easy to understand" manner. I am very lucky to have a professor like him and I advice anyone to seek out a class with this professor, you won't regret it
Dr. Zhao is very approachable, but his thick accent does make it hard to completely understand some lectures. Other than that, he wants everyone to succeed and is pretty active within class.

Very smart man but is not a good lecturer. He rambles about random things and it is impossible to know what is important. He's kind and wholesome and will answer questions but is hard to follow. Talk to him outside of class to understand the material.
Thick accent, broken English. If you are somebody, like me, who does not cope well with professors with accents, avoid his class. I learned nothing, while paying full attention, at his lectures.

Dr. Zhao is a kind, wholesome professor who is a rare example of someone who's deeply passionate about their work but also wants their students to succeed. Tough exams but there are backtests and practice questions. He's happy to go over your exams and is quick to reward points back when appropriate. TL;DR: tough class, but he's on your side.

The way he speaks is incredibly hard to understand as he speaks very quickly and his accent is quite heavy. He speeds through lectures and his PowerPoints have essays written on each page. Difficult to follow along his presentation because it is so unorganized and he does not really address the slide but goes off his own notes.
Professor Konstantopoulos is kind, clear, helpful, and an incredibly effective teacher.  Nothing negative can be said about him or the classes he instructs.

Hard course to begin with, but you'll feel much better as he moves along. His handwriting is very clear and he posts the notes online. Homework sets are hard but tests are fair. There is a nice curve for the class.
Great professor that you can almost always understand through the accent.  Class is still difficult though.
Great teacher.  Hard class but very clear lectures and notes.  Know the lecture examples.

I found his teaching style to be amazing. Often challenged students and engaged students during class. Easy to talk to after class or during office hours. Remarkable teacher. Do back tests, final was extremely difficult, but generous curve. I would take all my classes from him if possible!
Very hard final exam (make sure you are really prepared for the tests). Doing the practice exams on e-reserves is a must. He is a very likable professor, though.

A good professor overall. He teaches the concepts well, and he respects every student. But don't expect an easy A, and you have to work hard (tests may sometimes be difficult). Be sure to READ before attending class. I thought I did meh on the finals but I ended up with an A. Generous curving if you ask me.

Very easy to understand. Make sure to do the practice tests on eReserve. Has a fairly generous curve for the class -- 83%ish became an A. Show up to lecture -- very useful. Overall, good teacher, but doesn't seem to like emails from students. Voice is monotone, but he's still interesting. Good professor.
She's really cool! She has a lot of inciteful things to say and really got the class talking. She requires a fair amount of writing, but is a pretty even grader. Well worth taking.

Professor Suk is etremely passionate about her work. But much more importantly she is comitted to seeing that her students understand the material which is an extremely hard task to accomplish when you are working a level as high as hers. It was my most influential class of the semester and it made me reevaluatethewayIpercieve theworld.TAKEHERCLASS
This is one Professor that will stun you with her intellect and wit. She will challenge your notions of reality and perception. Her class is a pure mind orgasm!
Really a great professor.  Goes out of way to help us out of class on papers.  Class material was rough, but she helped me through it.
lectures are fun but Walters tries to hard to impress students. Some think he's insecure.  Readings are heavy but tests Ok.  Walters' knowledge of history is really superficial at best.
No Comments

Ron Walters is a great historian and a fantastic teacher.  I trust that you will learn as much from him as I did.  Ron's scholarship as well as his character set a standard.  Wise, kind, soft-spoken, and completely unpretentious, Ron Walters is a rarity in academia: an emotionally-mature adult male.
great thesis advisor.  one of the nicest professors i've ever had. really cares about students.

Extremely good professor. His classes are hard, but if you're willing to spend some time working on them, he will make it worth it! He can be a little scary when you don't know him, but he really is devoted to his students.

Previous comments are a travesty.  Katz is a great professor with an accent that put a smile on my face everyday.  Previous ratings most likely due to subpar grade performance, but Katz can't be blamed for that.  No longer teaches thermodynamics, but is a pleasure of a professor, take his classes if you like to challenge yourself.
After scheduling students' lab time to conflict with the class - "Do we have class tomorrow? You bet your boots we have class tomorrow!"
An overall good guy
Nice guy, interesting lectures

Professor Paquette is easily the best History professor I have ever encountered at Hopkins. Not only is he extremely knowledgeable and passionate about the subject material, but he is the rare professor that truly cares about his students. For all JHU History majors, it is a must to take any class with him.
Encouraging and give credits to efforts
He gives a lot of reading but his lectures are very interesting and he is exceptionally helpful if you visit his office hours.
Great prof, very good lectures, and the TA's were very helpful. Just a nice guy overall, definitely take his class if you're thinking about it.

Dr. Bett was very flexible and accommodating to my absences (excused and unexcused), but his lectures were a touch dry, especially for someone new to the subject (Hellenistic Philosophy). You can do the readings or not do them honestly but its better to just do them so you dont have to go back when its time to write papers. Only 3 papers for class

Interesting subject (Intro to Greek Philosophy). Prof. Bett did a great job of explaining concepts, so much so that reading the texts was not strictly necessary to do well in the class (although they were interesting).
I had him for intro to greek philosophy. was very clear about the material, i rarely did the reading and was fine.
I love her

Took Contemporary French II as well as Franco-Caribbean Lit with her as professor. Extremely intelligent and organized, she created a really sophisticated syllabus and engaged students in very thoughtful & challenging discussions that truly inspired interest in the material. She's at Duke now, but will be missed at Johns Hopkins!

Took French Cinema with her and it was absolutely amazing. The class content was fascinating; I think I learned more in that class about film and history than in any other class, and my French improved a lot as well. She's also genuinely interested in her students, and is a very fair grader. And she's gorgeous, with impeccable style.
No Comments

The instructor is okay. I didn't see the relevance for Poli Sci, not even along political theory lines. More appropriate for Writing Sems/Philosophy. Very small class, think 4. Overall a tough grader esp for the niche course content. you can still do well but not worth the laborious exercises imo and I might've dropped if S/U wasn't a thing

A really unusual class but absolutely worth it. A lot of class is dedicated to imagining real life situations in which you'd say one thing rather than another, and this was a lot of fun. Some of the most I've laughed in a class. You're expected to do a lot of work but it is not too harshly graded. I was told the class average at one point was an A-
rating_tags: Gives good feedback--Lots of homework--Participation matters

comment: The class content was ok in my opinion but I don't think he was really good at "teaching" what he was so harshly grading and also sometimes wouldn't let you speak or convey your idea. He would shut you down sometimes subtly sometimes not so subtly (i.e. with a scoff). Also class felt like experimental which makes sense when grad "students" teach
rating_tags: Gives good feedback--Get ready to read--Tough grader

comment: CJ is engaging and clear and class was thoroughly enjoyable and enlightening but the workload imo was too unreasonable. Roughly 40-50 pages reading AND essay of 2000+ words due EVERY week. It also seemed like he would grade harshly. I think many people dropped and it's 4/5 in the class now. The instructor is great but the work is too unreasonable
rating_tags: Get ready to read--Amazing lectures--So many papers

comment: Definitely an amazing professor. I took her class before even starting my freshman year of college and she was so accommodating to my (and my peers) situation! She was also a very interesting person and it was clear she was dedicated to math.
Professor Sui is very accommodating and cares about the understanding of her students. She constantly ensures the information "makes sense". Her office hours are helpful and laid back.
rating_tags: Gives good feedback--Accessible outside class--Participation matters

comment: She was very informative during office hours and very funny. She wants to help you to understand the information.

Sui Tang is the worst professor I've had at Hopkins. Her lectures are terrible and non-informative, her TAs are unhelpful and don't make things clear, and her final exam was by far the most unfair test I have ever taken. A class average in the 40s in Calculus II is embarrassing and reflects poorly on her as a teacher. Avoid her class at all cost!

Professor McCarty speaks almost incomprehensibly soft, like he is speaking to himself. This makes it difficult to follow his material. His exam questions are very tricky. Worst professor out of the three General Biology professors. Learn all the names and equations you don't think you'll need to know.
Really laid back class. The material was difficult in the beginning, but gradually eased up to the point of being pointless. Easy to get a good grade if you put in the effort

really nice old prof; a bit absent minded sometimes; very lenient and is tenured so can do what he wants (field trips, take home exams). very fair, but teaches some hard material so that part is hard.

His powerpoints notes explain things really well. He really likes teaching, but its obvious that he's shy about talking in a 300 person classs. Out of the three lecturers in the class, he was the best. He was especially enthusisatic when teaching about plants since thats his research areas. His test questions were tricky but they were fair.
Incredibly caring and thorough professor who provides practically infinite resources and practice problems.

Tifft's classes are largely composed of working together in small groups. This means that you need to do a fair bit of studying outside of the classroom to understand the material as it is never directly taught. Tests have few questions which allows chance to play a large part in grading. Tifft is very available and informative in office hours.
rating_tags: Test heavy--Graded by few things--Accessible outside class

comment: she doesn't teach you everything you need to know for exams, so exams feel like a lot of guesswork. even the practice problems have explanations that could not be extrapolated from the information she gives in lectures. not a good professor.

Tifft is so nice! I took biochemistry online with her and she made it so much more bearable. She simplifies concepts, regularly checks Piazza, and is super helpful in office hours. I will be taking another class with her next semester. I just wish the other biochem profs followed her example because she is truly amazing. Not a hard class either!

comment: The classes are very well structured. I'm just not good at biochemistry...

comment: I had no prior coding experience and did well in the class. She starts from the basics, which makes it easy to understand. There is extra credit offered, which is very helpful. The course is unnecessarily rigid, offering no flexibility and too much work/assignments. Though the computing may be easy for many, not much is offered for those who fall behind. Some assignments felt very harshly scrutinized and many point deductions were made for small errors. I would not take this alongside other time-consuming classes.
Amazing lecturer and great personality. Her class was a joy! Would definitely take again.

Intro to computing is probably one of the easiest classes you will ever take. Prof is really nice, lenient with extra credit and missed assignments etc. I wouldn't take the class if you want to learn in-depth programming stuff though

Two midterms, and lots of homework. Each homework together with code is like 20 pages if all typed. Midterms are time limited and almost no one can finish it. Lecture notes are not organized. Lecture videos and notes are posted.

comment: Telling what he thought were humorous jokes in class. Exams were very hard, lots of homework and difficult. Recommended not to take
Sometimes hard to reach via emails, and class is very disorganized.

Lecture notes are unorganized, very harsh homework grading policy. Exams are difficult. Basically, if his courses are not required for your major then don't take his courses. If you need his courses for graduation, then good luck and try to get as many points from HW as possible. Write your solution very clear and detailed.
He is a boring lecturer.  Wears his shirt unbuttoned nearly halfway down.  Otherwise a reasonable course.

Scolds people who ask "dumb" questions, discouraging to those who don't already know the content.
Great professor.  Extremely helpful. Very hands on. Sincerely interested in students.
Very difficult. Demands things to be done his way. However you will learn how to code.

jerk.  very arrogant and travelled alot.  was very rude to the TA.  Very unclear on expectations and standards

Kessler is one of the best in the history of art department.  He is open to questions; however, he does not provide much clarity on what the exams will cover.  He is one of the fairest professors at JHU!
Nancy is really great teacher. I will appreciate her help forever.
Nancy is a very good teacher. She taught me a lot of useful things and I thank her a lot!
Nancy is the best teacher.She knows the way how to teach and she has a lot of knowledge.
I learn a lot from her about spoken English, even though her class didn't require much effort and there was very few homework. Thanks Nancy!
Best professor of all time. Don't go through Hopkins without taking a class with Glenn.

This guy is an absolute moron! 11 weeks into a WORKSHOP class Ive only been workshopped once! He has never written more than 5 words on my stories, rants the whole class, never lets anyone else speak, &thinks hes always right. If u want ur $'s worth at Hop, never take a class with this moron - I have learned NOTHING except to avoid him at all costs
Really wonderful guy.  He tends to get off track and quote movies a lot, but he is genuinely interested in helping his students succeed in whatever field they want to pursue.
Learned to write by having a wild life, but also happens to be a genius who can quote any great writer of the 20th c off the cuff.  Also - hilarious.  Made my semester!

The Professor is very hard to understand and will constantly make fun of Americans. He also will make you look stupid if you answer a question wrong in his class.
