well, his accent is this weird combination of like french and whatever african language he speaks.. so half of the time, I have no idea what he's trying to say. BUT the class is easy...class is fun..he mostly mentions things you should probably already know though.
he's a nice guy, really interesting lectures.
Don't need to do any of the reading for his classes. He'll just assign random halves of books and never discuss it in class. His essay prompts are also random. TAs grade everything.

Relatively not a lot of reading considering it's a writing class. She gives everybody 98% on their writing assignments so easy grading.  The readings are interesting and she definitely cares about the class but you can't count on it as an accurate representation of the writing sems department at Hopkins.
Her class was easy and she's super helpful.  The readings and papers are interesting and fun to write.

She's great. She's a passionate writer and a wonderful mentor. I recommend Intro to Fiction and Nonfiction to anybody looking to learn to write, or to write "more better." I enjoyed a lot of freedom of expression in her class. Kinda sucks that she makes you buy the relatively expensive textbook that she wrote, but whatever, no prof is perfect.
Not very understanding. Strict, hard grader (harder than should be for night school)
by far the best biology professor at hopkins. don't ever miss his lectures
Very engaging and knowledgeable! Don't be afraid to ask him any questions! He answers them with clarity! He does speak fast so listen to podcasts and memorize notes for an A!

Talks fast, so listen to recoded podcasts and take notes off those in addition to coming to class. Look at old exams that he posts. Very fair exams. Very approachable during office hours, especially if you are prepared with questions
No Comments

The class was lazily thrown together. He is a fair grader, and his lectures aren't terrible, but it feels like he just copied and pasted everything from the assignments to the lectures from somewhere else.

Great class full of interesting topics. No midterm or finals. Mostly based on discussions, quizzes (can be tricky), and written assignments. Additional assignments help with learning PharmGKB database, wearable devices, etc. Final paper on choice of topic at the end, but is mostly based on the weekly written assignments. Would take again.

Dr Chavez is a great professor and explains the material very thoroughly. He definitely expects you to remember your organic synthesis reactions, so have your organic chem book accessible! rating_tags: Get ready to read--Amazing lectures--Tough grader

comment: Dr Chavez delivers the materials comprehensively, and is well-prepared to teach his students. He approaches biochemistry with a background in organics, so it allows you to better understand reaction mechanisms, enzyme kinetics, and biochemical processes. I find the lectures to be lucid, and readily-absorbable.

Workload was reasonable/manageable. Exams are essay question style, group/class discussions, a few assignments, quizzes & a project. Positives: very caring & helpful if you reach out. Negatives: difficult to hear back from her, & no real assignment feedback provided unless you ask. Overall, I would definitely take her for any other class again!
I wish I could take her for more classes!

Dr. Wellman is the best! I learned A LOT from her epigenetics course. I felt challenged but never overwhelmed. Exams are takehome essays and really reinforced the material/were very effective exercises ensuring we remembered everything we learned and could tie it all together independently. She takes pride in teaching and is very skilled at it.

Professor Wellman was by far the best and most caring professor I've had at JHU AAP! She takes the time to record video lectures and reads through all assignments/emails. The midterms are take home and very detailed, helping reinforce the material. She also ties in her research and current events to class topics. Would highly recommend!
rating_tags: Gives good feedback--Participation matters--Clear grading criteria

comment: One of the most time consuming courses I have taken. The majority of the course material such as the discussion posts, project papers, and quiz's were not helpful at all. Lectures failed to explain the material competently. Worse yet, he regularly insulted and belittled students in the required discussion section. JHU should be ashamed to employ such a callous individual.
rating_tags: Tough grader--Lots of homework--So many papers

comment: Hard courses come in two varieties: 1) tough but fair ones where you learn a ton, or 2) artificially difficult due to an incompetent instructor. In intro to machine learning, you will implement machine learning algorithms from scratch, write complex papers, and submit a video for every assignment. Grading requirements are vague. rating_tags: Lots of homework--So many papers--Tough grader

comment: Very funny lectures and cares about students.
Super nice, extremely caring and super accessible and helpful for homework and exams.

Professor Garg is funny and knows how to break the tension during an early lecture. This class had more in-class work than most of my other CS courses, but it helped prepare me for the midterm and final exams.
AMAZING PROF. If you can take Algo w Gagan def do it!! Algo will always be hard but he makes it fun!!
Deplorable human. Done great work I've been told, yet seems determined to scare away the next generation from also contributing.

He's a well respected professor, but he's got a bluntness about him that verges on rudeness sometimes. Extraordinary professor and mentor. If you really want to learn statistics at an advanced level, he's your man.
Best prof at jhu, hands down

Doctor Markovic now works at goucher, but she is geniunely so kind and amazing, I have taken multiple of her classes and all of been very thorough and comprehensive. excellent

Awesome teacher. Despite the vast breadth of the class she does a great job of focusing on the most important things you need to know to succeed in a physics career. Very upbeat, smart and caring professor. Thoroughly enjoyed her class.
Great professor. Clear explanations and interesting material.

I thought I would get away with the formulaic paragraph essay's of high school, but no. She restricts what you can write about, and how you have to write about it.

Classes are extremely dull. In 3 different classes, we spent 30 minutes each going over what we notice from a picture -- "The stars are bright," etc. I loose brain cells every class.

Office hours are helpful. Best way to improve your grade is to spend a lot of time and effort into every writing assignment, even if it's just a rough draft.

comment: She will be there to assist you.
Hard class but was worth it. Learnt a lot, especially how to use models to simplify and solve economic problems.

Very helpful and a great instructor!

I took Shakespeare: Then and Now and thoroughly enjoyed it. I was not previously interested in Shakespeare however the lectures were entertaining and offered a way to actually understand the plays on a more profound level. The reading pace is rigorous (a play a week) but it is very manageable.

Also took Shakespeare: Then and Now... Halpern is thoroughly entertaining in his lectures but the TAs are incompetent and the grading was unfair. For a 100 level class that should be easy, this course--and Halpern-- took themselves a little too seriously.

I took "Shakespeare: Then and Now" with him. Class moves very fast. Great lectures, but TA was bad. HARD TESTS!!! Midterm and final ask you to identify speaker of quotes from a NUMBER of plays. Don't take it. HARD!!!

I took Professor Vidal online class on Generalised Principal Component Analysis and it completely changed my understanding of Machine Learning. I recommend PhD students to follow him and to study his books.
Prof Vidal is so strict and stubborn. Better reconsider it when you have to select his courses

Had him for controls... did a horrible job teaching.  Homework is always over material that he has never taught. Tests are absolutely insane with averages below 30%. It's only because of the TA's that anyone comes out of this class alive.

Great guy who's incredibly intelligent and thoughtful. Class has a lot of material but it's not that difficult. Don't get behind and I repeat, study daily!
Amazing guy. Super nice and more scared of you than you are of him.

Derek is only a postdoc, but he was my favorite professor of my first semester at Hopkins. Unbelievably nice and understanding professor that I've met here. comment: Didn't participate in class. Expected to just read textbook and "get it", lectures were just textbook summaries. HW was 20 Qs, very time consuming and not helpful for deeper understanding. Professor Gonzalez is clearly passionate about teaching -- you can tell from the first lecture on the first day of class. Gonzalez is a VERY smart man. Probably the smartest guy in the humanities department. He loves teaching and can talk a lot. This was Cuba and its Culture since the Revolution. He assigns a LOT of work and expects it to be done. quizzes were 90% of the grade and he gave a quiz every week. This professor is very rubbish. First of all, you can't learn any useful knowledge in her courses. In fact, her grades are very low.

comment: The real issue with with this class was that she didn't proof read her assignments so there were material typos and ambiguities on every assignment that would effect the outcome of a regression. Dr. Rubey is a great professor! The class itself can be a bummer, but he really tries to make it as manageable as possible. Don't pay $5000 for this horrifically taught class, it's a shame this school only cares about $$$.

Extremely condescending and arrogant. Doesn't take the time to think about your question before dismissing it. Only capable of explaining things in one manner, then keeps repeating that explanation - gets frustrated when you don't understand. Fixed mindset.

Really love professor Rubin. He is knowledgeable and kind.

Professor Celenza genuinely cares about all of his students. I've learned a lot about the history of philosophy from him and he makes it all feel engaging. a first rate indoctrinator

He does a pretty good job of explaining the material. Some of his lectures are a bit boring. His tests are pretty fair.

Matt teaches fire hose-style (a lot of information given in a short amount of time). Matt teaches firehose-style (a lot of information given in a short amount of time). Tough material and just a tough class in general.
Taught a complex subject in a very straightforward manner. Exams were easy as long as you understood the material.
The lectures often became overly technical and repetitive. Lacked passion for material/teaching.

One of the nicest/most understanding professors I've ever had. He is so patient and calm with students, even if they ask the same question 50 times (no joke, there was one student who did this). He is extremely straightforward with what students need to know for homework/quizzes/exams, and does whatever it takes for students to understand material.
He is a very straightforward professor who teaches exactly what you need to know for the exam. Make sure you do the reading and work hard on the homework assignments.

I had her for Intro to Archaeology.  I never really knew what to make of her personality, some days she seemed cold and intolerant, and others she was very nice.  The class assignments were generally graded pretty easy, but I had trouble with her midterm.  The final wasn't too bad.  Never really did the textbook, wasn't a problem for me.

I had her for Neanderthals to the Neolithic (130.102). She misplaces things, so make sure you email her too if you give her a hard copy of something. On midterms and finals, write your essays with the information she says in class. I found the textbooks unnecessary, but I was well-versed in the material before I entered the class.

Very interested in topic.  Multiple required books included one she wrote.  No class notes just stands and lectures so bring a laptop and get any days you missed from someone else.  If you do the work you will get a good grade.  Is very nice and will answer any questions you have.

He is not good at teaching his material. He ALWAYS referred us to his TA... Why doesn't his TA just teach the class. He made the exams really hard and was not very helpful even going to office hours. Your better off not attending class and reading the book and getting to know the TA.

Bad lecturer. Didn't actually learn the material. Basically relied on the TA the whole time, except that meant that I didn't learn much. Had no idea what was going on 95% of the time. Class is a bore.

Computation and Math Modeling was the most boring class I've ever taken. I fell asleep pretty often. The tests were okay and GIS was kind of cool, but the homeworks kind of sucked. Everyone just asked the VBA guy in our class what to put. The TA was pretty awesome...He should teach the class. I don't know how he is for FM yet though.

The class is really long since it's only once a week so the interesting lectures kind of drone on but the professor cares so much about all of his students doing well and learning. Dedicated Professor. Had what I want in a professor: care, about subject matter and students.  Nice guy, good teacher.
Great teacher. Keeps the material interesting. Always available to help. Overall, just a great guy!

It was a hard class but he was a great teacher. Tough grader but if you put the work into your answers he was fair. His lectures were fun and he loved to slip science fiction references into lectures and tests. Don't take his classes if you are looking for an easy A. I personally loved the class.

comment: Lectures are very general; will not tell you what to focus on. He admits to being ambiguous in lecture but expect you to know everything. He emails back quickly.  DO NOT take him if you are pre-med.  Save your GPA.

HARD and TRICKY tests: he uses a "storyline" style of testing where you apply principles to problem solving - his quirkiness that he adds to the questions can be distracting. Dr. Holland has a lot to say, but rightfully so. He's very knowledgeable!

I found the course not difficult and Cervone very affable. She even moved a paper deadline back a week when we asked her and she allowed people to retake parts the exam they missed. The lectures can get boring or repetitive but overall nice professor nice class.

This class was the worst experience. Everyone around me would agree. People are doodling in their notebooks because her lectures end up no where. comment: This class was ridiculous. She would go on and on, it's mind numbing. Unless you wanna feel every single minute of her 1.15 hour class, don't take it. Discussion mandatory.

Great teacher, lets you do a lot.  Knows his patients and expects  you to learn them quickly.  Does inpatient and outpatient and always has after hours events (health fairs, working sporting events) or patients.  Day is never over, but you hardly notice the time.

If you want to practice medicine outside of Hopkins this is the guy to show you how.  Has office and hospital patients, doesn't overwork you, but expects you to take EVERY pt seriously-sick or not.

John is a great instructor. Everything you need to know are in his lectures and reading assignments. He responds promptly to questions and gives little hints when you need it. Don't expect an easy A. Everything must be earned. Bad students get bad grades.

Prepare to spend 25+ hours/week on homework. 30 towards end. Assignment due every six days, plus three labor-heavy projects. comment: Prof. Katz is the perfect combination of extremely knowledgeable and relaxed in his teaching style. comment: Brilliant.  His lectures are well presented, engaging and sometimes provocative.  Not always the best at answering questions, and can be hard to get in touch with.  Most students get As.

comment: Don't teach much but grade hard.

comment: This is a highly technical course, so be prepared for a lot of intense statistical inference work (the workload is rather heavy). comment:

His classtime is either him walking through simple examples or just nonsensical mumbling and then his assignments/exams is insane.

AVOID!!!!!!!!!!
rating_tags: Get ready to read--Lots of homework--Test heavy

comment: Paul Weinstein is a great instructor. Make sure to prepare for assignment projects. He will grade fair, but tough. Make sure you know your content before tackling an assignment. I would take his course again without hesitation.

Lectures usually get the job done but he's rude and dry. You can rarely get a hold of him and when you do, most likely, he'll only answer one part of your email and just pretend you didn't ask him anything else. I wish Hopkins gave you other choices for advisors instead of giving everyone to him. He's too busy to actually connect and be helpful.
rating_tags: Skip class? You won't pass.--Clear grading criteria--Tough grader

comment: Great background in both academia and in government.  Head of program, sometimes hard to get but pretty reasonable.  Lectures are very interesting and entertaining.
The class was bad. The literature did not help at all, and neither did the professor. He didn't offer help when students encountered the problems.

This class was... odd. I had no R background before this class so spent most of my time figuring out how to work in R. Once you get through that, and his odd scheduling/rules for turning assignments in, its not bad. You have a lot of flexibility in how you answer your questions. Lectures aren't super helpful, but the code in his slides is.

Lectures are all theory, no application Be prepared to learn all on your own No clear grading criteria Uses old code and does not update unless enough students complain about it not working Very short turn around from lab assignments to due dates Records all lectures and makes available for re-viewing
rating_tags: Lots of homework--Get ready to read

comment: Grading criteria is simple and he replies to emails quickly, but the class was lazily prepared. Each quiz and test is riddled with sp/other errors that cause significant confusion. No outline is provided so you better hope you are remembering the important parts of the textbook for the test because the questions are specific and from 2 or 3 pages.
rating_tags: Get ready to read--Graded by few things--Test heavy

comment: Dr. Goralski is a good professor. In the class there are not any lectures and you have to read the textbook... so its a self taught class if you will. He does respond fast to emails and answers questions quickly though so thats a pro. The assignments of the class are fairly easy as well. Overall, his class is easy as long as you read the text.

If you already have a strong command of mol bio, this is the professor to take. This class won't make you waste time if you've already taken plenty of mol bio and don't need to be taught it again. Exam questions were challenging but fair. No lectures, so you can skim readings and see if you need to refresh any concepts in more detail.

I took 2 courses with MC. Her lectures were so engaging. MC will get you excited about leadership, and it's clear that she cares about her students. I've raved about MC to probably all my Hopkins friends by now, because if you haven't taken one of MC's classes, you're missing out big time. Why're you waiting? Hurry up and enroll in MC's classes!

Excellent excellent professor, would take her class and any others she teaches. Her class was always extremely engaging and she gives great feedback on all assignments. It is a decent amount of work, but the rewards you get are worth it.

MC is a legend! She is an incredible educator who teaches leadership extremely well, and she's caring, hilarious and inspirational. She deeply cares about each of her students and their success and growth. Every class is highly engaging and I learned so much while having her as a professor. 11/10 recommend!
Dr. Divito really did help me with this class and was very easy to talk to. She wanted you to understand the material and got me through it. I highly recommend her.

Lazy professor, doesnt create lectures just posts very sparce notes with little value. Takes over a month to grade exams, unresponsive to emails. 3 exams that are basically open book projects, a few quizzes (open book), weekly discussions, and 1 project. Not hard to get an A, but dont expect to actually get anything of value out of this class.

This professor is such a slow grader. I completed one exam and I am in the midst of taking my second one and she has yet to grade the first one. Very discussion heavy and for little value She is a slow email responder based on if she wants to answer. lecture notes heavy but no real correlation to the actual test. Teach yourself how to read research
rating_tags: Participation matters--Graded by few things--Lecture heavy

comment: Prof has difficulty understanding course scope and devising relevant course content. Plethora of research projects, final project is a proposal, redundant interim report, & final paper ranging from 20-25 pages in which we propose a new system design for a very specific system- irrelevant to chief cybersecurity needs for an organization. Impractical
rating_tags: Get ready to read--So many papers--Tough grader

comment: His lectures are cluttered and disorganized. His rubrics are the same, with the addition of being unclear and haphazardly thrown together. I get the impression very little effort was put into the creation of course materials. His lecture recordings consist mainly of rambling and plodding along through the slides. Arbitrary and difficult grader.

- Assignment rubrics are unclear and poorly written. - Exams are unreasonably long (7+ pages written single spaced in Word in 2.5 hours) - Has you write research papers on PhD level cybersecurity topics despite the class being an introductory course. - Will take off points for undocumented, qualitative reasons. - Test grading contradicts textbook.
rating_tags: So many papers--Tough grader--Lots of homework

comment: Kind and understanding. Lectures are entertaining, just remember general ideas from philosophers. Grading criteria for writing assignments usually unclear but professor is open to helping when needed. Grade for weekly reflections is very dependent on TA so learn how they grade. Very interesting class where you will learn to think in a nonstem way.

Karen is one of the best professors I have ever had! Although the class was evaluated with only 2 translation tests (25% for each), a critical analysis paper (30%), and 20% of participation, she is willing to offer help so students can make the most out of the class. A lot of translation (10-15hr/wk) is required for this class but I bet it is fun.
rating_tags: Gives good feedback--Lots of homework--Graded by few things

comment: Karen was super enthusiastic about our topic, and she always gave great feedback. I'd highly suggest visiting her office hours.
rating_tags: Gives good feedback--Participation matters--So many papers

comment: Tanksley is amazing not only as a professor but as a mentor and someone who truly cares about her students. She's intelligent and good looking as well. ;)
Sarah Tanksley is an incredibly knowledgeable professor. Her exams will challenge you but you will leave the class knowing you've definitely learned some new, interesting, and useful knowledge.

Prof Tanksley is wonderful! She runs her own GMP consulting firm and is clearly very knowledgeable. She held live lectures weekly, where she would explain all key concepts. No non-value-added assignments or discussions were required. There were two assigned books to read throughout the semester, and both were fascinating! Highly recommend!
rating_tags: Get ready to read--Clear grading criteria--Amazing lectures

comment: I took the section of Leadership & Org. Behavior with a mandatory 2-day in-person residency in Baltimore. It was great! Fun activities that relate to the course content and a good networking opportunity. Barton's grading is a little subjective so use lots of direct quotes. If you can write well and really know the content, you'll get a good grade.

A lot of reading assignments for this course, graded by only quizzes, individual assignments, and final exam. The assignment grading criteria is subjective and not clear at all. I would get comment saying "Good Job!" but get a 9/10 on a short reflection essay. The quizzes are not well written, with frequent typos.
rating_tags: Tough grader--So many papers--Graded by few things

comment: Michelle Barton grades very subjectively. I got all 100 in my quizes. She graded other my assignments with much lower grades to drag the total grades down. Her comments are vague and lacks solid standings. She does not have any skills. Those who can bs a lot can get much better grades.

Absolutely the worst teacher I have ever had... He downloads a set of slides and gets stuck on the first 5 slides all lecture. He doesn't even follow them. He is an unfair grader. He picks on his students. Quizes and papers have nothing to do with the lectures or textbooks. Lectures are unbearable. I wish I asked for a refund. DO NOT TAKE HIM!!!!!!

If you have an option, don't take any class with him. Literally 50-100 slides but will skip most of them. He does not take any critique even though he acts "nice". He refuses to elaborate on any rubric when you ask then will slam into you when you don't follow what he never clarifies. If something is wrong, he isn't helpful. Says to check again.
rating_tags: Group projects--Lots of homework--So many papers

comment: Professor doesn't teach at all. The course is full of errors and spelling mistakes. The material in quizzes is from different textbooks than what is thought. Research assignments are graded on how he feels about your group rather than on the rubric (which is missing). He is always late with grading, so you don't know how you are doing overall.
rating_tags: Lots of homework--Test heavy--Graded by few things

comment: Very inconsistent does not show up to class and will not notify students. Is most of the time late. Gives instructions then reprimands you for following them on her assignments. Is unprofessional and always disorganized. Re-teaches topics already taught. Does not communicate well with students and fails to notify when certain assignments are due.

She is a lovely person and the readings chosen were strong.  The material covered was important.  However, it was very difficult to determine what she was looking for, even when asking specific questions.  She seemed disorganized as a professor.  On another note, she is a great person to just chat with.

This was a required course in the online Ed.D. program at Johns Hopkins. This professor was completely disorganized, was rarely coherent, and for an online course, was virtually absent from all the discussions. Avoid at all costs!

I had him for AS.470.688 (81)	Political Institutions and the Policy Process

This professor was thorough, helpful, knowledgeable, and reasonable.

He helped me tremendously and the quality of the class was great interesting and succinct. Glad to have learned from his expertise.

I LOVED this class. I was pretty nervous taking it because it was required but this professor made it so fluid and easy to understand. The grading criteria was VERY clear and his feedback is crazy spot on. I had a loved one pass away mid-semester. Harris was INCREDIBLY kind and understanding. He's got a great sense of humor which really helps too.
Excellent professor, extremely knowledgable. Learned very much in his class and assignments were great to apply what I had learned. Readings were also very relevant.

I took History of Occidental Civilization: Europe and the Wider World with Marshall. He's an AMAZING lecturer! He has excellent flow.  He is a seasoned professor and does an excellent job linking between events of a period to give you a feel for what was going on at the time. I highly recommend him!
Interesting class, not bad.  Sometimes lectures can be dry.  He just lectures.  TA sessions can be annoying.
Easy to follow by putting his notes up on the board, though paper topics tended to be hard.

I took Freshman Seminar on Race and Education, really recommend it - amazing and interesting class and she was great. Graded papers sort of hard but if you participate in class and actually try your fine

She graded papers hard, but since the class was a seminar, participation was weighted heavily. Lectures were very informative but dry at times. She is very helpful and responsive via email and office hours.
No Comments
Word of advice: talk to her and not the TAs. She's incredibly generous and willing to sit down with you and go over your outline/paper. Best prof at Hopkins!

Melanie Shell-Weiss is the best professor at Johns Hopkins!!!!! She is really invested in her sudents. Knowledgable, caring... I have taken a lot of history classes, but she is really amazing. Every professor should be like her.
Very knowledgeable, extremely effective teaching, and always there for assistance.

A well-respected and mother-like figure in the Hopkins Materials Science Department! Although her lab class can sometimes be frustrating (due to lots of old instruments), her door is always open and help is always available. She is one of the few professors at Hopkins who genuinely cares about the well-being and futures of her students.

Professor Wilson makes a genuine effort to know her students, and helps whenever a student asks for assistance. Her laissez faire style is frustrating for many students, but most wouldn't learn how to think about an experiment if she hand fed them the answers. While her lecture classes are easy, MatSci lab can be overwhelming if you procrastinate.

A very nice lady who is genuinely interested in science. She is always open to questions and concerns. Unfortunately, the equipment used in her lab class is outdated and rarely produces results that are consistent with theories. Lectures can be fun but usually disorganized. What is expected of students is also sometimes unclear.
This professor is awesome! You will definitely get out of this class what you put in. Professor Madsen is hilarious and helpful. Career class was always fun.
My favorite teacher in the counseling department so far.  Very energetic, helpful, approachable.  He has a great sense of humor and makes class fun, and you also learn a lot.  Highly recommended.

Amazing teacher..really helpful couse for anyone who ever wants to get a job anywhere...really helpful..funny...hard grader but very fair tells you what he expects..an added plus if u take his class he will offer you his counseling services once you complete his course....such a benifit he is great at what he does!!!!!!!!!!!!!!
Reviews material from the previous lecture thoroughly during each lecture and is approachable. Genuinely cares about students.
rating_tags: Skip class? You won't pass.--Clear grading criteria--Caring

comment: Prashant is a brilliant lecturer, had him for 550.211, he speaks very clearly and genuinely cares about his students.

Pretty bad professor overall. Doesn't respond to emails, office hours almost useless and has a god-complex while teaching. Take LADE with another professor if you can (he also teaches prob stats for bio and for engineers).

Very knowledgeable of the subject matter and willing to engage in intelligent discussion of economics applied to real world scenarios. Must actively pay attention and participate in class to reap the full benefits - if you weren't expecting this, why are you in school. Not paying attention will cost you on exams.
arguably one of the worst teachers I've had; an opinion shared by almost everyone in my class.
You want to attend all classes and take notes, some exams questions are not in slides/book and review class assignments especially for first exam...
She's adorable. Gotta love the white Hanes v-necks!
what a cutie!
From now on, there will be a tragic strain to my writing that I'll always owe to Ms. Gumport. I'll never forget this class.
She's hot!! Smiles all the time, is lots of fun and always helpful!
Julie is perfect!
French is awesome with Julie. She really makes it fun, and truly cares about your progress.
MY senior year, I am taking one of the best classes I could have ever taken. The class is extremely interesting. He cares a lot about students, and is very knowledgeable. Everyone likes the class.

Best professor I've had at Hopkins so far. Very engaging and funny when talking, and he is the most passionate person I've ever met, even if his passion is geared towards Ancient Assyria. Very very highly recommend taking any of his classes!

This professor is amazing. His lectures are extremely engaging. I was not interested in this topic at all before enrolling in his class, and now I'm totally passionate about it. He's really genuinely funny and enjoyable to listen to. One of the best profs at Hopkins! Highly recommended.
Has no interest in his class or lecturing whatsoever.  Leaves learning up to the student and the book.  Make use of TA's, very nice and helpful, but don't speak clear english too well.
Take the introductory course for 1 free credit.
Good course, good professor, nothing really specific - only took the introductory course.

He was a wonderful teacher, probably my favorite professor I had as an undergrad. The class was a review on single var calc, but he turned it into a wonderful introduction to pure math. We wrote proofs and demonstrated them. He's insanely funny and weird in the best way. Every class was a joy! He always made sure that you understood the material.
Made class interesting and exciting although made many small mistakes that had to be corrected when writing on the board that was occasionally confusing.  We had a class fish Sfin though!
Outstanding Professor. Brilliant but accessible. Super hipster.

I love her. PEBL has been such an amazing and valuable experience and I strongly recommend it to freshmen, although it does take some time to finish all the work. Dr. Fitch is the best prof I've ever had at Hopkins, very caring and passionate and she has been so helpful both in and out of class. She cares about her class and her students a lot!

My absolute favorite professor at Hopkins, hands down. She cares about her students and wants to see them succeed. Class is relatively simple and does require a time commit. I learned so much and my friends agree that PEBL was the most beneficial lab at Hopkins. Would take another class with her in a heart beat! I miss her!
She's an amazing person, my goodness. Loved her clear teaching style and compassion

Prof. Sogge is definitely a first-rate expert in Analysis and PDE, as well as a considerate teacher who gives me the fullest freedom to self-study and explore my interested topics. His lecture is very clear, and he introduces some further topics which turn out to be very helpful in research. Also, he is very patient and respectful in & after class.

He is a kind guy who is very intelligent and approachable outside of class, but Sogge is a mediocre lecturer at best. He is subpar at explaining things and the handwriting on his slides is awful. Grading is fair, but if you don't have a calc background you might struggle. If you have taken AP/IB calc you should do well if you do HW consistently.

He's a great guy, not the best lecturer. Tests are very difficult; 2 midterms and the final make up the vast majority of your grade. Practice problems beyond just homework is essential for success. Final was very difficult, usual concepts but makes you apply them in ways not specifically covered in the course.
Kind but not the best teacher

Dr. Spall is one of the most strict professor from AMS department, but, you will learn a lot from his class. He put lots of time prepare his class, lecture notes, and literatures. You will struggle in his class, overwhelmed with homeworks and quizz and exams, but you will learn a ton after the class.

Clearly knows his subject material. Grading can be a little tough (he tends to be nitpicky about careful writing and notation). Exams are generally fair but somewhat time-consuming, so need to work efficiently or risk not finishing. Hard grader who doesn't tend to give much partial credit.
rating_tags: Tough Grader--Respected--Skip class? You won't pass.

comment: Professor Spall was one of the best professors I had at Hopkins. However, his courses are very tough. Do not expect any of his courses to be walk in the park. In fact, expect them to be far more difficult than the average course. That being said, his courses are very rewarding. I wish I had taken every one of his courses while at Hopkins.
Mike really knows his subject matter and is always able to find real world examples to bring home the point.  A student really needs to care to get the most from his classes

Kubik is not helpful and tells student to see the bb to explain answers.  Very tricky test and his teaching style is boring and way over most students heads.  If you want to understand your subject and pass, do not take his class.  I personally do not think he is in this field because he is passionate about teaching.  Do not take his class.

Very unfair style of grading! Gives points to questions that majority of the class got wrong. Does not award additional points to student who got it right in the first place. The grading method can be used for evaluating, not grading student. Very boring style of teaching. His tests are very tricky as he likes to test on the foot notes of the text

Professor Connolly gives great lectures and led discussions well with insightful questions in seminars. He is very knowledgeable in his field and weaves together a wide range of materials in a logical and thoughtful way. He is a tough grader on papers but gives good feedback that helps you with the next one.
rating_tags: Get ready to read--Participation matters--Amazing lectures

comment: Incredible lectures, if you can take any classes with this professor TAKE THEM!!!
Grades more harshly than usual. Interesting material that covers breadth well and examines macro-scale topics well but struggles to confer knowledge of minutiae.

He overcomplicates everything. Going to lecture actually confused me more than just skipping lecture, looking at the homework, and teaching myself. Test questions were different in style to those in the book and the professor never really worked out the problems in class, just theory, which fed into the overcomplication.

Savitt is the worst teacher I've ever had. Class is theory based (aren't we trying to learn math?), homework is unrelated to lectures, and test questions barely have to do with either. If you took AP Calc in high school you should be fine (may even want to skip lecture so you don't have to listen to his annoyingness) but otherwise you're screwed.
He's pretty okay.
for senior lab/design, she makes you work hard and think through the problems. she's very knowledgeable, but overall a tough grader.

Very monotonous voice, and not engaging at all, but she makes sure that she covers everything that there is to know. If you pay attention (which is very hard to do) and follow everything then its very useful, but reading the textbook for 15 min. can be just as effective. Problems in the textbook are good practice for exams.

540.202- I had her for Intro to Chemical and Biological Process Analysis. She has a french accent and does not speak loudly enough, but was thorough in class if you could understand her, didnt like the textbook much, but the class was easy enough if you keep up with the work.
The best Professor in ME. Quite a nice person
Awful at communicating goals to students; highly unrealistic belief in what she has communicated to us.

Is genuinely interested in becoming a good teacher but is woefully not cut out for the job.  Has absolutely no sense of what students need to learn, how to prepare a lecture, how to get students to come to class, and what types of assignments are useful.
He sucks
hard to follow.
Geat professor. Clear, office hours are good.

I took two classes with Falk at Michigan. He's a great guy.  He really goes out of his way to engage students in creative ways. You can expect homework sets will be tough, but if you go to office hours he'll walk you through anything you're stuck on. He will probably assign a bunch of MATLAB simulations, and maybe a class multimedia project.

I took two classes with Falk at Michigan. He's a great guy.  He really goes out of his way to engage students in creative ways. You can expect homework sets will be tough, but if you go to office hours he'll walk you through anything you're stuck on. He will probably assign a bunch of MATLAB simulations, and maybe a class multimedia project.
not too clear about what he is looking for in an essay. talks a lot and doesnt let students participate as much, then gives poor participation grades for it
He goes off on a lot of funny tangents, but he really gets into detail. He's a funny, extremely nice guy who really cares about students and that they are learning.
He starts talking about random things lol. He goes over everything so well that there is no way you could forget something or fail an exam/essay!

Dr. Cunningham's lectures are engaging and understandable. However, the homework is ridiculously hard and ambiguous. His tests are in a similar fashion, unfortunately. The questions are ambiguous, but the expected answers are so specific it's difficult to fathom how we are expected to reach the exact same conclusion. His office hours are unhelpful.
Dr. C was amazing.  I didn't expect to like Genetics, but he made it all totally relevant and interesting too.  By far one of best professors I've ever had.

Very inspiring lecturer and also very approachable. Has a British-like accent (!) Makes genetics interesting by presenting material to make students think. Exams tests your ability to comprehend, not memorize, so could be hard.

Not as interactive with the students as other online professors and she does rely heavily on self teaching and students answering each others questions. She assigns more work than average and is slow with grading but she is an easy grader and is very sweet if you do ever have to talk to her. Wouldn't say shes the best but definitely not the worst
rating_tags: Get ready to read--Participation matters--GROUP PROJECTS

comment: Online class was fine.
rating_tags: Gives good feedback--Get ready to read

comment: All her materials are exact copy of the main professor's class.  If you take it online, I do not recommend it - they both do not use audio lecture.  She provides discussion questions, research papers, quizzes for you to learn the material on your own and from other students.  Instead of lecture about material, she provides HOW-TO-STUDY TIPS HAHAHA

I don't recommend, he likes to create confusion by putting trick questions or giving an ambiguous explanation. He thinks he is helping but is making u confused. He is not easily approachable,emails back after 2 days. Has no interest if you learn or you struggle. This is not how you teach or develop interest in a student

What a great course. Probably the best biology course I've taken in my life. Dr. Lochamy teaches you HOW to think, not just WHAT to think. Any professor can point to a text and repeat the quotes, but it's rare to find someone who teaches you how to think as a biologist. He will make you work for it, but it's worth it for the learning experience.

Dropped in 3rd week to make room for harder course. Jonathan is personable and knowledgeable on the subject. Started a week early and asked students to do 2 weeks in one, led to confusing organization. Materials are good for learning subject. Quizzes are full of gotchas not answered by materials. Won't admit fault when questions are ambiguous.

She was honestly a really great professor. Attendance is mandatory and she is very helpful when it comes to camera use and editing techniques. Her tutorials are very easy to understand and the format of the class is very easy in the sense that if you show up, participate, and do your best, you will do well.
rating_tags: Gives good feedback--Skip class? You won't pass.--Clear grading criteria

comment: Really makes you focus on composition, subject matter, perspective, and intention. I would highly recomend taking any of her classes.
Phyllis is awesome.  She's always willing to offer good advice, and she really helps you progress.  Take her photo classes if you can get in--they're competitive, and with good reason.

She was very kind & understanding. Gave out extensions, due dates were more of a suggestion, not penalized if late. But course was disorganized. Didn't respond quickly to emails (5 days avg). Often opened course content several days late. Grading & instructions unclear. Easy readings, discussion, & assignments tho.
really cares, tests straightforward, concept based teaching  Biotechnology masters
rating_tags: Gives good feedback--ACCESSIBLE OUTSIDE CLASS--LECTURE HEAVY

comment: Real and engaging. Good prof all around. Clear and concise powerpoints. Focus on the main points, do a little preparation in advance for discussion purposes,  and you'll be fine -- you might even enjoy yourself. A very good course  and a very nice person too.
excellent professor
Best
meh
Too Much Useless theorical materials. Too much Math prove in the HW.

As a theoretical introductory course, it provides students with perfect start point, especially for those who wanna do research in robotics. In detail, every concept such as Lie Group and PoE formulations are delivered clearly. Final project has bonus credit for extra work so that students can give full play to toy robotic arm application.

The class is posed as an introductory course in robotics, but he frames it like a highly advanced theoretical linear algebra class. Of course the topics are relevant to robotics, but are not useful tools unless your research is in deep learning. Homework is too hard and confusing, and it takes too long. TA's barely help, and his examples are poor.
rating_tags: Tough grader--Get ready to read--Lecture heavy

comment: I'm here to say... Do not take Professor Sazama's class. She'll essentially dock you every point she can just to remind you that you’re still a student, not a professional. Reach out for feedback, she'll generically reply that you have a lot to learn but she wishes you the best of luck.
rating_tags: Tough grader--Get ready to read--Lots of homework

comment: Condescending to adult learners, demonstrated significant technical challenges with online course platform causing students to access exams and modules late, slow to respond / provided insufficient responses to student emails, and focused more on arbitrary formatting details on essays than demonstration of correct physiology concepts.
Grading criteria not clear, technical difficulties with course and did not respond in timely manner. Arrogant in responses.
Smith is not a good speaker, sorry to say. Lectures are impossible to follow, and the subject material is extremely tedious and uninteresting. Definitely a class to avoid if there ever was one.
She posts notes from her lectures that have all the info you need to study for exams. The discussion sessions aren't very helpful.

Dr. Smith is a nice person, but her lectures are very frustrating to try to follow. The material isn't that hard, but half the difficulty of the class has come from the sheer work of deciphering the convoluted, redundant recorded lectures. Discussion sections are very, very superficial, but the exams require much more knowledge. Avoid this class.
rating_tags: Graded by few things--Test heavy--EXTRA CREDIT

comment: Very unusual and interesting class setup. Tests are mc questions submitted by students, worth 75% of your grade. I did about 10% below the average on the first one easily got an A b/c of extra credit and second exam was easy and didn't even have to take the final. Funny and interesting man too, had fun and learned some cool things.

Towards the end it got better. His beginning exam policy where students submitted questions with the top 5 most difficult questions submitted by students earning extra credit led to a lot of unnecessarily hard questions being asked. Towards the end however his exams became a lot more fair as he allowed a cheat sheet. His extra credit is generous.

Dylan Selterman made this class so easy. For exams, he lets you have a cheat sheet, two-sided. He lets students write the exam questions so they're usually pretty simple and straightforward. He gives us several opportunities for extra credit, like literally making psychology memes. And in general, his classes were always enjoyable and engaging.
He's bad at explaining concepts, and that's not great for a class as complicated as biochemistry. He'll also interrupt students trying to answer questions with rude comments.

FYI--lecturing at 10000 mph and then calling the class idiots when over half get the clicker questions wrong without actually explaining the reasoning behind the answer isn't teaching. Unfortunately the best professor in biochem, since the others are even more atrocious, if one can even imagine a more arrogant and incompetent professor.
rating_tags: TEST HEAVY--GRADED BY FEW THINGS--LECTURE HEAVY

comment: Crystal clear.  And he had a very fun demonstration in class.  Really enjoyed his lectures.  But its biochemistry nonetheless....

Unclear, teaches directly from notes, and therefore is unable to answer questions clearly or accurately. Somewhat inapproachable. If you actually care to learn the material, Mr. Oxtoby, Gillis and Campion is your best bet (the text book authors).

Ridiculous. One of the worst professors I've ever had. Doesn't explain things clearly at all, and gets material/equations wrong half the time. Is not at all open to questions, and is very rude toward students. Easy, but learned nothing.
I am so confused and lost I don't know where to begin.
Having this class at 9 AM was a mistake; I could never keep my eyes open. The material was difficult and the TA didn't help at all.

she cares about her subject and teaches it well. also, when help is needed shell give it if you go to office hours. she expects everyone to read the text & take as much joy in the subject as her. if you dont  you can get by just doing papers & reading on the assigned topics. if you really want to learn the material she gives you the means to do it

Blah! somehow able to render very interesting material bland. also, has a tendency for making class very awkward by just standing there staring or calling ot a student for some random, harmless behavior like getting up to go to the bathroom.
She can be tough grader but it's worth it. Learning Spanish is tough.

Loreto is HILARIOUS. She's so warm and friendly and makes class enjoyable. That being said, she conducts class 100% in Spanish and speaks 1000/mph so be prepared for that! She also calls on you at random but as long as you do the homework for every class it's not a big deal at all. She really cares and wants her students to improve thei
Worst ever!
Elaborated examples to teach the students. One of the best classes I have taken at Johns Hopkins

Great professor, very clear with great stories to drive home the points. Hard to get good grades on his papers, as he is particular, but if you put in the effort you will do fine. Class based around the students and learning (i.e. limited notes and lecturing).

Eric Rice is a great professor. He is incredibly friendly and approachable and uses a lifetime of true stories to liven up the subject of business communications. Be warned, though, that he has incredibly high expectations in regards to the caliber of papers he expects from his students.
This man is a genius, best brain surgeon to ever live. Should've been our president, but HUD will do.
Okay teacher but I LOVE neurology
No Comments

I had the pleasure of taking Ed Scheinerman's first online class, and he was such a good professor that I'm rating him before getting my final grade. He is flexible, available, and very understanding. If you are struggling, with your schedule or the content, don't hesitate to email him. He is honestly one of the best professors I have had.
He's cool and very nice!
No Comments
He's nice, his lectures might not be the most interesting but he's willing to help students who don't understand. Uses the textbook a lot, and is very friendly to all the students.
GREAT!

Average of A-, very nice professor who won't penalize you for being smart enough to take a difficult class. Read lecture notes before class; homework takes a while, but really teaches you the material. tests are easier than hw. lecture goes well with text.

Just your average college course, nothing special. Homework and test questions were straight from the book. Read the book and you'll be fine. The course didn't really inspired students to be creative with the material and provided no opportunity for students to apply some of the statistical tools they learned in a meaningful way.
rating_tags: Get ready to read--Clear grading criteria

comment: If you like nitpicking, she's the one.

This course was no joke to say the least. Math involved was sometimes very challenging. Prof. Briand was always there and readily available to help. She posted replies to discussion boards same day, and always responded to emails within hours! She was always ready to help, and always understanding. Really glad I took this class with her!

She's trying to put in so much in a single course with little guidance, and she has her own standards but won't let you know cause otherwise you'd figure out the right answers before submitting your assignments. It's ridiculous.

Policy Analysis is a core course required for the MPP program, however it doesn't do justice to the degree. You don't learn anything new in this class- no tools, no models, no evaluation techniques, nothing at all. The only thing you learn is to write a memo. And you work towards writing a paper that the prof published under her name.

She teaches a course titled "Policy Analysis in the Real World" this could be further from the truth.  The policy issues are primarily outdated and irrelevant. She falsely advertises an "open door" policy, and her grading system is inconsistent. She is too focused on her own research to care about student advancement. Oh, and she has favorites.
Transformational professor. I 100% recommend to take.

Such an amazing, caring professor. Extremely accessible outside of class and gives clear, helpful feedback on essays before they're submitted. Readings are not long and are interesting. Participation in discussion matters! Takes a while to grade papers but is not harsh on grading. Easy to get an A if you revise with him and talk out your thoughts.

Professor Wexler was one of my favorite teachers that I have had at Hopkins. He's brings really engaging reading material to the class and his class focuses a lot on participation in discussions. He's always available to review papers and provides really good feedback on the writing. I would 100% recommend you take his reintro to writing class!

This is the worst Professor I have ever had and it was particularly frustrating given that the class was online. She usually took 5-7 days to respond to an email and her responses rarely answered the question I had asked, were short, and just generally unhelpful. I had to take this course as part of my program but highly recommend avoiding.

Her online lectures are a total joke, and the chosen textbook "Intro to Econometrics" is barely understandable and a total snooze (even though I generally enjoy statistics). She does not grasp the concept of explaining things to students who might be unfamiliar with a new concept. I was forced to take this course (and a followup Quant Methods).

Worst class I've ever taken at JHU. Does not answer questions, refuses to help, rude, actively discourages discussions on the discussion board, very scripted and narrow minded. If you can avoid this prof, do so at all costs.
His lecture does not follow the text. He assigns too much homework. Exams are not similar to his practice exam. There's probably a better professor to take. No curve either according to him.

The Professor's lectures are helpful for the homework problems. There are quite a lot of lectures, but it's manageable. The quizzes are pretty straightforward. The homework had some challenging problems, but you can ask for help, and he, or one of his assistants, will guide you. The midterm and final are not easy, but study and it will be fine
rating_tags: Lots of homework--Accessible outside class--Lecture heavy

comment: Dr. Specter was great and very accessible, I'm a math major in the department and he has been one of my favorite profs to work with. rating_tags: Accessible outside class--Skip class? You won't pass.--Hilarious

comment: Very clear, very concise. Very kind and supportive. I am honestly extremely shocked by these other reviews have no idea where they are coming from.

Have to give her a low score bc she bailed from the class w/o updates. Put us 2 wks behind in work, had to get a sub prof. The sub B Kondo redesigned the entire course bc the syllabus made no sense. The redesigned class was fun tho: easy readings, short discussions, 1 big ppt project. Just wish we learned more abt the marketing & develpt of meds.

Not my favorite professor. She's difficult to reach, not prompt with replies, and sloppily put this course together. Easy A, but don't expect to take much away from this class if you aren't seeking the answers yourself. I learned a lot because I read the textbook, but she doesn't teach anything and I read more than I needed.
Never responds to email or submits grades.

I greatly enjoyed Professor Gruber's Calculus ll class. His passion for math and for his students truly shines as he is always willing to answer questions and discuss ways to improve your grade. Portfolios for this class can be tough but clear grading guidelines are laid out.

Dr. Gruber is good at teaching basic calculus concepts to students, but his homework and quiz questions weren't always reflective of what he spent the most time on in class. The final was horrible, the average was a 64%. In the end, Dr. Gruber seems like a very nice person, and the class was set up so we could drop a few of our lowest assignments.

Professor Gruber is one of the most exceptional instructors. When I first joined his class, I had no prior knowledge, however, through his dedicated teaching, guidance and support, I not only was able to understand the subject, but also excelled in the class and earned an A. He is extremely fair, genuine, and committed to his students' learning.
Literally the worst professor at Hopkins

Don't read the articles- just watch the video lectures. In class lectures are boring. Nothing novel being learned. Don't put effort into presentations, they are free 100s. "Knowledge checks" are by participation, but the final was literally copy+paste the same questions so do it right as a study guid. Final is 50% of grade- multiple choice, 30 Qs.

He's a nice guy, but the class is just devoid of any subject material. Be prepared to learn literally nothing. Also beware, you have to present slides every class and you have to present your final paper, so it's really more of a public speaking course than anything.
She is a pretty good. Professor. She may not explain everything very well in class, but she will take the time after the class to make sure you know the subject matter.

Good professor
Great class

Definitely a great professor. She teaches you skills that will make you successful in future expos classes. You can tell she cares about her students and she always give great feedback. She also participates in faculty-student interactions.
Really great professor! Gives interesting readings and is really devoted to her students. I still visit with her even though I'm not in her class anymore.
Tough professor. Even calling her professsor by mistake instead of doctor could receive a warning by her. Late for handling assignment for two minutes resulted in no score for it.
tough professor
Fair grader. Keeps it interesting and she's funny!!

Basically watches over 4-5 TA's for a class and oddly enough videotapes them from time to time.  Most TA's are ok. Haven't seen her since the first class (?).  Awful textbook choice for this level Spanish class and online homework doesn't give ANY leeway for multiple possibility type questions.  Essays hardly graded for content.
The class sucked. Timed 100 question test on a stupid manual. 120 minutes to take the test.

Not helpful when approached. Teaching style favors the hands-off approach.  100 question multiple choice test with content based solely on 380 pages from an ANSI manual.  Unimpressed with knowledge.  Just teaches with "tidbits" of information.  Severely lacking enough for me to withdraw and pursue my degree elsewhere.

Would be an engaging guy if he weren't incredibly self-involved.  Not interested in hearing anyone else talk but himself.  Grades very harshly, on some level to help students improve, but its clear he gets off on giving back terrible grades.

It's clear that Prof. Leithauser knows his material, and his thoughts on literature are thoughtful and profound.  Still, his tone and choice of readings can be rather dry, which makes long classes with him hard to sit through.

lots of work to do. the way too much. Josh is brand new for teaching, that means he really doesn't know how to teach. just don't take this class. study ios dev by your self online. you will find better study resources. if you just want to take this course for credit? be prepared you already have ios dev experiences. worst ever

comment: Josh knows his stuff but his course lacks structure and clarity. Be prepared to do a lot of independent research. 95% of what I learned about iOS (Swift and XCode) came from online research. Jon Hricko hols his students to high standards and seems genuinely concerned with everyone's learning. He's laid back yet really interesting.

Grades kind of tough on the first essay.  Everyone in the class got a C on the first essay, a B on the second essay and an A on the third essay.  He is nice, expects a lot, but is  willing to have a good time.
The smartest professor I have ever had. An absolute genius. His teaching is intellectually stimulating

This class was called Spanish Avantgarde. It was amazing. Great material. Such an amazing and astute professor. The class is not easy. She is incredibly caring, and her teaching made me intensely interested in literary studies. She truly tries to involve all the students in the discussions and makes class engaging. I would highly recommend her introductory literature class. Her office hours are also very helpful.

comment: Awesome professor.

Assignments were a nuisance, in the sense that you don't learn much, they leave you frustrated, and they take alot of time. comment: Good class/professor. She's responsive to questions, and explains concepts well. comment: Professor Angelini is highly knowledgable on the many disparate subsets of anthropology and is an expert purveyor in interesting ideas. This class is basically like more concrete philosophy in that you regularly write, discuss and consider ideas on many topics within anthro. He is also an extremely kind human being. At times, it gets too political.

Prof Angelini is so amazing. He is so well versed and is very passionate and intelligent in his field, he gave amazing lectures that were extremely insightful and interesting. He asks for participation in classes but he makes it so easy and interesting to participate it doesn't matter. If you are at all interested in anthro/culture, take his class

Dr. Jasnow is a very funny and kind professor. Although his lectures are a bit boring, his class was pretty easy and intriguing for anyone interested in ancient Egypt. Anyone can, and should, take this class.

He is extremely caring, just a lovely person, and so much fun to talk with. I highly recommend taking at least one class with him, if not more!

I had two courses with Professor Masugi and both courses were definitely reading and writing intensive - but doable if you manage your time well. comment: My one big complaint about this class is that when you register, the course is marked as not being writing intensive. comment: Really just genuinely kind. Always letting us know she's there for us if we have questions. I had a family thing happen this semester and she was so understanding and thoughtful, unlike some of my other professors lol. I really enjoy reading now and I especially love writing.
Genuinely wants her students to do well and have meaningful, engaging discussions about the material. Great class!

comment: His class was really hard but there was a big final grade curve. He made question banks to help us study for the final and was always available to talk. His handwriting could be a bit better, though.

WORST TEACHER EVER! disorganized lectures and unrecognizable handwriting. Midterms were completely different from lectures and hw. When I asked him for advice, he literally told me just to relax. rating_tags: Group projects--Lecture heavy--Graded by few things

comment: The prof skips slides when lecturing, and usually, I don't know what he's talking about. You will need to study the slides by yourself, and sometimes you don't know the linkage between the unbelievable homework and the course. The prof assumes you know everything before the course (but we don't). Not recommended, avoid the prof if you can.

Professor Robinson is great and her classes are generally relaxing. Dr. Robinson is so great with her students and cares deeply about their well-being. She is willing to give much feedback and discussion on ideas for papers. It will be easy to form ideas for assignments and there is much flexibility when it comes to letting her know how you are feeling and what is happening outside of school.

Dr. Locke understands that we all have busy lives outside of this class, and in turn creates a challenging but fair course. One of those classes where if you put effort into doing the work, you'll be just fine. Highly recommend!

comment: Great professor, gave good feedback, graded things in a timely manner. A solid professor, I definitely recommend taking him. comment: Such a helpful professor. He will tell you exactly what you need to know for the exams in class. If you go to lecture, take advantage of the review sessions held, you will be fine. Very interesting topics discussed as well.

Exams are 90% of your grade so STUDY! Focus on knowing the bigger concepts and being able to apply them over small details. Go to lecture because slides have few words and some of the recordings aren't the same. Professor seems distant from the class, but it is interesting and a good overview of the neuroscience major.
Very passionate teacher. Actually learned something  from her class.
No Comments
very sweet and nice teacher. enjoyed taking intermediate and advanced with her.
nice teacher
One of the best professors I have had.
No Comments

Good professor and passionate about counseling. Grading can be arbitrary and not objective. Overall learned a lot and worked my butt off to get an A. Definitely a lot harder than other counseling courses but you get some of the best supervision for your recorded sessions.

Intro to Counseling: 861.507. Worked like crazy to end up with an A-. The workload of this class is unrealistic. Three counseling sessions are conducted with a classmate (accompanied by 10 pg papers) and two research papers - takes forever to get back (over a month). Grading is arbitrary. Take if you want to learn. Skip if you care about your GPA.

I am currently in her techniques class at JHU. Yes! She pushes you to be the best, because she truly cares. I mean come on your at Hopkins your gonna work!!!
Very reactive, anxious, panicky, hot tempered and not very knowledgable about the subject matter

comment: There is a lot of reading and writing in Conversation Compostion but it really improves vocabulary, reading comprehension and writing ability. Speaking did not improve though.
Very nice professor. Gives a LOT of homework, but it does help you learn a lot of vocabulary.

Her instructions was good, but her attitude off the class was abosulutely the opposite. The easiness of the course means that a teacher's profession does not affect your learning very much. Be prepared to the pressure and difficulties she create intentionally.

Statistics is really a hard thing to learn but she explains everything very well and easy to understand. She's the BEST teacher I've ever seen!! Just follow her guideline sheets for the mid-term and final then you will be fine. The pop-up quizzes are quite easy. Revise the materials before each class. She writes everything on the board :)

I LOVE paula!! I had her for 2 classes and she is AWESOME. im so glad that she is finally on here so i can comment on her awesomeness. TAKE MED SPANISH with her! shes so adorable and super sweet too!!
Me gusta a Paula MUCHO!! She is DEF the BEST spanish professor I've had here; and it was awesome to have her teach me for 2 spanish classes this semester.  I LOVE Paula
Ezpz lemon squeezy
Not the most exciting lectures. When I took the course, he made some comments about mental health that made me feel uncomfortable. I didn't ever feel excited to go to this class (intro to sociology).
Prof. Andreas is super kind and relaxed. He is a great lecturer and I learned so much in one semester with him. If you put in some effort you will come out with an A. highly recommend his class

Professor Andreas makes what could be a very dry subject - sociological theories of Marx, Durkheim, and Weber - interesting and relevant. The class involves a decent amount of reading and writing, but it's graded fairly, and class participation is also factored into your final grade.

I could tell from the first class that Professor Woodard is incredibly genuine. She made me feel like she cared about my own goals, even though I was in a really large class. Professor Woodard would proactively reach out to us and set up extra office hours, including virtual office hours, which really helped. She really is there for you.

Prof. Woodard is awesome. The class is crazy with the amount of work due for edtpa but Woodard helps! She is motivating and has scheduled office hours every week to answer questions and feedback. Attendance is required but the homework is intense. This will make you a better teacher and she reminds us that we are colleagues as well as students.
Accent has improved greatly. Takes, and posts better notes than I've seen in any other class.
Interesting professor to learn from. Teaches material thoroughly. However, impossible to understand in class due to heavy accent. Go to section!

Unfortunately, Professor Leboeuf did not host office hours as stated in the syllabus and also did not reply to any emails, Canvas posts, etc. I could not recommend taking her unless you're content to learn purely from pre-recorded lectures conducted by a different set of professors.

Dr. Leboeuf was very kind and caring. Helpful during office hours and was willing to modify assignments/due dates if the class was struggling. Cons - JHU lecture videos were from another professor and weren't very good imo. I think Dr. Leboeuf is new to teaching this class and seemed to be testing out new assignments on us. Very slow grader.
Great professor! Weekly assignments were actually fun and helpful for learning the concepts.
Amazing person, wish she taught more classes at JHU. Definitely a class worth taking.

Extremely unforgiving grader. Requires all assignments to be typed and equations inputted with LaTeX. This professor just lecture on the simple stuff and everything else should be figured out by yourself and will be on the exam. Basically his online video is a waste of time. Excellent classes, led by excellent discussion. The course I took was very reading heavy, but it was beyond worth my time1

Mark Thompson's class on literary theory was phenomenal. The reading syllabus has something for everyone. Do not take intro to public health unless you need it. Dr. B is nice, but her lectures are incredibly boring, her canvas is hard to maneuver when looking back to review. Ok professor but poor example of a department head for the #1 PH program in the world. The final deadline for grade submission was a week ago, and we still don't have our grade. comment: Honestly one of the best professors I have ever had

Great Prof! Really knows his stuff, always brings in real-life examples to the class. There is hw every night, and tests are difficult but he makes the material engaging. Best option for financial accounting.

Avoid! I wish I listened to the other review because it is so accurate. Do not take this class unless you are ready to spend hours on lectures then textbook readings then assignments. Avoid.

His teaching style is really intriguing. It is the way to do economic

Very dense course relative to other semesters. Extremely knowledgeable in all of the content and is able to dissect it into more simple and intuitive explanations. Very math heavy and theoretical. comment: A communication error was made between Professor Alcorn and my team for our group project, and he worked with us to resolve this issue. I don't really lean one way or another. His class wasn't the best I've ever taken, nor the worst. A safe choice overall.

Very funny and enthusiastic. Intimidating at first, but she really just wants to be your friend. If you do the work, you'll be fine.

Great teacher. I can recommend my friends to take his courses.

An absolutely amazing professor.
