Lectures are rushed and somewhat shallow even for complicated material. Homework assignments are huge, though not too complicated. While the exam is crazy with suspicious grading. I do regret taking this course. He must be a good researcher, but teaching is simply not his cup of tea.
The pop quizzes are the worst.

This is probably the best professor to take in the Engineering for Professionals Applied and Computational Mathematics Program. He sticks to the book and teaches you in a way that is fair, and predictable. He does not go on useless tangents and sticks to main ideas and concepts. Tests and homework are fair. Manageable in 12 hours of work a week.
Vague and unfair grading criteria. Test form is inconsistent with what she said on the syllabus.

Professor Fox really cares about what she is teaching about. She is always enthusiastic. But the problem is her teaching skills. She goes too fast on lectures. She skips important slides on lecture notes, and keeps assigning new readings although she has already assigned readings based on the syllabus. The overall structure of the class is messy.
Pretty bad experience.

Dr. Chlan is very out-of-date, disengaged from students. Doesn't offer help. Hard assignments--this is rated as one of the hardest courses at Hopkins. Not particularly sympathetic. A bit of a sadist. And her knowledge set on computer science dates to the 1990s. Don't listen to anything she says about what is current in computer science.
rating_tags: Tough grader--Lots of homework--Graded by few things

comment: Dr. Teague is a thoughtful, kind, and empathetic professor with a clear passion for philosophy. Class was engaging and always thought-provoking.

Prof Teague clearly had a great passion for his work and did a good job sharing that with us through the semester. The course material was quite difficult but super intriguing. Often I would leave class questioning some of the most basic beliefs about the world that I'd had for years!! Philosophy is a great subject and prof Teague was v engaging.

Dr.O is simply the best. She respects everyone's differences and cares about her students. She is really chill and fun. You also learn a lot. I highly recommend her as an ear training teacher, the best I ever had!

Dr. Orlando is a great ET/SS professor. Talk to anyone, and they'll tell you they love taking her class. Some students could definitely stand to come to class more often though. I think she's added a new attendance policy, which is honestly called for. If you have a conflict because you're dual degree (etc.) she was very understanding though.

Edison is by far one of the best professors at Hopkins. He is a very genuine guy and actually care to get to know his student's names. Python can be kind of confusing but his office hours and project workshops were always helpful. His quizzes are also very fair. As long as you show effort and your performance somewhat shows that you'll be fine.

If you come in with any Python experience its an easy A. Study zybook, participate in class, and most can get an A. Projects take lots of time so start them early. Professor is very nice, is soft-spoken, and gives the topics for the quizzes in advance. Quizzes are open textbook and not too challenging. Zybook takes lots of time to do, 5% of grade.
I loved taking Professor Greif's class.
rating_tags: Get ready to read--Group projects--Gives good feedback

comment: The class is really easy. Just surface level knowledge of race and in American society. If you have any background in racial justice, the class will likely be an easy A. There are reading reflections for every lecture but you can miss 3. 2 tests w/ 5 multiple choice questions and 2 page long FRQs, and a final paper.
I would take him for any course! Amazing, he was incredibly nice and so professional.
Great amazing teacher.  Love her so much.  Really cares about your work.  Too bad she is not at Hopkins anymore

This class has a decent amount of reading but it's totally worth it. Laura is a great teacher and really cares about the material, as well as her students. Her lectures are clear and interesting and she always tries to include some class discussion, even if it's a big class. Definitely take a class from her if you have the chance

If you engage, participate and are a self starter with an independent approach you will do just fine. Professor will not spoon feed you. He will lead you to the water, but you must dive in. Read, complete the assignments and express opinions. The take always are worth the investment.

This guy likes to hear the sweet sweet sound of his own voice. He told you what grade you were going to get in the syllabus before you even set foot in his class.  Your fate is predetermined.   He leaves everything up to his TA Alison and she never says a word in class.

Great professor. She moves fast but she's extremely clear and makes even the dullest material interesting and engaging. Be prepared to take a lot of notes and pay strict attention, but also expect to get a lot out of the class. I had no interest in medieval history before The Medieval World and now it's one of my favorite courses.
very passionate, enthusiastic and clear. Her class The Medieval World is great.

Monica was a wonderful teacher truly interested in the subject she teaches and earnestly concerned that students learn their material. She was great at latin and, though softspoken, made sure that everyone participated and learned. Excellent class and teacher

She is very kind and obviously enjoys what she does. I was in her intermediate latin class and overall, it was very easy to do well. She seems genuinely concerned if the students are learning. She can be a little soft spoken at times, but that's not always a bad thing! Great Teacher!
Lot of material is covered. Need to stay diligent and understand the material. Very tough.
Not easy. Need to study a lot and make sure you understand the material. If you are behind, its its too late to play catch up. Good luck you will need it.
Such a cute and adorable instructor with a passion for teaching. Very helpful when students have questions.  One of the best ones at JHU
Great professor! The lectures are interesting, and she's always willing to answer any questions you have. The exams are fair. As long as you come to lecture, you will be successful.

Surprised by the poor review.  This professor has several years of experience in InfoSec and keeps the discussions and assignments relevant to current technology and trends. Combination in-class and online discussions that are interesting.  Short papers weekly and long group paper due at the end.  Worthwhile experience for a foundations course.
Terrible instructor. Does not know material. Told class we needed to read her mind. Seems to do a reverse curve to keep most people from getting an A. Grading arbitrary.
Systems engineering with the BEST PROFESSOR EVER

Homework makes up most of the grade, and it is always self-explanatory.  Open note exams, and he posts the lecture online.  He doesn't like the idea of stressful learning, which is why he does this, but he covers a lot of material. Midterms are based on in-class examples (which are in the notes).

One of the best German language professors that I have had in college. Shows a definite interest in making sure that each student understands the material, and always comes up with a creative application for our language-learning. I ended up learning a lot about German culture/literature, as well.

She's a really nice person and a pretty decent teacher. One thing that bothered me though, was that she often returned our homework late and sometimes got ahead of herself when she was teaching. Overall a good professor though :)

Great professor, very knowledgeable about the subject and makes many connections to outside references. Felt like I was learning a lot about history and life in general instead of just the texts that were assigned. However, he is not an easy grader.
Inspiring--passionate about his subject.  Hard but fair.

I took his graduate seminar in Baroque Perfomance Practice, Beginning Viol, Viol consort, and baroque band and I have to say John is a very knowledgeable and very fun professor.  Class/rehearsal is never boring, and I have him (and his wife, Risa Browder) to thank for getting me going on baroque strings.  Plus, John wears the coolest socks ever.
What a great teacher! This professor makes me want to go to class. He facilitates discussions so we really learn!

Professor Yassa is excellent. He's clearly very knowledgeable in the subject matter and teaches it with a passion you don't find in other professors. He genuinely cares about every single person getting an A in the class. I'm not a neuroscience major and yet I was still able to get an A and understand everything, because he makes it so transparent.

Professor Yassa is easily the best professor at Hopkins. His lectures are exciting, straightforward, and never boring. The course content is incredibly diverse covering all aspects of learning and memory. Exams are absolutely fair and he is always available outside class and office hours for questions. I would take any other class he teaches.
Professor Carpenter clearly loves poetry and loves teaching. He really inspired me to go on and pursue poetry. His feedback is incredibly detailed. Great guy
rating_tags: Gives good feedback--Get ready to read--Inspirational

comment: Great guy, really wacky assignments. You will LOVE IT!!!!
rating_tags: Gives good feedback--LOTS OF HOMEWORK--BEWARE OF POP QUIZZES

comment: If you're seeking an Intersession course, this is it. You're def not going to sit around watching videos, like some other courses offered. Prof. Zwi is clearly excited by the material and he knows *a lot.* If you're willing to show up and do your work, class will be like hanging out with a cool dude who knows a ton and likes to teach. Good stuff.

This was an incredible course with mind-boggling material and amazing lectures that allowed us to think more critically and penetrate the deeper meanings of the text, art, and music we encountered. This was definitely one of the best classes in all my time at Hopkins!
He gives very little direction and no feedback. You're on your own to figure things out.

This class is great. Although the professor isn't always present in the discussions, the course is designed to be autotutorial. The textbook isn't really needed. There is quite a bit of writing here. There is a running group project throughout the course. This class requires work but it is not difficult. If you put the work in, you'll get an A.

Dagdaddy has been teaching for many years, far too many years. His exams are tough and test you over very miniscule details. You need to know how to take to his tests more than the knowledge itself. It's possible to get an A but get ready to work for it.
tests are tough. you have to read and study a lot and do not skip the details. He is a tough grader

This class was tough for me, but learning any language is tough. Professor Soo Yun Lee really works with you to help if you come to office hours, and it's easy to ask questions during class if you forgot a word/grammar point or if you want to clarify or dont understand something. Don't slack on the HW, it can really bite you in the butt
rating_tags: Participation matters--Clear grading criteria--Gives good feedback

comment: Taking 3rd level Korean P/F with her (grad student). This class should be the GOLD standard for ALL language classes. She is kind, fun, an effective instructor, and creates a safe and positive learning environment. JHU is lucky to have her and I'm lucky to have her as my instructor. Your hard work and dedication do not go unnoticed, Prof Lee! :)

Incredible guy. Deeply cares about students. Interested in supporting students & making sure they do well. Content is a little dry at times but if you stay on top of the minimal assignments, you'll get an A. Students need to be self-motivated bc the major grade comes from a semester-long project that doesn't have many intermediate assignments.

His class is fun and easy to follow with lots of great personal stories for leadership theories. You can do really well on weekly papers if you write specific examples. I used textbook but it's not mandatory.

I enjoyed taking Professor Miller's Image Engineering class. He was always available during office hours and was pretty responsive via email. Homework load is reasonable and understandable. There are a lot of lectures but they definitely help when absorbing the concepts. Overall, fantastic professor and would enjoy taking him again!
rating_tags: Clear grading criteria--Lecture heavy--Accessible outside class

comment: Good professor.  Class wasn't relevant to my work but still interesting material.  Lots of lectures, homework was not super light but reasonable.

Dr. Balanoff is incredibly caring and nice and a professor who genuinely cares about you learning material and concepts rather than just focusing on grades and assignments. Highly recommend taking one of her classes.

There's still a few weeks left in class, but I wanted to rate her before I forget. Dr. Balanoff is a total gem. If you're struggling, reach out and she'll work with you. Her lectures are clear and are all you need to study for exams. On top of that, for this class, there's a 20 point extra credit essay. I would encourage anyone to take her classes.

Horrible professor that was not that effective in teaching. I had to use the online COVID lectures from Torcaso in the second half of the course. I wish I knew about them sooner because the online lectures are so much clearer and straightforward than Pisano's structured lectures.

Professor Pisano has a talent for making engaging lectures about, what can be, dull content. By the time I finished this class, I felt like I had a much deeper understanding of Prob/Stats and no longer felt an aversion towards the subject, as someone who isn't always great at math. He's also very willing to dive deeper on certain topics if asked.
Dr. Thornton was hands down the best professor I had this semester. Her lectures are clear and inspiring, encouraging more questions than answers. Would 100% recommend to any IS/Sociology major.

Professor Thornton is an excellent lecturer. I don't recommend taking if you know nothing about Econ because it is pretty reliant on Econ info. However, in the lectures she goes over all of the info from the readings and makes them easy to understand. No tests. One take home short essay midterm and a final group project. 8 Discussion Posts.
Get  ready to read

I have had this professor for 3 Classes: Negotiation & Mediation, Employment Law, and Constitutional Rights.  If you show up, pay attention, and participate you'll do great!  She has a great sense of humor!
Great prof. best at hopkins. Very knowledgable and interested in the courses she teaches. much better in seminars than in lecture.

Prof. Meyer-Fong is a natural genius-- brilliant and clearly invested in her subject of interest. During discussions, she is enthusiastic about every student's comment, yet also doesn't let participants make useless comments for the sake of 'discussion points'. Her passion is contagious and makes attending class that much more absorbing.
Fantastic professor. Great sense of humor and brilliant lectures! Don't leave Hopkins without taking one of his classes!
No Comments
learned very little from the professor had to teach my self from the book in order to pass
a good professor
Zhan Li was actually my favorite professor so far!
Straightforward, explains the material without being too technical and in-depth about theorem and proofs. Need textbook for homework problemsets.

The professor seems to be relaxed, but a little too much. We are nearing the end of the semester and nothing (actually nothing) has been graded. The homework were incredibly complicated and time consuming (tedious). The homework would also not be released in a timely manner so we would get a very little amount of time to complete the assignment.
vague
Prof. Jain is a great researcher, but has a bit accent so sometimes I didn't understand those course contents. However, he really provides a good course.
Extremely intelligent and a good teacher.  Can give you research opportunities.
He's brilliant and cares about his students  and classes. The subjects of his courses are fascinating. He is quiet and has a dry sense of humor that we all appreciate.

Professor McCarter is world renowned for his work on the dead sea scrolls.  He knows so much.  Sometimes his lectures are a bit hard to follow because of that.  But, he's interesting, helpful, and it all comes together in the end.
good teach
No Comments

Dr. Jones will have you examine Colonial America from multiple, often out of the ordinary, perspectives through lecture, discussion groups, and readings. You will read. A LOT. He is super flexible if you have a legitimate reason for missing class. His exams can be tough. He really want you to know the topic inside and out.
rating_tags: Gives good feedback--Get ready to read--ACCESSIBLE OUTSIDE CLASS

comment: Fantastic professor and great class on the military history of early America. Lecture and discussion. Do the reading!
"What makes great people great is not that they're always great, its that they're sometimes great.  Some people are never great.  That's just how it works." - Zlatko
AMAZING!!!!!!!

The whole Archaeology department is just lovely, but Dr Anderson is something else. She is so caring, the class is never dull, and in addition to her heartwarming character she is incredibly experienced and knowledgeable. If you get the chance to take any of her 2.5 hour classes in the archaeology museum, take one, no matter your major.

Any class by Anderson is going to be incredible! She is sweet, personable, and you really learn the material via discussion and interaction.  If you are an archaeology major or not you HAVE to take one of her classes! AS.040.218(01)

Loved the class! Totally recommend for seniors. You learn more than you think, and Dr Nevin is really into the subject, since he was an army doctor. Hoping to score an A, but the final may be tough. Midterm was moderately tough, but very fair, just be sure to attend classes and do the readings.
Good seminar. Learned lots. Would recommend.

Jesse teaching Calc 2 was amazing, especially in the beginning with establishing fundamentals. He's got a great sense of humor and is pretty easy on the eyes, so not hard to like the lectures. Make sure to keep up with the textbook and homework, and reworking and understanding the homework is perfect for doing well in this class. Such a cutie

Amazing professor. The class wasn't easy by any means, but he really was a wonderful professor. I'd love to have him again.   He's a great lecturer and if he makes any mistakes he'll email them out. He's always there if we have questions and he really respects everyone's input. You do need to read the book, but he's there if you need help.

She doesn't seem to care for students learning and rarely responded to students' questions on time or ever. The TAs took all the responsibilities. The TAs helped tremendously with our course. But still, I don't think the core concepts were explained thoroughly in the lectures she gave.

She doesn't give lectures. Sometimes she gives notes on the topic. She just assigns books and papers to read the contradict each other constantly. She is a tough grader but doesn't give back the grades quickly so you don't know where you are at until it is too late. She also doesn't give back sufficient feedback.
rating_tags: Tough Grader--Get ready to read--LOTS OF HOMEWORK

comment: I liked how a lot of the class focused on figuring out how to use different DL libraries. I had never really thought of that as an important skill until I took the course, but now I see how valuable that is and am glad to have some experience in this area. I also liked how the class was application-based, but still summarized the important points.
He taught a really amazing intersession course on deep learning. I loved the style, the case-based approach was new to me but I learned a lot.

Was not responsive to any of my e-mails, extremely poor course organization: nearly no lectures or instructions, extremely dependent on self-study. She was seldom attentive to the course; once she set the deadline of one assignment but delayed 4 days to actually give the materials (nonresponsive during that period). A course with nearly NO values.

The online psychology class was poor. She did not provide any good feedback for assignments or discussions. I think she's not a good teacher because she doesn't know how to add good comments to the class discussion and does not reply to emails. If you have a technical issue or questions in the class, she is of no help. The worst summer class ever.

Get a group, try the homework, read/watch the lecture, ask questions, then you're guarantee to pass. Very difficult class but the instructor is very supportive and makes himself available to help his students.
rating_tags: Gives good feedback--Accessible outside class--Amazing lectures

comment: This class requires effective time management from students to review notes, read the book, and solve the problem sets. Brendan is passionate about the topics. He supports a lot his students and brings insight from his experience. One of the best courses to take at Johns Hopkins University
rating_tags: Gives good feedback--Clear grading criteria--Amazing lectures

comment: Love him

Had Husain for elements of micro fall 2022. I personally thought he was a very good lecturer, and he is a funny, caring guy. We had about an 80 person class and he knew most peoples names. His exams, however, are very conceptual and often have tough true false questions that can make or break your score. Therefore, the class can be kinda hard.
really good person
He's super nice, take his classes!
Prof. Wang is a remarkably intriguing teacher. He consistently puts forth his utmost effort to impart knowledge to his students and strives for the student's success. He is a great professor!

Dr. Wang is extremely generous and kind. You can tell he loves what he is teaching and wants his students to do well. He does a great job at making sure the students understand the content and he is very accessible & helpful during Office Hours. Amazing overall, would definitely recommend having him as an instructor.
I like her lecture style! If you listen to her lectures you will receive a good grade. Hope to see her again.
rating_tags: Get ready to read--Group projects--Amazing lectures

comment: Nice overview on different methods and technology in lab. Dr. Wellman previously taught this class, so some of the content/structure is similar to her epigenetics class (would also recommend) and carried over: essay style exams, four problem sets, lecture slides, and discussion. Easy to reach for an explanation/further clarification if needed.
rating_tags: Get ready to read--Participation matters--Gives good feedback

comment: Best experience for my first class in this program. You have to put in the work, but Ron sets you up for success. Rubrics were clearly laid out for each assignment, and constructive feedback was received. Super responsive to messages and is very self-aware in being fair when giving assignments and grading them.
rating_tags: Group projects--Clear grading criteria--Gives good feedback

comment: If he is an option, take him. He's such an amazing professor. He clearly loves his job and cares about what he does. There are a lot of assignments/projects and some group work but he reads/pays attention to every thing you submit it and gives through feedback. Seriously never seen a prof. give so much good feedback. He made me excited to learn.
rating_tags: Clear grading criteria--Gives good feedback--Accessible outside class

comment: Andreas is a very good proffesor and he really cares about it's students.

The professor spent lecture time explaining things (badly) that were tangentially related to the course and when asked a question about something actually important would laugh at you and tell you to read the book.  No wonder every project got an extension; he didn't explain how to do projects until the day they were due.

I thoroughly enjoyed my freshman seminar, and would definitely take any other class that Professor Libowitz taught. I feel like I learned so much, without being overwhelmed. Professor Libowitz genuinely cares that we understand the material, rather than that we have everything memorized. He clearly cares about his students and our education.

One of the best professors you could ask for your first-year at Hopkins. He teaches by being able to apply what we learn in class to the cases he brings up. There are minimal numbers of readings, and no written assignments. It mainly just participation in-class and the final mock trial using the things we've learned in-class.
Best biochem professor.  He is really clear.

Lightner teaches Radioactive Waste Management at Hopkins EP program. He's very knowledgeable about the everything radiation and his lectures are so interesting, as are the readings he assigns! There are both individual & group HW assignments each week, and an individual as well as a group project - it's time consuming. Definitely cite EVERYTHING.

He is a solid researcher and educator; his course has lots of homework and he enjoys even adding more to it. He is extremely observant and quite. It may make you feel uncomfortable first, but you'll get used to it. If that happened, remember that his best friend and lunch buddy is this adrenaline (cheerful) diplomat character faculty, Dr. Manbachi!
rating_tags: Tough Grader--LOTS OF HOMEWORK--Clear grading criteria

comment: The lectures are extremely boring and the grading is pretty harsh. I really did not learn anything from this course. He essentially reads lecture slides which are monolithic blocks of text.
Exams are very long...goes over a lot of material in one class, and almost all of it is on the exam. Final was a presentation when I took it, and it wasn't too bad.

Really chill professor, cares if you understands the topics and is reasonable with grading., especially if you are not a strong writer. Writing topics are a bit difficult to understand though, his office hours are very helpful.

Dr. Tilli is a decent lecturer, explains the biochemical pathways well. But, I found that what she stressed in class was not always to the level of detail that she expected on the exams. Some things seemed as if we didn't need to know them at all, and they were a large portion of the test. She is awesome in office hours and lab though!

Good professor overall. Tries to get his students involved and the activities he makes help you to see stuff at the macro level, which is very helpful. Most importantly, he's always open to students, not like most professors. And he does know a lot about the subjects he teaches.
Pretty cool instructor.
Great and helpful!

Provides clear examples and answers questions well. Homeworks aren't too bad, but there is always one problem that sucks, but TAs are helpful. Labs are pointless but graded easily. The lecture is very helpful. There is often an unassigned homework/example problem on an exam, so you might want to study the solutions to these (which she posts).

Pretty helpful professor if u go to his office hour. Exams can be a bit hard because there are only 40 points and 88% or above for an A. But there will be final grade bonuses based on everyday's quiz.
Very easy exam, and accomodating professor, would love to take this Spring..

I really cannot understand why a good name school, like Johns Hopkins, hires such an incompetent instructor. I already had PhD from another university before I started MS at the Applied Economics program, and I have seen all kinds of instructors, but I rate him the worst I have had since grade school. He cannot even answer basic questions.

Nancy is a working professional, so pay attention. Tips for success: 1) answer the DQs on time, 2) find hints in her lectures, 3) learn AP style, 4) read the grading rubric before writing an essay, 5) use your critical thinking in your analyses, and 6) focus on your group work. Grammar is important, so don't be lazy. She is one of my favorites!
rating_tags: CARES ABOUT STUDENTS--ACCESSIBLE OUTSIDE CLASS--GROUP PROJECTS

comment: The class was bit heavy on assignments. But the lectures were amazing, with lots of scope for in-class thinking, participation, discussions etc.
rating_tags: LOTS OF HOMEWORK--Clear grading criteria--Amazing lectures

comment: Super nice professor
Great professor. Really friendly and engaging. Doesn't just lecture but leads interesting class discussions.
I really enjoyed this class, the texts were interesting and Chris is awesome. Totally gay but really attractive in an older man way anyways. Loves what he does.

I have literally never met anyone that didn't adore Dr. Benjamin. She's one of the best profs at Hopkins. Her classes are engaging and occasionally mind-blowing, and she's probably the nicest person you'll ever meet. 10/10 would take more of her classes if I could.
Lurhmann is the light of my life. He is the personification of a ray of sunshine. I am not monotone man.

He gave interesting lectures which always included current news stories. The papers and exams allowed you to pick your own topic, so you could choose what you felt most passionate about. The only problem was that he didn't give clear criteria for grading and you couldn't be sure what exactly he expected -though the TAs helped with that.

This is at UMGC! She never actually showed up to class. She is a glorified grader and didn't educate me at all. I wish I would have taken a different professor. Spending good money on my classes only to see that my professor grades my work is a huge let down. I had to open up a case about her 4 times because of different issues in the classroom.
Dr. Fischer is an amazing lecturer who sparked a real interest in perceptual science in me. His Sensation and Perception class helped me decide to major in Neuroscience. Would 100% recommend.
It would be beneficial to write down every single thing she writes on the board. Usual weekly hw set, quiz, written hw due on the same day. Not a very good lecturer and exams are really hard

Had her for History of Medicine. Professor Hanson is enthusiastic about the material; her lectures are quite interesting. She's kind and willing to help outside of class. TAs do a lot of the grading; they are kind as well and give great feedback. There are many extra credit opportunities; overall not difficult, pay attention and you'll do well.
rating_tags: Gives good feedback--Clear grading criteria--EXTRA CREDIT

comment: Dr Greene's teaching style is very 'keep it as simple as possible, but no simpler'. Beginner level CS concepts can be tough to teach, but even intermediate programmers will likely learn a thing or two still. Take home finals that were challenging but doable. Great intro class for fundamental skills with an emphasis upon those important for bioinfo

This class is fine if you spend the mental effort associated with keeping up with the professor as he speaks. The accent and handwriting can be a bit difficult to work through at times however. Otherwise, he is a fine professor.

Overhated I think, he's not the best lecturer but you can tell he cares about the math. OH are not super helpful and the tests were more focused on speed than knowledge, but overall it was a solid class. Wouldn't go out of my way to take him, but wouldn't drop b/c I had him.

Prof Kim is one of the most inspiring profs I had at the East Asian Studies department. She has a unique approach to Japanese history and I was inspired tremendously merely by talking to her. Shes not only an amazing scholar but also a vocal advocate for history. Take advantage of her office hours and you wont regret.

She was strong on content, lenient on pop quizzes, and adept at asynchronous formats. I thought of her today because everything is online now due to Covid and I had a jump on everything in 2020 because I took her class previously.

Very difficult to get an A in her class. Her lectures are disorganized and hard to understand. The quizzes and exams are online but SO difficult. The Exam is 4 hours (2 parts) with 46 multiple choice and 9 short answer. She is also not easily accessible through email. I would avoid this professor.
rating_tags: Get ready to read--Test heavy--Lecture heavy

comment: Extremely vague questions, badly written problems. Will take off points for correct answers if they do not match exactly what she wanted. Very hard to understand during lecture as well.

Loved this class, the virtual live format allowed Chuck (and co-professor Pete Harmatuk) to make the class engaging. Really appreciated the ad libbed examples from his current and previous work experience. Very kind, flexible, and understanding. Great communicator and enthusiastic about the subject

The professor is a great lecturer and is very patient. The class is lecture-heavy because there is no textbook used. Grades are based on test score only, but the professor provides extra credit opportunity to improve grades if needed. Tests are very straight forward. Study and you'll pass.
rating_tags: Skip class? You won't pass.--Test heavy--EXTRA CREDIT

comment: One of the most caring and professional educators I have ever met.

I took Persuasion from Dr. B. as part of the MA/Communication program at Johns Hopkins. She is an incredible professor! Great lecturer, fascinating content, & challenging (yet manageable) assignments. It's clear she wants us to succeed, and she is available to help whenever needed. I would take another class from her in a heartbeat!

Fun class that didn't require student to read ahead of time.  A lot of role-playing.  The final threw some people off.  I would recommend to take good reading note, review the note, and rewatch the lecture video to prepare for it.  It was open book exam so not too difficult.
rating_tags: Get ready to read--Participation matters--Group projects

comment: Cool class, very practical. Weekly homework, discussion, and lab assignments that don't usually take too long but are interesting (i.e. performing worm attack, working with IDS tools). You also do a mock group pentesting exercise which was kinda confusing at first but was pretty fun once I understood the flow of it. Definitely recommend the class

I enjoyed taking this class from Professor Dickey. She did a great job and really cared about the students. The work was hard sometimes, but she helped my group get through the projects when we didn't understand something. The projects were fun and the lectures weren't too long.
Honestly the worst professor I've ever had. He just reads definitions and formulas. He doesn't work through problems or explain why things need to be done. Prepare to be taught by YouTube.

Easy class, nice professor. Gives feedback and grades quickly. Good if you have no background on cGMP but very basic/underwhelming course if you have experience in the field. Guess that's on par for an intro class. Can complete assignments for the week in < 3 hours. Easy A.

Introduction to Prob and Stat. Alot of material covered in the course and the HW takes time, but you will learn a lot. Dr. Johnson and Dr. Mcculloh teach the course together and do a great job at it. They bring real world experience to the class which makes it engaging. Excel is used for statistical analysis. Dr. Johnson makes great videos!

Lectures are just powerpoint slides that you need to read through; no added voice recordings, which is tough for auditory learners. Instructions for the final paper and final group project were very vague. Requires weekly discussion posts, but he does not participate or provide any feedback. Not a class worth taking.
rating_tags: Lots of homework--Graded by few things--Group projects

comment: Overall Klausen was not a horrible professor. This being her first time teaching Orgo II definitely made the course a bit harder. The exams were on the most part very straightforward, with the exception of exam 2. It was a bit frustrating that she did not give answer keys to her back tests, which were borrowed from Falzone.

Prof. Galasi seems like a very nice person, however his class was a bit boring and required a lot of reading. Overall, I would take another one of his courses, I think it was just this one that wasn't my favorite.
rating_tags: Get ready to read--Gives good feedback

comment:
Pros:
- Advanced course with new tech introducing
- High grading curve.
- Projects can be published if excellent.

Cons:
- Professor speaks slowly.
- Lectures can be boring.


The grading rubric discussed in the first class seems intimidating, but it's actually quite simple in practice.

You'll need to stay up to date on readings and lectures to balance the quizzes and discussions each week. I appreciated the essay exams instead of just MC questions. Dr. Morgan uses lectures created by another professor a few years ago, but was responsive when I asked questions and seems a very fair grader.
rating_tags: Participation matters--Clear grading criteria--Gives good feedback

comment: Dr. Morgan is helpful, a fast grader, and accessible for questions. I would highly recommend taking this class with her if possible. Truly top tier. Class is not easiest but if you read the Carlberg textbook as suggested you'll be fine. One midterm, one final, both take-home essays. Don't buy the other textbook; you won't ever use it.
rating_tags: Participation matters--Gives good feedback--Accessible outside class

comment: I wanted to express my appreciation for his teaching style and the quality of his classes. Despite being relatively new to teaching, his ability to convey complex material in an understandable and engaging manner is exceptional. The challenge was balanced with his clear explanations and supportive teaching approach.

Dr. Hull cares about her students in the most genuine and compassionate ways! Her in-class activities are creative, get you to delve deeper into the nuances of outlining, citations, and simple structural essay components that one would otherwise gloss over or assume proficiency in. However, her feedback has no mercy despite rubric ambiguity.

The professor grades subjectively and does not follow the rubric she provides for essays during class. She will manage to find sources that support her views even if Purdue owl does not. All classes are completely lectures, and she does not give work time in class, and expects you to do work over break.
rating_tags: Tough grader--Lecture heavy--Graded by few things

comment: 70% of the grade in this class depended on the scores of 3 essay assignments, none of which had a rubric or clear guidelines. Point distributions and grading felt extremely arbitrary and completely up to the professor's discretion. Many of the readings felt directionless and unimportant. Would not recommend unless clearer instructions are given.
rating_tags: Tough grader--Participation matters--Graded by few things

comment: Don't take this class if you value your sanity. She doesn't respond to any messages and when she does arrange for an actual meeting, she fails to show up. She says she doesn't want stuff done in a cookie-cutter approach, but that just means she doesn't want to give us a rubric to go off of. There is no direction with this class with projects/tests.
rating_tags: Get ready to read--Skip class? You won't pass.--Lecture heavy

comment: Generally nice teacher with clear expectations

Taking Matrix Theory with Prof. Lizard (her preferred name) was one of my biggest mistakes this year. She assigns incredibly unnecessary busy work and doesn't seem to care about the "applied" side of the subject. On top of that, if you attempt to be pragmatic in your work, she deducts points. Avoid at all costs if you care about your life.

First Year Seminar course is pass/fail only. Work is very straightforward: read the assigned material, actively engage in discussions, and it's an easy pass. Knowledgeable and passionate. Very caring, easygoing, and straightforward, and there's no extra work like writing essays. Great Professor and great class!
He seems to think that your average student learns best via proof. The textbook is also close to useless- problems are in the right place by chapter, but not by section.

I took Feminist and Queer Theory with him. He is really cool (ordered us pizza multiple times) and is very down to earth. GREAT discussions in the class (don't even have to do the readings in order to participate). Had to write three papers but mostly just explaining others' arguments, not making arguments of your own. Approachable and funny!

He's a very nice guy, ALWAYS willing to help, and very intelligent. However, he is an awful lecturer. His thick accent is only one reason for this. He speaks incredibly fast and his demeanor during lecture makes him unapproachable, so that you are afraid to ask questions.
rating_tags: LOTS OF HOMEWORK--ACCESSIBLE OUTSIDE CLASS--TEST HEAVY

comment: Available most of the time for appointments, responds quickly to emails, easy to talk to. Would recommend taking him for any courses that cover medieval arts and history. Gives all the material necessary for reading. Textbooks are primarily for background information. Gives extra credit.
Extremely knowledgable, loves discussing his field andn current topics. Assignments are great as he gives you a lot of flexibility to be creative, and readings are really nice and relevant.
Very hard but very interesting course. Professor is very helpful but homework assignments and exams are very hard.
The most stressful teacher I've ever dealt with. She's horrible at explaining and she switches up requirements without warning often

I personally like Joel. His funny. But you dont learn much. You dont necessarily have to go to class. Just do your homework and readings. You have to go to all section meetings, since he gives quizzes. Not much work is required. Easy A+ class.

Boring lectures, ppl either don't come or fall asleep in class.  The choice of text is horrible, with very few examples.  Great guy though, very approachable.  The TAs don't speak English, but know the craft.

Prof. Altschul is extremely warm and friendly. She conducts class completely in Spanish and speaks at a native pace so be prepared for that. Class had an extremely manageable amount of reading - some reading was in English, some in Spanish. Overall, I had a great experience with her and would definitely take a class with her in the future.
Great teacher.  He is really clear to understand nad is easy to approach.  It's orgo though, so what can you expect.

Do not take his class, you will hate yourself for staying in the class. No one understands what he talks about, and he doesn't think there is something wrong when more than 60% of the class gets lower than C.

So, this class's content is pretty much learned online with a physics program that is required for the ourse. I rarely paid attention in class, except to respond to mandatory questions that counted participation in the class. The professor is very nice, however, and usually reasonable.

He's not good at explaining things or writing clear instructions. If you ask for clarification, he re-routes you to the assignment description. He does grade very fairly. Creativity counts in his class, so use it to your advantage!

KK is very fair and a great lecturer. Attending lectures is HIGHLY RECOMMENDED, even though he will post his notes online which are very helpful. He is very understanding and you should frequent his office hours. The final was near impossible but he curves well. The exams are also tricky but try to find back tests and you'll be fine.

Dr. Wang is a bit difficult to understand during lectures so make sure you pay attention. He asks you to do the reading and YOU SHOULD. He will ask for anyone has done the reading and may assign extra credit. It also keeps you in tune with what he's teaching in class. He's a bit intimidating in class but is very helpful during office hours.
Changes criteria for group projects the day that the project is due. Additionally, does not read emails thoroughly.
He's the best professor ever, he was very good about feedback and our entire group loved and respected him by the end of the semester
The lectures are good, very straight forward and interesting. The tests are not very difficult and the curve is friendly. One of my favorite economics classes at Hopkins.
rating_tags: Skip class? You won't pass.--Clear grading criteria--Amazing lectures

comment: Assignment instructions are very vague. Does not explain things well. She will act petty if you try to question her grading and she shows it. Class content can be improved. Overall did not enjoy this class and her teaching style. Can tell she has a preference for certain things.

First class I've taken that I really felt the Professor didn't care about the subject she was teaching, or the students she was interacting with. Really disappointing experience and would not recommend to other students.
rating_tags: Tough Grader--Skip class? You won't pass.--LOTS OF HOMEWORK

comment: Professor Khan is a gem. Grades your first paper very roughly, but if you follow her feedback from it then you will do better.
rating_tags: Gives good feedback--Get ready to read--Hilarious

comment: Took her for linear algebra, She is by far the nicest professor in the math department, she told us she would give out as many A's as possible - and she lived up to that promise!

Clay (he asks us to call him by his first name!) is an absolute joy to be around. His class is easily my favorite. He doesn't hold anything back, which is extremely refreshing. He seems to genuinely care about his students, too. He's made me such a better writer, and a much more contemplative person.

TA for The Medieval World. He was a great TA and made the class worthwhile. I learned more in his section than I did lectures. He is a really great teacher and gives good feedback on weekly writing assignments. He cares about students and took the time to reach out to me about my goals in taking the class. Best TA I've had so far at Hopkins.
Easy A in his class
rating_tags: Gives good feedback--Accessible outside class--Skip class? You won't pass.

comment: Dr. Campbell is a caring and knowledgeable professor in the field. He remembers all of our names. He is really a nice grader and his exams are not hard if you take notes and pay attention in classes. The group project and field trip are also fun. Would love to take his classes again in the future.

The professor read through his slides, which does not help students to grasp concept. In addition, the department is irresponsible not putting any pre-req for this course. The courses uses a classical graduate text. It requires at least one course of prior knowledge in set theory and philosophy proofs (formal logic etc).

Belkoff is a nice guy, and his lectures can be funny, but they aren't structured very well. Mostly, he just does practice problems on the board and you are mostly expected to learn the material on your own, so attending class isn't necessary. Exams are pretty simple, not much harder than high school physics, they're generally pretty fair.

Impatient, will trivialize your questions and not help you at all in-depth, as if he doesn't understand the concepts himself. Least caring and empathetic towards students, and an unnecessarily irritating grader with ambiguous standards. Also, not a "professor".
Mid term and Finals were especially brutal. The homework will take a good portion of time.
He cares about the work and assigns readings that give you multiple perspective on complex issues. You'll learn a lot; he's invested in improving your writing.

Prof Manning was a little tough at the beginning of the class, but provided great feedback which helped me progress throughout the course. Group project heavy, but I lucked out with good teammates (and the groups were switched for each project).I liked how current topics were discussed which made the course feel applicable to work outside of class.
Professor Zhao is truly a gem. She has helped me significantly throughout my first year of learning Chinese. She is a phenomenal professor and she is passionate about helping students succeed.
She was the sweetest. She provided the material so no spending money on books. Super helpful. Resourceful. Amazing 10/10

I had Prof. Iyengar for calc II. I actually really enjoyed the class, despite fear of it being a "weeder" course. The homework and exams were very reasonable, and the lectures were quite engaging. He is super knowledgeable about math, and clearly describes nuances of complex topics. Great prof, would recommend to anyone.

Dr. Papadakis made me excited to learn. I liked her so much as a professor, that I decided to switch her to my major advisor. Psychopathology is interesting, engaging, and just the right amount of work so that studying for exams isn't hard because you've already learned the material. Overall, great class.

Amazing professor that teaches students not only about the Spanish language, but also about the many intricacies within lots of different Spanish-speaking (and non-spanish-speaking) cultures and histories. There's homework due each class, but it's almost always very light and supplements the in-class learning perfectly. This class is for anyone!

Overall workload is slightly above medium, depends on your background. Professor and TA are both super responsive and provide helpful feedback to ensure you are following the material. Assignments are difficult but always allow second attempts, reasonable grading. I like how he brought up brilliant research topics along the classes, great bonus!

I've taken two of Harry's classes, this and Cancer Biology. Typically there are two exams, a group paper analysis, and one presentation. Lectures aren't mandatory and he was a great source of support during my degree. There's a lot of material, but the exams are open book, so not difficult to do well.
Nice class
Learned something new
Very helpful and tries to be as clear as possible, but class is very hard. Exams and homeworks are fair and very useful in understanding the material.

Adler expects a lot, but he makes it a priority to get to know all of his students so he is more understanding. Make sure to read his instructions. He grades fairly. I would take another class taught by him.
Alex Norris is an incredible professor and musician. If you play and instrument, take this class. You will become a better musician from speaking with him.

I had Manuel for Conversational Spanish and he made the class very fun. I learned a lot and we had a great atmosphere. He made sure everyone learned. He's still my favorite spanish professor, and he runs JHU in Madrid. He's a funny guy and all the girls thought he was hot. He dresses kinda like a European Mr. Rogers.

The most stuck up and disorganized teacher I have ever had in my entire life. I am righting this 19 days after my final and I still haven't gotten my final grade. This course was flat out disorganized, the teacher was never available on the dot when help was needed and he shouted back at us when we requested things, like where are we taking exams.
rating_tags: Skip class? You won't pass.--LOTS OF HOMEWORK--LECTURE HEAVY

comment: Best instructor I've had in this program. Really responsive, even late at night and weekends. Answers questions clearly.
rating_tags: Gives good feedback--LOTS OF HOMEWORK--ACCESSIBLE OUTSIDE CLASS

comment: No Comments
The professor is very unprofessional, bring personal feelings to class, intolerate and disrespectful to its students. She is very rude treating students and avoid at all costs
terrific experience and knowledge, terrific sense of humor and ability to relate with graduate students.

Provided more feedback than any other instructor I have had, and the feedback given was useful for making improvements. Video lessons were provided, as this class was not a typical online "read this book, and do this assignment" style. I was better able to retain information than I had in previous courses.

Dr. Shilliam is a true gem! Not only are his classes inspirational and a transformative learning experience but he is also highly cognizant of students' feedback, expectations from him and the course, and how to help each person individually. Also one of the most perceptive and intelligent instructors that I have ever had! So happy I took him

His lectures were designed to be death by PowerPoint, regurgitation of the textbook. If you couldn't understand the textbook, good luck getting clarification on the subject from watching his lectures. His class was all tests, no homework. Other than a practice midterm & final, he didn't provide supplementary practice materials to his students.
good

I just completed my first year of Chinese and it has been an incredible experience thanks to Professor Yang. Professor Yang is motivating and inspiring. I could not ask for a better professor and I am so thankful to have had her to guide me through First Year Chinese I and II.
lots of office hours!
rating_tags: Gives good feedback--Accessible outside class--Group projects

comment: Dr. Shelby is an amazing professor. His lectures are clear and thorough. He genuinely cares for his students and takes from his personal time during weekends to support them. The grading is fair, and the discussions are very insightful. I would recommend taking a class with Dr. Shelby any day. He is a wonderful, wonderful person.

Dr. Leaf is a phenomenal professor. This past semester I took "Lectures on Public Health and Wellbeing in Baltimore," and I thoroughly enjoyed his class. Each week, he would invite different speakers that worked in Baltimore to describe their work and the impact it had on the community. This is a great class and I would definitely recommend it!
Very nice professor. Lectures were a tad dry tho. History of Biology was a very chill, informative class. Only difficult assignment was a 10 page final paper. Just do the work, and you will be fine.
rating_tags: Get ready to read--Clear grading criteria--EXTRA CREDIT

comment: Laurel's amazing, probably my favorite prof here. Her teaching style is lecture-heavy, but they're engaging, effective, & discussion is integrated. She clearly cares about students/their learning beyond class content (broadly useful critical thinking, writing, etc skills). 10/10 teacher & person; loves bones; singlehandedly got me into archaeology.

Really kind person and very intelligent and thoughtful with feedback. Relatively easy class as long as you participate and finish assignments. Felt like I left every class feeling inspired to write and get more serious about my writing. Liked her enough to take another course with her.

Dr. Panchal is caring and knowledgeable. It is by no means an "easy A." You will do best in the class if you have basic lab skills and lab math (like dilutions etc). She is soft spoken and talks a bit in circles but if you pay attention and show you want to learn there is a lot to get out of the course.

I took her for Cell Culture Techniques and I thoroughly enjoyed having her as my professor! She made learning protocols in lab exciting and she was always approachable when it comes to questions and feedback. If anyone is looking for a lab course where you get to perform hands-on techniques and gradually excel in them, please take her! Love her.

I was not a huge fan of his teaching style. He often reads directly from the slides and he posts the slides afterwards (thus not a lot of ppl attend his lectures). Pacing is off sometimes and doesnt give clear answers when you ask questions. Difficult content (even the homeworks), but the TA Sections are extremely helpful and clears everything up.

A white savior teaching public health: She shows class Facebook photos of Bangladeshi villagers (w/o their permission), mocking them about their food habits/ lack of knowledge in acquiring nipah virus. Meanwhile, she works in Bangladesh for nipah! Focuses on irrelevant material for exams which you had to memorize 100 disease characteristics for.

He was an extremely tough grader, for example if your codeblock is over 20 lines or if it has comments, automatic zero.Class was extremely unorganized, TA's don't show up to office hours or help.And the professor is unhelpful and slightly rude on discussion boards.Hard to understand his lectures(slight accent).Posts old lectures from years ago only
Chris is a great instructor! I learned so much from him. He is practically Italian!! Definitely take his class.
He scheduled amazing intimate convos with people who helped shape the city. He really cared about making sure everyone understood, and broke down complex topics so you can understand.

This guy is a horrible teacher, just wants his students thinking like he does, not much open for discussion. I enjoyed the readings, but lectures were long and rambling without ever reaching a point. Responses to questions were the same. I was really excited for this class, especially because of my German heritage, but it was a huge disappointment.
Fairly straightforward class, 50% of test is straight off the HW and the other 50% is from lecture. You never need to even buy the textbook.

Autumn is a great professor. She's a fantastic French-speaker and very helpful with any questions you have. She's a pretty easy grader and is very encouraging and friendly. Very willing to help you do well. Sweet and funny person. Great style, too!

I believe the professor was not typical of profs at Hopkins. In my opinion he was  unenthusiastic, not knowledgeable and showed no interest in teaching. He was disorganized and did not communicate well. I believe he gave the bare minimum. He was negative and lacking in academic qualifications to teach at MA level - no phd. He always seemed angry.
Not really any good.
rating_tags: SO MANY PAPERS--GRADED BY FEW THINGS

comment: Really tough class

Professor Yao teaches a very fun on class on Advanced Readings in Chinese. The class pace is easy going but very engaging; student participation in discussions are strongly encouraged. Questions are met with thorough answers. The level of intellect and knowledge Professor Yao had exhibited is the best I've seen from a professor in a long time.

She's a very sweet person and she's very skilled at teaching. Her grading is extremely easy but I didn't find that this detracted from the teaching. She was very creative in how she presented information. There were lots of games and activities and you could tell she had a passion for teaching Arabic. She has even studied linguistics.

Gives great lectures. If anything he could be faulted for going too in-depth on certain topics, but it prepares you for later classes. Very good at explaining memory usage which is an important topic to know from this class. Also has clearest grading criteria I've ever seen. Every assignment comes with a point-by-point rubric.

He is really smart and funny and lectures much better than the older professor. I don't know why he didn't teach more since his notes made the material more accessible than the primary readings. For our sections, he assigned 25+ pages of homework each night. I had time to read but it was definitely hard.
rating_tags: ACCESSIBLE OUTSIDE CLASS--SO MANY PAPERS--Amazing lectures

comment: One of the best profs Ive had here. I loved his class!

She's an amazing instructor. I think she's still a graduate student but she does teach other courses specific to her dissertation as well. She is an inspirational and caring instructor, and is an amazing person. I would give anything to be in her class again. Take her section if you can. She's awesome.
Professor Childers is the best teacher I have ever had! He really knows a lot--everyone should meet Prof Childers!

Very mean. Teaches nothing. Gives no specific instructions before students' presentations but does criticize a lot after. Has an extra pre than others professors. Does not extend the deadline of essay while half class is taking CFA exam though other professors do. Have extra work( weekly post) than others.
rating_tags: Tough Grader--Skip class? You won't pass.--LOTS OF HOMEWORK

comment: At times, Professor Lee can be kind of dry, but she is great at leading discussions and providing specific feedback. She makes time to sit down and work with every student outside of class and also works to accommodate students to the best of her ability.

Professor Gu is one of the best math professors at Hopkins (it's a shame that he's leaving us). He is kind, funny, loves class participation, and is always willing to answer questions. He gives lots of opportunities for extra credit, and really wants us all to succeed. He mostly uses slides for his presentations, which actually worked well.
Easy grader, lectures werent too helpful, but his office hours really help
rating_tags: Lots of homework--Get ready to read--Participation matters

comment: Professor Koehn is a really cool guy but the way he explains ideas as a professor is only alright. He is really lenient on the grading. He is not a particularly engaging teacher with the way he speaks and some people get the feeling he does not care all that much about the class itself. He definitely knows his stuff and minimum effort is still ok.

Christian Priday is the best I ever had. By no means is he easy. He is very very hard, but he is sooooo worth it. It is very obvious that he works out but he has high standards and is very sharp minded and teaches with clarity. I highly recommend taking Bus Driving 101 from him!!
He was such a nice professor very sweet, really helps with questions about text and open to discuss about it

Dr. Najmi's lectures are easy to understand. He gives feedback within a day at most when emailed with questions. Office hours are held via Zoom and are recorded, so you may go back a review at any time. This course definitely required the textbook as the lectures follow the book very closely. No exams or projects!
rating_tags: Gives good feedback--Get ready to read--Amazing lectures

comment: Don't get me wrong. OS is a heavy course, but this is also one of the most useful and interesting courses I took at JHU. I appreciate how the professor and TA put lots of thought into preparing course materials. After one semester's training, you can see how much your system engineering skills improved. I also like those starwar jokes in the exam

He is so fun and so enthusiastic about what he teaches, it makes lectures go by quickly. He moves fast through the material but makes sure you understand the concepts by repeating them. One of my favorite professors since I got to Hopkins.

The class is an easy A if you do everything. Youll learn some stuff but all interactions are only via email so the tuition for this class is way too high imo. You wont learn Stats in much depth but if you already know the concepts its a good brush up.
Truly amazing professor. Love him. Very nice. Got a brick for my syllabus. I fall asleep with it now. Prof Grimmer is great

Is sometimes difficult to understand in lectures and hard to hear. But, all of the homework and exam questions are from posted lecture slides so if you study that you will be fine. Curves to a B+ which I think is pretty reasonable. The content isn't hard, its just a matter of whether you understand/have memorized it.

Professor Savkli is a great professor. Very knowledgeable in the courses he teaches, and is very easy to access out of class. If you follow the class material and are truly engaging with it, you should have no problem with his courses. If you are still struggling, email him, he has almost always responded within an hour. Very helpful.

Dr. Lawrence genuinely cares about her students learning, not just their grades. Class consisted of three short papers, a midterm, and a final. She focuses more on making sure you actually understand the topics, so the midterm and final were open notes and if you completed the final you automatically got a 100. A bit heavy on the readings.
rating_tags: Get ready to read--Clear grading criteria

comment: I loved her IFP I class. I am a STEM major but her class was by far my favorite. She is very understanding and cares about her students due to the small class size. I learned a lot and recommend her class for everyone!

Geetha is passionate and caring. The outline and curriculum for the course aren't the best, but that's not entirely up to her. She works hard to build relationships and opportunities for collaboration between classmates.

Dr. Wright is very passionate about her class and caring for her students. Her class allowed me to explore topics that I had never been exposed to. She gave great feedback and was very reasonable with her assignments.

This professor cotaught with three others. Between the three, they seemed to put forth about a quarter of the effort required to actually teach a course. Lecture materials were recycled, out of focus, missing sound, and often not there altogether. Readings were thrown at the wall, sometimes 5 pages sometimes 200. Course was a disgrace.

This is the worst professor. Her expectations for assignments vague and she doesn't use rubrics. Her test questions are unclear. She does not explain why she has taken points off. She only cares about cheating. She takes over two weeks to respond to emails. When I had covid I asked for a 24 hour extension she literally never responded to me.

Very nice and intelligent professor. Class is only frustrating because of the lead professor, Dr. Hendry. Kuchibhotla is new to the course and only taught a few lectures but seems like a good professor overall. Ask questions in office hours because there is little information on his slides.
rating_tags: Lecture heavy--Test heavy--Graded by few things

comment: There is no way to actually learn from Yuchin. I was completely unable to follow her in lecture and by the end of the semester, less than 1/4 of the class actually showed up. Youtube taught me instead.

Class is mostly online and underwhelming. He has a very busy and involved job outside of teaching and it shows. He is a smart man and familiar with his field. There was a in person lab which was very enlightening. I wouldn't go out of my way to take him again, but I wouldn't avoid him.
This professor makes sure to be mindful of student's heavy schedules, and facilitates problem sets with hints on the discussion boards.  The material is tough, but he makes it manageable.

Class is not mandatory nor necessary to attend since the content on the homework and quizzes is more difficult than what's covered in class and the lecture slides are posted on Canvas. However, she's easily approachable in office hours and the practice quizzes are super reflective of what's on the actual quizzes, so this is not a super hard course.

She's pretty good to have quizzes really easy if you study the practice quizzes. Attendance not really mandatory if you need extra help do attend but if you're pretty good with math there's no need to go. Definitely attend section tho.

I was very nervous to take the advanced econometrics requirement in the MS in Applied Econ program, but Argyn was a great surprise! He broke down the coding and econometrics concepts step-by-step, and has great knowledge of the subjects. Would highly recommend!
rating_tags: Group projects--Clear grading criteria--Accessible outside class

comment: Barely any curve in this class.  Grading's fair.  Trush is a great guy.

This is for Human Development 861.605. If you follow the guidelines for each assignment (primarily 3 papers) to the letter, you will be okay. This prof allows you to submit papers early for feedback which is extremely helpful. A few online assessments, class participation, and three papers. No tests! Class is better when students participate.

I had her for Making America: Mastery and Freedom in British Mainland America.  She was easily one of the most approachable and nice professors I've ever had.  She gave a lot of readings, but she was a very good lecturer.  She didn't even need a powerpoint for her lectures to be clear and concise.  Recommended if you don't mind reading and writing.

This guy curves to a C or C-. Don't take his class. Got 20 points above average and got a B. That makes no sense. Planning on making a complaint. Do a ton of practice problems and you'll do well. Most students can't understand his english, so most did not come to class or dropped his class for the engineering one, which was the best idea to do.

Disorganized, hard to understand, terrible notes, repetitive labs and absolutely no pedagogy.  This man does not want to teach and it shows in his terrible teaching.  Possibly the worst class of my career in terms of learning.  Got an A.

John is a great professor. You can tell he really, really loves math, and he wants you to, too. He's extremely helpful and will work with you on homework, journals, whatever to make sure you understand the material. Patient and encouraging.  The class is almost purely group-work with proofs. Fairly easy grader. No tests.

Marieke is a really nice person and professor. She is interested in her students' well-beings on all levels. She seems to be knowledgeable about anthropology and values students' insights and opinions. However, she cancelled a lot of class. Very few lectures and was sometimes disorganized. Fairly easy grader.
Has great perspectives on life, universe, and everything be sure to ask questions either in or out of class if you want to make the most of your time studying under this man.

Awesome guy in general. No midterms - only a weekly quiz and one final. Super-easy to do well in his class. No need for textbook reading, either - he has his own extensive notes available. Not to mention the awesome computer labs we do. No more is biochemistry the domain of PacMan eating a carrot.

Overall, Professor Morgan was a pretty good professor. She was adept in facilitating conversation and in lecturing. Her grading fell somewhere between fair and harsh. The class was reading and writing intensive, though the professors did work to decrease the amount of writing between last year and this year. Overall positive experience
rating_tags: Get ready to read--Participation matters--SO MANY PAPERS

comment: She's a really nice and helpful teacher who actually cares about how you do in the class. You're lucky if you get her as your teacher
Politics of South Asia was literally the best class I have ever taken.  A lot of reading but so interesting.  Absolutely fantastic, amazing teacher.
he is a wild guy but his class is entertaining and even though it is long it really helps you become a better cinematographer
Im a terrible writer, but Robert is awesome at seeing what you do well and helping you fix what you need to work on. I recommend this class to everyone!

Ferrario is a great professor with a true, genuine passion for Islamic Studies. It is easy to access him outside of class to talk about a past lecture or upcoming assignment and his lectures coincide with the reading notes which makes it easy to catch-up if you miss a lecture (but watch our for the class participation grade)! 10/10 reccommend
rating_tags: Gives good feedback--Get ready to read--Amazing lectures

comment: This class is primarily based and graded on a video game the professor created. This type of learning doesn't work for everyone and for those of us that struggled with the technology side of the game, there was no sympathy or clear guidance from the professor. Very cold and difficult to approach professor. Don't expect any kindness or help.

I'm so grateful for Prof Rajaram, I was intimidated heading into intro to fluid mechanics and he made it approachable without oversimplifying the material. He puts in the effort to make sure his lectures are helpful and informative and he provides helpful summaries and notes to reinforce his lectures.

Very passionate about the subject, has many papers published in this area which is very hard to understand for an undergrad student, but, the lectures make it easy to get a hang of topics discussed in class. Very kind and funny. Fantastic prof!

Professor Papageorge is quite possibly my favorite economics professor to date. His class features a disparate set of heavyweight behavioral economics concepts designed to make you think and participate lest your pristine GPA gets thwacked. He isn't afraid to approach difficult (in all senses of the word)topics. A true believer of healthy discourse
Doesn't care about students, and super arrogant in a really toxic way. Would not recommend dealing with this professor.

The professor is very nice and gives good feedback on papers. There are only 2 papers in the entire semester in which your grade is based on. If you aren't some star writer, this course will be hard. She is good at teaching, but her grading criteria is not clear either. I wouldn't take her again for the fact that I like my GPA.
rating_tags: Gives good feedback--Get ready to read--Graded by few things

comment: For an ISET course, it's rather lackluster. No 3D model building or VR for example. The final project is the only thing worth boasting about and that proved to be less valuable. As for Sack himself, I think Krieger should consider placing people where they're needed. I think he does VR/AR work, but he didn't fulfill the class description.
rating_tags: Accessible outside class--Participation matters--Graded by few things

comment: Dr. Ziad is a gem of a human being. She is kind, caring, and open to discussion of all worldly issues. She opened up to students in her class, showing her empathy and lack of hesitation to become familiar with the students. An amazing person, professor, and friend. Highly recommend her class for anyone interested in Islam. Lots of reading!
rating_tags: Gives good feedback--Get ready to read--Participation matters

comment: Tim is a sweet guy but his teaching was very ineffective. The concepts covered in lecture were unnecessarily abstract and he taught them in a very convoluted and roundabout manner, so I ended up not going to lectures for the last month of the semester and teaching myself. Quizzes, portfolios, HW, and group projects were very easy overall though.

rating_tags: Participation matters--Graded by few things--Lecture heavy

comment: Very intelligent, but one of the worst lecturers I've ever experienced. Notice that I didn't say worst professor. Basu is not a bad professor by any means, he really tries and constantly makes himself available. He's very passionate. However, he moves incredibly quickly, almost never fills in the gaps nor tells you why certain topics are relevant.

Professor Lubberts is extremely smart and quite nice but is somehow lacking teaching experience. This class is overwhelmingly difficult if you do not have a solid understanding of linear algebra, and the materials covered are very theoretical. Be prepared to spend a large amount of time doing proof problems.
This professor's grading of each student was available for the whole class to see for half the semester. Additionally, some of her feedback was a little tough.
rating_tags: Participation matters--Graded by few things--Tough grader

comment: I loved taking the story of earth with Professor Sverjensky. I never would have thought that I would be interested in Earth Sciences, but I ended up learning so many cool things in his class! I also enjoyed having classes outside before the winter. Read from the book, write engaging reflections, and participate in class and you'll earn an A!
Crazy amounts of homework required. Difficult exams.
rating_tags: Lots of homework--Get ready to read--Tough grader

comment: Dr. Belienson is an amazing professor. I took Public Health Policy with him. He brought it all kinds of different lecturers from Baltimore and made the class very relevant and interesting. Super nice and humble guy, but also very decorated. My favorite class at Hopkins.

Very lecture oriented class, which is just based on the textbook. Homework is just lists of textbook problems. Exams and quizzes are all handwritten and zero practice tests are given, just chapters of textbook they will be on. Final is 40% of grade. Weekly quizzes are 2 questions and you get 10 minutes, basically fail them if you make an errors.

Dr. Humphries clearly knows this material on a deep level and does a really nice job of participating in the canvas discussions. Homework and canvas discussion heavy but homework is not too bad. Only complaint is grading stopped halfway through the semester, but syllabus was clear what would get you a good grade. Great class; would take again
rating_tags: Participation matters--Gives good feedback--Accessible outside class

comment: There are many guest speakers and experts who join for live sync sessions and share about their expertise and experiences. The class also provides a fair enough of reading, and a lot of additional / optional reading.

I took Foundations of Materials Science and Engineering with Professor Erlebacher. As a foundations class, it wasn't meant to be very difficult. I talked to him a lot after classes. He was very friendly. I am slightly biased, however, because his daughter, who was also taking his class, became a close friend of mine not very far into the semester.
His lectures can be a bit boring at times, but he is a good professor. He is a well of knowledge and a great person to get to know.
rating_tags: Group projects--Clear grading criteria--So many papers

comment: Dr. Wicks is super nice and loves what she teaches. Her first year seminar was fun and easy (light readings and no previous background needed). If you come to class, you will pass (it's pass/fail). She made the class fun with cool lectures, guest speakers, a movie day, a field trip, etc. I really enjoyed her course.

I loved this class and her teaching. I was scared at first since the class is graded only on 3 exams, however the exams are extremely fair and she gives extra credit assignments if you need it. The content is really interesting and the logic of reasoning is clear. She is so funny and genuinely cares for her students!
Dr. Wellman is very kind, motivating, and responsive to questions. The entire class is projects and writing, each of which took me many hours, but it never felt like busywork and I learned a lot.
rating_tags: Clear grading criteria--Gives good feedback--Lots of homework

comment: He;s like so bad at teaching and also unforgiving for unnecessary things

The exams were poorly designed with vague wording, leading to a median of only 60% and no curve. 

The instructor's teaching was ineffective, and we were forced to use jMonkey, an engine unsuitable for practical game development, causing unnecessary difficulties. 

Grading was very strange, arbitrary and unclear. Avoid at all costs.
